INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ak_getting-your-alaska-instruction-permit', 'module_ak_overlay', 'getting-your-alaska-instruction-permit', 'Getting Your Alaska Instruction Permit', '# Getting Your Alaska Instruction Permit

Alaska''s path to a driver license starts with the **Instruction Permit**, which you can apply for as early as **age 14**. Alaska is one of the few states that allows permit applications this young, but the trade-off is that you must hold the permit for at least **six months** and be at least **16 years old** before you can move up to a provisional license.

## Who Issues the Permit

The **Alaska Division of Motor Vehicles (DMV)**, part of the Department of Administration, issues all driver credentials. You apply in person at a DMV field office. Many rural communities are served by **DMV Business Partners** — commissioned agents who can process applications where there is no full DMV office.

## What to Bring

When you visit the DMV, plan to bring:

1. **Proof of identity** — a certified birth certificate or U.S. passport.
2. **Proof of Social Security Number** — your SSN card, a W-2, or a pay stub showing the full SSN.
3. **Proof of Alaska residency** — typically two documents such as a utility bill, school enrollment letter, or parent''s lease.
4. **Parent or guardian consent** — because you are under 18, a parent or legal guardian must sign the application in person, or provide a notarized consent form.
5. **Fees** — bring the current application fee (check ak.gov/dmv for the exact amount, as fees change).

## The Knowledge and Vision Tests

To earn the permit you must:

- Pass a **vision screening** (corrective lenses are fine; a restriction will be added to your license if you need them).
- Pass a **knowledge test** covering Alaska traffic laws, road signs, and safe driving practices. The test is based on the **Alaska Driver Manual**, which is free online.

Most field offices let you take the knowledge test on a touch-screen kiosk. If you fail, you typically must wait until the next business day to retake it.

## What the Permit Lets You Do

Once issued, your instruction permit allows you to drive **only when supervised** by a licensed driver who is **at least 21 years old** and seated in the front passenger seat. The supervising driver must be sober and able to take control if needed.

While holding the permit you must log at least **40 hours of supervised driving practice**, including driving in a range of conditions. Alaska strongly recommends practicing in winter weather, on gravel roads, and at night — the conditions you will actually face once licensed.

## Moving On

After holding the permit for at least six months with no major traffic violations, and once you turn 16, you can return to the DMV with your completed practice log and a parent''s signature to take the **road skills test**. Passing it earns you a **provisional license** — which is when Alaska''s GDL restrictions kick in.

## Common Pitfalls

- **Lapsed permits.** The permit is valid for two years; if it expires before you test, you start over.
- **Citations restart the clock.** A serious traffic conviction during the permit period can reset your six-month waiting period.
- **Incomplete practice logs.** The DMV may ask to see your log; falsifying it is a serious violation of the parental-consent agreement.

Treat the permit period as the most valuable training time you will ever get behind the wheel. Use it deliberately.', 35, 0
);
