INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ak_alaska-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ak_overlay', 'alaska-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living With Alaska''s GDL Restrictions', '# Living With Alaska''s GDL Restrictions

Passing the road test earns you a **provisional license**, but it is not the same as an unrestricted adult license. Alaska''s **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** system imposes two main restrictions for the first six months after you turn 16, plus general rules that apply until you reach 18.

## The Nighttime Restriction

Provisional license holders **may not drive between 1:00 a.m. and 5:00 a.m.** There are limited exceptions:

- You are accompanied by a licensed driver who is at least **21 years old** in the front passenger seat.
- You are driving **to or from work**, and can provide proof such as a pay stub or employer letter if asked.
- You are driving **to or from a school activity** sanctioned by your school district.
- You are responding to an **emergency**.

This matters a lot more in Alaska than in many states because of how dramatically daylight changes by season. In December an Anchorage teen may see the sun set before 4 p.m.; in June the sun barely sets at all. The 1–5 a.m. rule applies regardless of how light it is outside.

## The Passenger Restriction

For the first **six months** of holding a provisional license, you may not carry passengers **under 21 years old** unless:

- They are **immediate family members** (siblings, step-siblings, etc.), or
- A licensed driver at least **21 years old** is in the front passenger seat.

This restriction targets the highest-risk situation for new teen drivers: a car full of friends. National crash data shows the per-mile fatal crash rate for 16- and 17-year-olds doubles with one teen passenger and roughly quadruples with three or more.

## Practical Implications

- **Carpools.** You cannot legally pick up three friends to go to a basketball game during your first six months of licensure. Plan rides with a parent driving, or wait out the restriction.
- **Late shifts.** If you work past 1 a.m., keep a recent pay stub or schedule in the car as proof you are commuting from work.
- **School events.** A signed activity slip from a coach or advisor goes a long way if you are pulled over after a late game.

## Cell Phones and Distracted Driving

Alaska law prohibits **texting while driving** for all drivers. It is also illegal to operate a vehicle with a **screen displaying video** visible to the driver. While Alaska does not have a universal statewide handheld ban for adults, **local ordinances** — most notably Anchorage''s — prohibit handheld phone use while driving. For provisional license holders, the safest rule is simple: **phone in the glovebox, notifications off**.

## Seat Belts and Passengers

Alaska is a **primary enforcement** seat belt state, meaning an officer can stop you solely for an unbelted occupant. As the driver, you are responsible for ensuring all passengers under 16 are properly restrained. Children under age 8 and under 65 pounds and 57 inches must be in an approved child safety seat or booster.

## Violations Reset the Clock

A conviction for a moving violation during your first six months of provisional licensure can **extend your restrictions** by another six months from the date of conviction. Two convictions can trigger license suspension. Treat your provisional period as probation: every clean month is a month closer to full driving privileges.

## When the Restrictions Lift

The nighttime and passenger restrictions end six months after the provisional license is issued, provided you have a clean record. At 18, the provisional designation drops off entirely and you hold a standard Alaska driver license.', 30, 1
);
