INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_al_getting-your-alabama-learner-license', 'module_al_overlay', 'getting-your-alabama-learner-license', 'Getting Your Alabama Learner License', '# Getting Your Alabama Learner License

Alabama issues driver credentials through the **Alabama Law Enforcement Agency (ALEA) Driver License Division**. For teens, the journey starts with the **Learner License** (often called a learner permit), which is Stage I of Alabama''s Graduated Driver License (GDL) program.

## When you can apply

You can apply for an Alabama Learner License the day you turn **15 years old**. There is no minimum waiting period after your birthday - bring the right documents and you can test the same day at most ALEA examining offices.

## What you need to bring

ALEA requires applicants to prove four things: who you are, that you have a Social Security number, that you live in Alabama, and (if you are under 19) that you are enrolled in school or have graduated. Plan to bring:

- **Proof of identity** - certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or other ALEA-accepted primary document
- **Proof of Social Security number** - your Social Security card, a W-2, or a pay stub showing the full SSN
- **Two documents proving Alabama residency** - typically a utility bill, lease, or official mail addressed to your parent at your home address (parent''s documents can be used for minors)
- **School enrollment/exclusion form (Form DL-1/93)** signed by your school, OR proof of graduation/GED if you are under 19
- **Parent or legal guardian** in person to sign the application - Alabama requires a parent or guardian to assume financial responsibility for any minor driver
- **Application fee** - currently around $5 for the learner license; bring a card or cash

## The tests

At the office you will take three tests for the learner license:

1. **Vision screening** - basic acuity check; bring your glasses or contacts if you wear them
2. **Road sign identification** - you must recognize standard regulatory, warning, and guide signs by shape, color, and meaning
3. **Written knowledge test** - 30 multiple-choice questions drawn from the Alabama Driver Manual covering traffic laws, safe-driving practices, and DUI rules. You must score **80% or higher** to pass

Study the current edition of the Alabama Driver Manual (free PDF on the ALEA website) before you go. Most teens who fail the first attempt skipped the manual and relied only on practice apps.

## After you pass

The office prints a paper interim license valid for 60 days; your permanent card arrives by mail. While holding the learner license you may only drive when accompanied by a **licensed driver age 21 or older** (or a licensed parent, guardian, spouse, or driver education instructor) seated beside you in the front seat.

## The six-month clock

Your learner license must be held for at least **six consecutive months** with a clean record before you can move to the Stage I Restricted License at age 16. A traffic conviction or at-fault crash can reset the clock - drive like every trip counts, because it does.

## Driver education credit

If you complete an ALEA-approved driver education course (like this one), your certificate goes into your file and can reduce your auto-insurance premium under Alabama''s good-student and driver-ed discounts. It also gives you structured behind-the-wheel hours that count toward the recommended **50 hours of supervised practice** before licensure.', 35, 0
);
