INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_al_alabama-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_al_overlay', 'alabama-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Alabama GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Alabama GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Once you turn 16 and meet the six-month learner requirement, you can apply for the **Stage I Restricted License**. It looks just like a regular license, but it carries three restrictions until you turn 17 (with a clean six-month Stage I record) or 18. Knowing the exact rules - and the exceptions - keeps you out of trouble and on the road.

## The midnight-to-6 a.m. rule

A Stage I driver **may not operate a vehicle between midnight and 6:00 a.m.** That covers the highest-risk crash window for new drivers. Exceptions include:

- Driving accompanied by a parent, legal guardian, or licensed driver 21+
- Driving to or from work (carry a recent pay stub or letter from your employer)
- Driving to or from a school-sanctioned event
- Driving to or from a religious-organization event
- Driving for a medical emergency or to a hunting/fishing event with a valid license

"My friend''s house" and "a party" are **not** exceptions. If you are pulled over at 1 a.m. coming back from a movie, expect a ticket and a possible delay in earning your Stage II license.

## The passenger limit

A Stage I driver **may not carry more than one non-family passenger under age 21**. The intent is simple: research consistently shows that crash risk for teens multiplies sharply with each additional teen passenger. Family members (siblings, cousins living in the home, etc.) do not count toward the limit, and the rule is waived when a parent, guardian, or licensed driver 21+ is in the car.

Practical examples:

- You + one friend: legal
- You + two friends: not legal
- You + your 14-year-old sister + one friend: legal (sister is family)
- You + four teammates after practice: not legal unless a coach 21+ is riding along

## The phone rule

Alabama bans **all use of handheld communication devices** by drivers under 18 holding a restricted license. That means no calls, no texts, no scrolling - even at a red light. Mounted, hands-free GPS navigation is allowed, but anything that requires you to hold or type on the device is off-limits.

Alabama law **also bans texting for every driver in the state**, regardless of age, and starting in recent years police can stop you for texting alone (primary enforcement). A texting ticket adds points to your license and triggers an automatic insurance surcharge.

## Seat belts - not just a rule, a save

Alabama requires every front-seat occupant and every passenger under 15 in any seat to wear a seat belt. As the driver you are responsible for every minor in your vehicle. A first offense is a $25 primary-enforcement ticket, and unbelted teens are roughly twice as likely to die in a crash.

## What happens if you break a restriction

Violating a GDL restriction is a moving violation in Alabama. Beyond the fine, the conviction:

- Resets your six-month clean-record clock for advancement to Stage II
- Adds points to your license (Alabama uses a 12-points-in-2-years suspension threshold)
- Notifies your parents through the address on file
- Will likely raise your family''s insurance premium for three years

## Planning around the rules

Make a habit of checking the clock before you leave anywhere after 9 p.m., counting the people in your car before you put it in drive, and dropping your phone in the glove box or a Do-Not-Disturb dock before you turn the key. Treat the restrictions as the floor, not the ceiling, of safe behavior.', 30, 1
);
