INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_al_alabama-rules-and-quirks', 'module_al_overlay', 'alabama-rules-and-quirks', 'Alabama-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Alabama-Specific Rules and Quirks

Every state has its own personality on the road. Knowing Alabama''s quirks - both the laws written into the code and the practical realities of driving from the Tennessee Valley to the Gulf Coast - will keep you safer and ticket-free.

## Move Over Law

Alabama''s Move Over Law is one of the most enforced traffic statutes in the state. On any road of two or more lanes in the same direction, you must move one lane away from a stopped **emergency, law-enforcement, utility, wrecker, or sanitation vehicle** with flashing lights. If you cannot move over safely, you must slow to **at least 15 mph below the posted speed limit** (and to 25 mph if the limit is 25 or less). State troopers actively patrol I-65, I-20, I-10, and I-59 watching specifically for Move Over violations. The fine starts around $100 plus court costs and goes up sharply for repeat offenses.

## Open container - and the Sunday quirk

Alabama prohibits open containers of alcohol in the passenger compartment of any vehicle on a public highway. Unlike many states, Alabama leaves alcohol sales rules largely to counties and cities, so you will drive through **dry counties** (no alcohol sales at all), **wet counties**, and counties with patchwork Sunday rules. The driving rule is constant: no open containers, no consuming alcohol behind the wheel, ever. For a driver under 21 the legal blood-alcohol limit is **0.02%** - essentially zero tolerance. One drink can end your driving career before it starts.

## Funeral processions have the right of way

Alabama law gives funeral processions, led by a vehicle with purple-and-white or amber flashing lights, the right of way at intersections. Once the lead car has lawfully entered an intersection, every vehicle in the procession may follow without stopping, even against a red light. Other drivers must yield and may not cut into or through the line. This is a longstanding Southern courtesy that is also codified - cutting through a funeral procession can earn you a ticket and a lot of stink-eye.

## School buses and rural roads

When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and its stop arm extended, **all traffic in both directions** must stop on a two-lane road. On a divided highway with a physical median or barrier, only traffic following the bus must stop. Many Alabama school districts now equip buses with stop-arm cameras that mail citations directly to the registered owner of the offending vehicle - the fine is steep ($150 minimum) and the violation cannot be defended by saying "I didn''t see it."

## Weather you actually need to plan for

Alabama''s weather creates conditions other states'' manuals do not cover well:

- **Severe thunderstorms** can drop visibility to near zero in minutes. If you must pull over, get fully off the roadway (not the shoulder) and turn on hazards.
- **Tornadoes** are a real threat from March through May, especially in the central and northern parts of the state. Never try to outrun one in a car - abandon the vehicle for a low-lying ditch or sturdy shelter.
- **Fog** is common in river valleys (Tennessee, Coosa, Alabama, Tombigbee). Use low beams, not high beams, and stay well behind the car ahead.
- **The rare ice storm** shuts the state down because road crews lack heavy salt fleets. If forecasters say "freezing rain," stay home; bridges and overpasses freeze first.

## Headlights with wipers

Alabama law requires headlights to be on **any time the windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to weather. Daytime running lights do not satisfy this requirement - your tail lights must also be illuminated so drivers behind you can see you in the rain.

## Wildlife on the road

From October through January, deer activity spikes dramatically across Alabama, especially at dawn and dusk. Open-range areas in some rural counties also allow livestock on or near roadways. If an animal appears, **brake straight - never swerve**. Most fatal animal-collision crashes happen when drivers lose control trying to dodge.', 30, 2
);
