INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ar_arkansas-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ar_overlay', 'arkansas-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Arkansas-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Arkansas-Specific Rules and Quirks

Every state has driving rules that are easy to miss because they do not show up in generic study guides. Here are Arkansas-specific rules and customs that will save you a ticket - or a crash.

## Move Over Law

Arkansas''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers to change lanes away from any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, utility vehicle, or highway maintenance vehicle with flashing lights. If changing lanes is not safe, slow down well below the posted limit. Violations are a primary offense and fines escalate sharply if a worker is struck.

## Open Container - Even Empty

It is illegal to have an open alcoholic beverage container in the passenger area of a vehicle on any Arkansas public roadway, even if no one is drinking and even if the container is empty. Stash empties in the trunk. For drivers under 21, **any detectable alcohol** triggers a Zero Tolerance violation and license suspension.

## Implied Consent

By accepting an Arkansas driver license, you give **implied consent** to a breath, blood, or urine test if an officer has reasonable grounds to suspect impaired driving. Refusing triggers an **automatic 6-month license suspension** for a first refusal, separate from any DUI charge.

## Headlights On When Wipers Are On

Arkansas law (the **wipers-on, lights-on rule**) requires headlights any time your windshield wipers are in continuous use due to weather. Daytime running lights do not satisfy this rule - your taillights must be on so drivers behind can see you in rain or fog.

## School Bus Stops

When a school bus is stopped with red lights flashing and stop arm extended, **all traffic in both directions must stop** on a two-lane road. On a divided highway with a physical median, only traffic on the same side must stop. Passing a stopped school bus carries some of the steepest penalties in Arkansas.

## Funeral Processions

Arkansas formally recognizes funeral processions. A lead vehicle typically has flashing hazards and a purple flag; following vehicles also use hazards. **Other drivers must yield** to a marked procession and may not cut through it, even at a green light.

## Weather Hazards

Arkansas weather is dramatic. Expect:

- **Flash flooding** - never drive through standing water. "Turn around, don''t drown" - just 12 inches of moving water can sweep away a small car.
- **Tornadoes** - if a warning is issued while driving, abandon the vehicle and seek the lowest interior shelter. Do not park under overpasses.
- **Ice events** - bridges and overpasses freeze first. Reduce speed dramatically.
- **Deer** - especially active at dawn, dusk, and fall rut (October-November). If a collision is unavoidable, brake firmly and stay in your lane.

## Rural Road Realities

Much of Arkansas is rural. Watch for slow-moving farm equipment (orange triangle = under 25 mph), loose livestock, logging trucks with shifting loads, and unpaved county roads where gravel changes everything about braking.

## Insurance and Financial Responsibility

Arkansas requires minimum liability coverage of **25/50/25** ($25,000 bodily injury per person, $50,000 per accident, $25,000 property damage). The state runs an electronic verification system - lapses can suspend your registration. Always carry your insurance card.

## Real ID

Arkansas issues both standard and Real ID-compliant licenses. To board a domestic flight or enter a federal building using your driver license, you need the gold-star Real ID version. Request it at your first appointment - it requires birth certificate, Social Security card, and two proofs of residency.

Knowing these quirks early makes you the kind of driver Arkansas families, employers, and insurers actually want on the road.', 30, 2
);
