INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_az_how-to-get-an-az-instruction-permit', 'module_az_overlay', 'how-to-get-an-az-instruction-permit', 'How to Get Your Arizona Instruction Permit', '# How to Get Your Arizona Instruction Permit

In Arizona, your first official step toward a driver license is the **Class G Instruction Permit**, issued by the **Arizona Department of Transportation, Motor Vehicle Division (ADOT MVD)**. This permit is what lets you legally practice driving on public roads with a supervising adult. Here is exactly what you need to do, in the order you need to do it.

## Step 1: Confirm you meet the age requirement

You must be **at least 15 years and 6 months old** to apply for an Arizona Instruction Permit. Not 15. Not "almost 15 and a half." The MVD examiner will check your birth date against the calendar on the day you apply, so you cannot test before your half-birthday.

## Step 2: Gather your documents

Arizona is a federally compliant state, which means MVD verifies your identity using documents that satisfy both state and federal rules. You will typically need:

- **Proof of identity** — a certified U.S. birth certificate or a valid U.S. passport.
- **Proof of Social Security Number** — your Social Security card, a W-2, or a paystub showing the full SSN.
- **Two proofs of Arizona residency** — examples include a utility bill, bank statement, school enrollment record, or a parent''s Arizona driver license (if you live at the same address).
- **Parent or legal guardian consent** — because you are under 18, a parent or legal guardian must sign your application in front of the MVD agent or provide a notarized consent form.

If you plan to get a **Travel ID** (Arizona''s REAL ID-compliant credential), you will need the same documents — bring originals, not copies.

## Step 3: Make an appointment

ADOT MVD strongly recommends scheduling an appointment through **AZ MVD Now** (azmvdnow.gov) rather than walking in. Many MVD offices and Authorized Third Party providers handle teen permit testing, and an appointment can save you hours. Some Authorized Third Party offices charge a small fee but offer faster service.

## Step 4: Pass the written knowledge test

The Arizona permit test is a **30-question multiple-choice exam** covering road signs, traffic laws, and safe driving practices. You must answer **at least 24 questions correctly (80%)** to pass. The test is based on the **Arizona Driver License Manual**, which is free to download from azdot.gov. If you have completed an approved teen driver education course, your school may have given you an online "permit test" voucher that lets you take the official knowledge test from home — ask your instructor.

## Step 5: Pass the vision screening

MVD will check your vision on the spot. If you wear glasses or contacts, bring them — a corrective-lenses restriction will be added to your permit if you need them to pass.

## Step 6: Pay the fee and get your permit

The Instruction Permit fee is modest (typically around **$7**, though fees can change). You will receive a paper interim permit immediately; the actual card arrives in the mail within about two weeks.

## Step 7: Start your 6-month clock

The moment your permit is issued, two clocks start:

1. **The 6-month holding period.** You must hold the permit for at least 6 months before you can apply for your Class G graduated license.
2. **The 30 supervised practice hours.** You must log at least 30 hours of supervised driving, **including 10 hours at night**, with a licensed driver 21 or older in the front seat.

Download **Form 40-5122 (Driver License Application and Parental Consent for Minors)** and start logging practice hours right away. A parent or guardian must certify these hours when you apply for your license.

Keep your permit on you any time you drive — driving without it in your possession is a violation, even if you have technically been issued one.', 35, 0
);
