INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_az_az-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_az_overlay', 'az-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living With Arizona''s GDL Restrictions', '# Living With Arizona''s GDL Restrictions

Getting your Class G graduated driver license is exciting, but Arizona''s **Graduated Driver License (GDL)** program comes with real-world rules that shape how you can drive for the first 6 months. Understanding these limits before you start driving solo will keep you out of trouble — and keep your license.

## The two big restrictions, in plain English

For the **first 6 months** after your Class G license is issued (or until you turn 18, whichever comes first), two restrictions apply every single day:

### 1. The nighttime curfew
You may not drive between **midnight (12:00 a.m.) and 5:00 a.m.** This is one of the strictest curfews in the country — most states start their teen curfew at 11 p.m. or even 10 p.m., but Arizona''s window is narrower and later.

There are exceptions: you may drive during curfew hours if you are

- accompanied by a **parent or legal guardian** (not an older sibling, not a friend''s parent),
- traveling **to or from work**,
- traveling **to or from school**, or a school-sanctioned activity,
- traveling **to or from a religious activity**, or
- responding to an **emergency**.

If you get pulled over at 2 a.m. coming home from a friend''s house, "I was just hanging out" is not an exception. Officers can — and do — ask. Pay stubs, school IDs, and a quick text from a parent can all help, but the safest move is simply to plan your night so you are home before midnight.

### 2. The passenger restriction
You may not transport **more than one passenger under age 18** who is not an immediate family member. "Immediate family" generally means siblings, stepsiblings, and your own children. Cousins, friends, classmates, and your boyfriend or girlfriend all count toward the one-passenger limit.

Exception: a parent or legal guardian sitting in the front seat suspends this rule.

This is the rule teens get cited for most often, because it is the easiest to forget. Two friends crammed in the back "for just a quick run to In-N-Out" is still a violation.

## The cell phone rule (applies to everyone, but stricter for you)

Arizona is a **hands-free state for all drivers** — no one of any age may hold or support a phone while driving. For drivers under 18 with a permit or a first-6-months Class G license, the rule is even stricter: **no wireless communication device use at all**, including hands-free, except in an emergency. This means no Bluetooth calls, no voice texting, no streaming controls — phone goes in the glove box or Do Not Disturb mode before you start the car.

## Seat belts and impaired driving

Arizona uses a **Zero Tolerance** standard for drivers under 21: any measurable amount of alcohol (BAC of 0.00 detected) can result in license suspension. Marijuana, even where personally legal, is treated as impaired driving when it affects you behind the wheel. Every occupant under 16 must be properly restrained; the driver is responsible for them.

## What happens when you break a GDL rule

Arizona uses a **points-based corrective action system**. A teen who accumulates **8 or more points in 12 months** must complete Traffic Survival School. Two violations of GDL restrictions during the restriction period can trigger a **30-day license suspension**; a third can trigger a **90-day suspension**. These are administrative consequences on top of any traffic citation.

## A practical 6-month survival kit

- Set a phone alarm for **11:30 p.m.** any night you are out driving.
- Tell your friends about the **one-passenger rule** before they ask for a ride.
- Keep your **work schedule or school activity flyer** in the glove box as proof of an exception.
- Mount your phone but put it in **Driving Focus / Do Not Disturb** before you shift into Drive.

Follow these rules for 6 months and they expire automatically — no extra paperwork needed. Break them and the clock can reset.', 30, 1
);
