INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_az_az-specific-road-rules-and-quirks', 'module_az_overlay', 'az-specific-road-rules-and-quirks', 'Arizona-Specific Road Rules and Desert Driving Quirks', '# Arizona-Specific Road Rules and Desert Driving Quirks

Most of what you learned in driver education applies in every state. But Arizona has a handful of laws and environmental conditions that catch out-of-state drivers — and teen drivers — over and over again. Knowing them will keep you safer and save you from tickets that are easy to avoid.

## The "Stupid Motorist Law"

Arizona''s most famous traffic statute is officially **ARS 28-910**, but everyone calls it the **Stupid Motorist Law**. When seasonal monsoon rains hit (typically June through September), normally dry washes and low-lying roads can fill with fast-moving water in minutes. Authorities post **"Do Not Enter When Flooded"** signs at these crossings, and they will close the road with barricades.

If you **drive around a barricade** into a flooded area and need to be rescued by emergency services, **you can be charged the full cost of the rescue** — often thousands of dollars — on top of a traffic citation. The water is almost always deeper and faster than it looks. The rule is simple: **Turn Around, Don''t Drown.**

## Dust storms ("haboobs") and the Pull Aside, Stay Alive rule

Arizona is one of the few states where giant walls of dust — called **haboobs** — can roll across the freeway and reduce visibility to zero in seconds. ADOT''s official guidance is **"Pull Aside, Stay Alive"**:

1. Look for a safe place to exit the highway if possible.
2. If you cannot exit, **pull completely off the roadway** — as far right as possible.
3. Put the vehicle in **Park**, set the **parking brake**, and **turn off all lights including hazards**. (Lights left on signal to other dust-blinded drivers that you are still on the road, and they may follow your taillights right into you.)
4. Take your foot off the brake.
5. Stay buckled and wait for the dust to pass — usually a few minutes.

This is the opposite of what feels natural, but it is the rule that saves lives.

## Move Over for stopped vehicles

Arizona''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers to move one lane away from any **stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or maintenance vehicle** with flashing lights. If you cannot safely change lanes (because of traffic), you must **slow down significantly** as you pass. This includes police on a shoulder traffic stop. Failing to move over is a primary offense — an officer can pull you over for that alone.

## Right turn on red and U-turns

- **Right on red** is permitted after a complete stop unless a sign prohibits it.
- **Left on red from a one-way street onto another one-way street** is also legal after a complete stop, unless prohibited.
- **U-turns** are generally legal in Arizona unless a sign prohibits them, but **never** make a U-turn at a railroad crossing, on a curve, near the crest of a hill, or where you cannot be seen by approaching traffic from 500 feet.

## School buses and school zones

Arizona has a **15 mph school zone speed limit** when children are present and lights or signs indicate the zone is active. This is one of the lowest speed limits in the country, and it is strictly enforced. When a school bus stops with its **red lights flashing and stop arm extended**, drivers in both directions must stop — except on a divided highway with a physical median, where only drivers behind the bus must stop.

## Insurance and the SR-22

Arizona requires minimum liability insurance of **$25,000/$50,000/$15,000** (bodily injury per person / per accident / property damage). Driving without insurance triggers license and registration suspension and an **SR-22** filing requirement — proof of high-risk insurance that you must carry for up to 3 years. For a teen, this can mean dramatically higher premiums into your 20s.

## Heat is a safety issue

In an Arizona summer, the interior of a car can exceed **160 F** within minutes. Never leave a child, pet, or another person in a parked car. Carry water. Sun on a dashboard can warp phone mounts and make the steering wheel painful to touch — keep a sunshade in the car. If your tires look low, check them in the cool morning, not on hot pavement, and remember that tire pressure rises with heat.

Arizona''s roads are mostly straight and fast, which makes complacency the biggest risk. Respect the desert, respect the monsoon, and respect the signs.', 30, 2
);
