INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ca_how-to-get-a-permit-in-california', 'module_ca_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-california', 'How to Get Your Provisional Instruction Permit in California', '# How to Get Your Provisional Instruction Permit in California

In California, the first formal step on the road to a driver license is the **Provisional Instruction Permit**, issued by the California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV). It is the legal authorization that lets you practice driving with a qualified supervising driver. This lesson walks through exactly what you need, in what order, and how to avoid the most common mistakes that send applicants home empty-handed.

## Who is eligible

You may apply for the provisional instruction permit if you are at least **15 years and 6 months old** but not yet 17 years and 6 months. If you are 17 1/2 or older you can skip driver education and apply directly, but most teens benefit from completing the course earlier so they can begin practicing sooner.

## Step 1: Complete driver education

Before the DMV will issue your permit, you must finish a **California-approved driver education course**. The standard requirement is 30 hours of classroom instruction, which may be taken in person or through an approved online program. At the end of the course your school issues a completion certificate (commonly referred to by its DMV form number) that proves you finished. Keep both digital and printed copies.

You can begin behind-the-wheel training in parallel, but you cannot drive on public roads with a licensed instructor until you have your permit (the first 2-hour BTW session is sometimes scheduled the day you get your permit).

## Step 2: Start your application online

California uses an online application system that lets you fill out the DL 44 form before your DMV visit. You will need to:

- Create or sign in to a **DMV online account**.
- Complete the driver license/ID application.
- Pay the application fee (one fee covers the permit and your eventual provisional license).
- Schedule a DMV office appointment - walk-ins are accepted but appointments save hours.

## Step 3: Gather your documents

Bring **all** of the following to your appointment:

1. Proof of identity (certified birth certificate or valid passport).
2. Proof of your Social Security Number (card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full number).
3. Two documents proving California residency (utility bill, school records, parent''s mortgage statement with you listed).
4. Your driver education completion certificate.
5. A parent or legal guardian if you are under 18 - they must sign the application in person to give consent and accept financial responsibility.

## Step 4: At the DMV

You will:

- Have your photo taken.
- Provide a thumbprint.
- Pass a vision screening.
- Pay any remaining fees.
- Take the **knowledge test** - 46 multiple-choice questions; you must answer at least 38 correctly. You get three attempts on the application fee; failing all three requires reapplying and paying again.

If you pass, you walk out with a paper interim permit. The plastic card arrives by mail within a few weeks.

## Step 5: After you have the permit

You must hold the permit for **at least 6 months** before you can take the behind-the-wheel drive test for your provisional license. During this time you must:

- Complete **6 hours of professional behind-the-wheel training** with a state-licensed driving instructor (usually three 2-hour sessions).
- Log **50 hours of supervised practice driving**, including at least **10 hours at night**, with a licensed driver age 25 or older.
- Always have your supervising driver in the front passenger seat - never drive alone on a permit.

Keep your practice log accurate and signed by your supervising drivers. The DMV may ask to see it when you arrive for your road test. Treat the permit phase as your real education: the habits you build in these months are the habits you keep for life.', 45, 0
);
