INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ca_california-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_ca_overlay', 'california-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Living with California''s GDL Restrictions', '# Living with California''s GDL Restrictions

Earning your **provisional license** in California is exciting - but the license that comes in the mail is not a full, unrestricted driver license. For the first 12 months, you are subject to the state''s **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** rules. Understanding them is not just about avoiding tickets; it changes how you plan your week, who rides with you, and when you can be on the road.

## The 12-month clock

The restrictions below apply for **12 months from the date your provisional license is issued or until you turn 18, whichever comes first**. Plan around that anniversary - many teens miscount and assume the rules expire on their 17th birthday. They don''t.

## Passenger restrictions

For the first 12 months, you **may not transport any passenger under 20 years old** unless you are accompanied by:

- A licensed parent or legal guardian,
- A licensed driver who is 25 or older, or
- A licensed or certified driving instructor.

This rule has practical consequences. You cannot drive your younger siblings to school, give a teammate a ride home from practice, or pick up a friend for a movie - even if your friend is 18 or 19. Plan carpools accordingly, and never let social pressure talk you into bending the rule "just this once." Officers can stop and cite you, and a violation extends or restarts the restriction period.

## Nighttime restriction

For the first 12 months, you **may not drive between 11 p.m. and 5 a.m.** unless accompanied by the same categories of supervising adult listed above. That means if you work a closing shift, attend an evening concert, or want to catch a late movie, you need a plan for a ride home before you head out.

## Limited exceptions

California recognizes a narrow set of **documented exceptions** to the passenger and nighttime rules: medical necessity, school or school-authorized activity, employment necessity, immediate family necessity, and emancipated minors. Each requires a signed note (from a parent, employer, school authority, doctor, etc.) carried in the vehicle. The exception is for *necessity*, not convenience - prepare to justify it.

## Cell phones and electronic devices

California is **stricter for minors than for adult drivers**. If you are under 18 you may not use a cell phone, text, or operate any wireless device while driving - period. There is **no hands-free exception** for minor drivers. Bluetooth, speaker mode, and earbuds are all prohibited while the car is moving. The safest habit is to put the phone in Do Not Disturb While Driving mode (built into iOS and Android) every time you start the engine.

Adult passengers may use phones, and you may use a phone in a genuine emergency to call 911, fire, or medical responders. "My friend really needed to know I''d be late" is not an emergency.

## Seat belts and child passengers

Every occupant must be properly restrained. As the driver you are legally responsible for any passenger under 16 who is not in a seat belt or appropriate child restraint. Children under 8 generally must ride in a booster or car seat in the back seat. Get in the habit of confirming belts before you shift into drive.

## What happens if you break a GDL rule

Violations are reported to the DMV and can result in fines, mandatory court appearance with a parent, license suspension or restriction extensions, and increases in your family''s insurance premium. The cost of one citation often exceeds an entire semester of driver education tuition.

## Building habits that outlast the restrictions

The goal of the GDL system is not punishment - it is the gradual introduction of risk. Use this year to develop the boring, reliable habits that prevent crashes: phone away, eyes scanning, hands on the wheel, planning your route, and asking yourself before each trip, "Am I legal, alert, and unimpaired?"', 40, 1
);
