INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ca_california-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ca_overlay', 'california-rules-and-quirks', 'California-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Driver Should Know', '# California-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Driver Should Know

Many road rules are similar from state to state, but California has a handful of laws and conventions that catch out-of-state drivers - and teens taking the road test - by surprise. Mastering these signals to examiners and insurance carriers alike that you are a thoughtful California driver, not just someone who memorized a generic handbook.

## Lane splitting is legal (for motorcycles)

California is the **only state in the U.S. that explicitly authorizes lane splitting** - motorcycles riding between lanes of slower or stopped traffic. As a car driver, this changes your habits in two big ways:

- **Always shoulder-check before changing lanes**, even in slow traffic. A motorcycle may be in the gap between you and the next lane.
- **Never intentionally block a splitting motorcyclist**. It is unsafe and may be considered road rage.

Assume a motorcycle could appear next to you at any time, especially in traffic on freeways or near intersections.

## The "California stop" is illegal

Ironically, the rolling stop nicknamed the "California stop" is **never legal in California**. At a stop sign or red light, you must come to a complete stop with the vehicle no longer moving, then proceed when safe. On the DMV road test, a rolling stop is one of the most common automatic disqualifiers. Count one full second at every stop sign.

## Right turn on red

Right turn on red is permitted unless a sign prohibits it - but only after a **complete stop** and only when it is safe and pedestrians have cleared the crosswalk. Many San Francisco and downtown Los Angeles intersections post "No Turn on Red" signs; obey them precisely.

## Move Over Law

When approaching any **stationary emergency vehicle, tow truck, or Caltrans vehicle with flashing lights** on a highway, you must move over one lane if it is safe to do so, or slow to a reasonable speed if you cannot. This includes police, fire, ambulances, and roadside assistance trucks.

## Headlights and weather

California law requires headlights any time you are using windshield wipers because of weather. The shorthand is **"wipers on, lights on."** Parking lights alone do not satisfy this rule.

## School zones and crossing guards

The default speed limit in a school zone with children present is **25 mph**, and many zones drop to **15 mph** when posted. You must come to a complete stop for a crossing guard''s handheld stop sign and remain stopped until the guard has fully cleared the crosswalk and lowered the sign.

## Bicycle and pedestrian protections

- The **Three Feet for Safety Act** requires drivers to give bicyclists at least 3 feet of clearance when passing. If 3 feet is not possible, you must slow to a safe speed and pass only when no danger is present.
- Pedestrians have the right of way in any marked or unmarked crosswalk at an intersection. "Unmarked" includes the imaginary extension of a sidewalk across an intersection where no white lines are painted.

## Driving under the influence - zero tolerance

For drivers under 21, California has a **zero tolerance law**: any measurable alcohol (0.01% BAC or higher) results in license suspension. For drivers under 18 the consequences are even steeper and can delay or revoke licensing eligibility. Cannabis is legal for adults 21+ in California, but it is **never legal to drive while impaired**, regardless of age, and an open container - including a partially used vape pen - in the passenger area is a violation.

## Smog, registration, and proof of insurance

Every driver must carry proof of insurance, the vehicle registration card, and the driver license while operating a vehicle. California requires biennial smog checks for most gasoline vehicles over a certain age, and electronic proof of insurance on a phone is accepted at traffic stops.

## Earthquake and brushfire awareness

California is the only place where your driver education realistically must mention earthquakes and wildfires. During an earthquake while driving, pull to the side of the road away from overpasses, power lines, and large signs; stay in the car until shaking stops. During wildfire evacuation, follow posted emergency routes, keep headlights on through smoke, and never park on dry grass.

Knowing these California-specific rules is the difference between passing your road test and learning them the expensive way.', 40, 2
);
