INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_co_co-how-to-get-your-permit', 'module_co_overlay', 'co-how-to-get-your-permit', 'How to Get Your Colorado Instruction Permit', '# Getting Your Colorado Instruction Permit

In Colorado, the instruction permit is the first step of a three-stage Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) system run by the Colorado Department of Revenue''s Division of Motor Vehicles (DMV). The exact path you take depends on how old you are when you apply.

## Age-based pathways

**Ages 15 to 15 years 6 months.** You must complete a 30-hour, state-approved driver education classroom course (online or in person) *before* you can apply. You also need a signed Affidavit of Liability and Guardianship from a parent or legal guardian, who must appear with you at the DMV office.

**Ages 15 years 6 months to 16.** You have two options. Option A is the full 30-hour driver education course described above. Option B is the four-hour Driver Awareness Program (DAP), which is shorter but only qualifies you for a permit - you''ll still need behind-the-wheel training before licensing.

**Ages 16 to 17.** You can apply for a permit without any pre-course, but you must still pass the written knowledge test and hold the permit for the required time before licensing.

**Ages 17 to 21.** No driver education is required to get a permit, and the permit-holding period drops to as little as 12 months in most cases.

## What to bring to the DMV

- Proof of identity (certified birth certificate, valid passport, or other accepted document)
- Proof of Colorado residency for your parent/guardian (utility bill, lease, etc.)
- Social Security card or other proof of SSN
- Completed Affidavit of Liability and Guardianship (DR 2460), signed in front of a DMV agent or notarized
- Your driver education completion certificate (if applicable)
- Application fee (currently around $18-$20; check the DMV site for current pricing)

A parent, legal guardian, or court-appointed custodian must accompany you and accept financial responsibility for you on the road. If neither parent has custody, a grandparent over 18 may sign with a notarized affidavit.

## The written knowledge test

The Colorado written test covers road signs, signals, right-of-way, sharing the road with cyclists and pedestrians, mountain driving, and Colorado-specific laws like the Move Over law. It''s 25 multiple-choice questions and you need 80% to pass. The Colorado Driver Handbook (free PDF from mycolorado.gov) is the official study source. If you fail, you can retest, usually the next business day, for a small fee.

## Vision screening

You must pass a vision screening at the DMV (20/40 in at least one eye, with or without correction). Bring your glasses or contacts; if you need them to pass, your license will carry a corrective-lenses restriction.

## After you pass

Once you have your permit, the 12-month clock starts. During that year you must:

1. Complete 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training with a state-licensed driving school (if you are under 16.5).
2. Log 50 hours of supervised driving, including 10 hours after dark, signed off by your parent or guardian.
3. Always drive with a licensed adult 21 or older in the front passenger seat - no exceptions.

The permit is valid for three years. Keep it on you any time you drive, and remember: any traffic conviction during the permit period can reset your eligibility clock for licensing.', 35, 0
);
