INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_co_co-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_co_overlay', 'co-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Colorado GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Living With Colorado''s GDL Rules

Getting your minor driver''s license in Colorado is a milestone - but the license you get at 16 isn''t the same one your parents have. For your first year, Colorado''s Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) law limits *when* you can drive, *who* can ride with you, and *what* you can do with your phone. Knowing these rules cold keeps your license and keeps you safe.

## The nighttime curfew

For the first 12 months after you get your license (or until you turn 18, whichever comes first), you may not drive between midnight and 5:00 a.m. There are narrow exceptions:

- Driving to or from work, with documentation
- Driving to or from a school-sanctioned activity
- Driving for a medical emergency
- Driving with a parent, legal guardian, or licensed driving instructor in the front seat

"Documentation" means an actual note from your employer or school - a text from your manager will not satisfy an officer at 1:00 a.m. If you have a late shift, keep a signed letter in the glove box.

## The passenger rule (the one teens forget most)

Colorado''s passenger restriction is **two-phase**:

- **Months 1 to 6 of licensure:** No passengers under 21 in the vehicle - period - unless a parent, guardian, or licensed driver 21+ is in the front seat. That means you cannot drive your best friend, your boyfriend or girlfriend, or even your 14-year-old cousin alone.
- **Months 7 to 12 of licensure:** You may carry one passenger under 21, but no more.

The most important exception is for **siblings** living in your household, and for emergencies. Even so, if you have three siblings, you''d be over the limit during months 7-12. Plan carpools accordingly.

This rule exists because crash data is brutal: a 16-year-old driving with two teen passengers is roughly five times more likely to crash than the same teen driving alone.

## The cell phone ban

In Colorado, **drivers under 18 may not use a wireless telephone for any reason while driving**, including hands-free. The only legal exception is reporting a genuine emergency to 911, a hospital, a fire department, or law enforcement.

That means no:

- Calls (even on speaker or via Bluetooth)
- Texts (even at a red light - you''re still "driving")
- Snapchat, TikTok, voice memos, or Spotify scrolling
- Navigating - set your GPS *before* you put the car in gear

A first offense is a $50 fine plus a point on your license. A second offense is $100. More importantly, a phone violation during your provisional year can extend your restriction period.

## Seat belts, every seat, every time

Colorado''s teen seat belt law requires the driver and *every* passenger - regardless of age or seat - to wear a seat belt when a driver under 18 is at the wheel. As the driver, you can be ticketed for unbelted passengers. Make "click it before I shift it" your habit.

## What happens if you break a GDL rule

GDL violations are primary offenses, meaning an officer can pull you over solely for the violation. Penalties stack: fines, points, mandatory court appearance for some violations, and possible license suspension. Two convictions during your minor-license period typically result in a one-month suspension; three result in three months and a required retest.

The simplest rule of thumb: drive like your parent is in the passenger seat, because legally, the consequences land on them too.', 30, 1
);
