INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_co_co-state-rules-and-quirks', 'module_co_overlay', 'co-state-rules-and-quirks', 'Colorado-Specific Rules, Roads, and Quirks', '# Driving Colorado: The Rules That Make This State Different

Colorado''s geography forces driving habits that don''t exist in flatter, lower-altitude states. Between the mountain passes, the wildlife, the weather, and a handful of state-specific laws, there''s a distinct Colorado driver skill set. Knowing these things doesn''t just keep you out of a ticket book - it can keep you out of a guardrail or a ditch.

## Mountain driving basics

If you spend any time west of the Front Range, you''ll face steep grades, switchbacks, and rapidly changing weather.

- **Downhill: gear down, don''t ride the brakes.** Continuously pressing the brake on a long descent overheats them and causes brake fade. Shift your transmission to L, 2, or manual mode and let engine braking do the work.
- **Uphill yields to downhill** on narrow mountain roads. The downhill driver has less control and a harder time restarting on a steep grade.
- **Use the runaway truck ramps if you must.** They are free, and always better than the alternative.
- **Watch the chain laws.** Colorado activates traction and chain laws on I-70 and other passes in winter. Passenger vehicles must have snow tires, M+S-rated tires with at least 3/16" tread, AWD/4WD, or chains. Violations start above $130; causing a closure can exceed $650.

## Wildlife collisions

Colorado averages thousands of wildlife collisions a year. Dawn and dusk are peak times for deer, elk, and moose. If an animal is in the road:

- **Brake hard, don''t swerve.** Swerving into oncoming traffic or off the shoulder causes more deaths than hitting the animal.
- **One deer means more.** They travel in groups.
- **Honk and flash high beams** if you see eyes near the roadside before the animal enters the road.

## The Move Over law

When approaching any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or utility vehicle with flashing lights on the shoulder, Colorado law requires you to **move over one lane** if you can do so safely. If you can''t change lanes, slow to at least 20 mph below the posted limit (or 10 mph below if the limit is 25 mph or less).

## Bicycles and the 3-foot rule

Colorado law requires drivers to leave at least **3 feet of space** when passing a bicyclist. Drivers may legally cross a double-yellow line to give that space when it is safe to do so - a quirk that surprises out-of-state drivers. Boulder, Fort Collins, and Denver have heavy bike traffic; treat every bike lane as a live lane.

## Marijuana and driving

Recreational marijuana is legal for adults 21+ in Colorado, but driving impaired by marijuana is a DUI just like alcohol. For drivers under 21, Colorado''s **zero tolerance** law makes any detectable THC, or a blood alcohol of 0.02% or more, grounds for a DUI-related charge. Open marijuana containers in the passenger compartment are illegal, just like open alcohol.

## Express lanes

Many Colorado highways use ExpressToll express lanes. **Crossing a double white line into or out of an express lane is illegal** and heavily ticketed - enter and exit only at the dashed white sections.

## Snow and black ice

Colorado''s first heavy snow each fall produces a notorious spike in crashes. Black ice forms on bridges and shaded curves even when the rest of the road is dry. Slow down, double your following distance, and avoid sudden steering or braking. If you start to skid, ease off the gas and steer gently in the direction you want the front of the car to go.

Master these habits and you''ll drive Colorado the way locals do - with respect for the mountains, the weather, and the wildlife that share the road.', 35, 2
);
