INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ct_getting-your-ct-learners-permit', 'module_ct_overlay', 'getting-your-ct-learners-permit', 'How to Get Your Connecticut Learner''s Permit', '# How to Get Your Connecticut Learner''s Permit

Getting your learner''s permit in Connecticut is the first major step toward driving independently. The Connecticut Department of Motor Vehicles (CT DMV) administers the process, and the rules are designed to make sure new drivers are prepared before they ever take the wheel on a public road.

## Eligibility

You must be at least **16 years old** to apply for a learner''s permit in Connecticut. If you are under 18, your parent or legal guardian must sign the application in person and provide consent. There is no younger ''junior'' permit — 16 is the earliest you can begin.

## What to Bring to the DMV

Connecticut uses a strict identity verification system. When you go to the DMV office or an authorized testing center, you will need:

- **Proof of identity** (such as a certified birth certificate or valid passport)
- **Proof of Social Security number** (Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub)
- **Two proofs of Connecticut residency** (utility bill, bank statement, school transcript, etc.)
- **Parent or legal guardian** in person if you are under 18
- **Application fee and knowledge test fee** (check ct.gov/dmv for current amounts)

Double-check the CT DMV website before your appointment — missing documents are the #1 reason teens get turned away.

## The Knowledge Test

Before you can be issued a permit, you must pass a **25-question knowledge test** based on the Connecticut Driver''s Manual. You need to answer at least 20 correct (80%) to pass. The questions cover:

- Road signs and signals
- Right-of-way rules
- Speed limits and safe following distance
- Connecticut-specific laws (cell phones, seat belts, GDL restrictions)
- Sharing the road with pedestrians, cyclists, and motorcycles

You will also take a **vision screening** at the DMV.

## The 120-Day Holding Period

Once you have your permit, Connecticut requires you to hold it for at least **120 days** if you complete driver education through a commercial driving school or secondary school program. If you do not complete formal driver ed, the holding period is **180 days**. Either way, you cannot skip the wait — the CT DMV checks the issue date of your permit against the day you apply for your license.

## Driver Education Requirements

Connecticut requires teens under 18 to complete:

- **30 hours of classroom instruction** (or the 8-hour ''Safe Driving Practices'' course if combined with a secondary school program)
- **40 hours of behind-the-wheel instruction** with a licensed instructor
- **40 hours of supervised practice driving** with a parent, guardian, or qualified adult (at least 15 of which must be at night)

## The Parent Training Requirement

Connecticut is unusual in requiring **parents and guardians** to complete a **2-hour training session** covering the GDL law before a teen can be issued a license. This session is offered at driving schools and some high schools. Plan for it early — many families forget until the last minute and end up delaying the license appointment.

## Permit Restrictions

While holding a learner''s permit, you may only drive when accompanied by a qualified instructor or, after the first 60 days, a parent/guardian or licensed adult age 20+ who has held a license for at least 4 years. Permit holders may not use any cell phone — even hands-free — while driving.

## Next Step

After the holding period, completing driver ed, logging your practice hours, and your parent finishing the training course, you can schedule the **road skills test** to earn your full license at age 16 years and 4 months or older.', 35, 0
);
