INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ct_ct-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ct_overlay', 'ct-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Connecticut GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Connecticut GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Getting your license is exciting, but Connecticut''s **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** rules mean you don''t get all the freedoms of an adult driver right away. These rules exist because crash data consistently shows that the first year of solo driving — especially with friends in the car or late at night — is by far the most dangerous. Understanding how the GDL rules affect your everyday life will keep you safe and keep your license intact.

## The Passenger Rule

Connecticut has one of the strictest passenger restrictions in the country. For the **first 6 months** after getting your license, the **only** people allowed in your car are:

- Your parents or legal guardians
- A licensed driving instructor

That''s it. No friends. No siblings. No cousins. For the **next 6 months** (months 7 through 12), you can also drive with **immediate family members** — parents, siblings, grandparents, spouse. Still no friends. Only after a **full year** of licensed driving may you carry non-family passengers.

How this affects you:
- You cannot drive friends to school, practice, or the movies in your first year.
- You cannot give a teammate a ride home after the game.
- If you carpool, someone older has to drive — or your friend''s licensed parent.

## The Curfew

During your first year of licensure, you may not drive between **11:00 PM and 5:00 AM**. The only exceptions are:

- Driving to/from a job (with documentation)
- Driving to/from school activities
- Driving for a religious activity
- A documented medical emergency

If you stay out late at a friend''s house, you need to be home before 11 PM or arrange a different ride. Police actively enforce this restriction.

## The Cell Phone Ban

Connecticut prohibits **all** drivers under 18 from using **any** mobile electronic device while driving — including **hands-free** devices. This is stricter than the adult rule. That means:

- No talking on the phone, even with Bluetooth
- No texting
- No GPS app interactions while moving
- No music app changes while moving

Set your music and navigation before you put the car in drive. If you need to take a call, pull over safely.

## Seat Belts Are Mandatory for Everyone

When a 16- or 17-year-old is driving, **every** occupant in the vehicle must wear a seat belt — front and back seats. This is stricter than the adult rule (which only requires front-seat belts). As the driver, you are responsible.

## Penalties Are Severe

Connecticut takes GDL violations seriously. A first offense for violating curfew, passenger, or cell phone rules can result in:

- **48-hour license suspension** on the spot for some violations
- Fines starting around $125 and going much higher
- Required reinstatement fee
- Possible 30-day or longer suspension for repeat violations
- A conviction stays on your driving record

## Planning Around the Rules

The smartest teens plan their social and work lives around the GDL rules:

- Talk to your boss about scheduling shifts that end before 11 PM during your first year.
- Coordinate with friends so adult drivers handle group outings.
- Use the time to build skill in low-pressure conditions before adding distractions.

The restrictions lift automatically at the 6-month, 12-month, and 18th-birthday milestones — there''s no extra paperwork required, but you must be ready to prove you''re within the rules if pulled over.', 30, 1
);
