INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ct_ct-gdl-restrictions-daily-life_4', 'quiz_ct_ct-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'What seat belt rule applies when a 16- or 17-year-old is the driver in Connecticut?', '["Only the driver must wear a belt","Only front-seat occupants must wear belts","All occupants — front and back — must wear seat belts","Seat belts are recommended but not required"]', 2, 'When a 16- or 17-year-old is driving, every occupant in the vehicle must wear a seat belt, regardless of seat position.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ct_ct-specific-driving-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ct_overlay', 'ct-specific-driving-rules-and-quirks', 'Connecticut-Specific Rules and Driving Quirks', '# Connecticut-Specific Rules and Driving Quirks

Connecticut may be a small state, but it has some unique road rules, road designs, and driving customs that can trip up new drivers. Knowing them ahead of time will help you avoid tickets, accidents, and the awkward moment of being honked at by every car around you.

## Move Over Law

Connecticut''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers to slow down and, when safe, move to a non-adjacent lane when approaching:

- Emergency vehicles (police, fire, ambulance) with flashing lights
- Tow trucks with flashing lights
- Highway maintenance and construction vehicles with flashing amber lights

Violating the Move Over Law carries significant fines and can lead to your license being suspended. On a 2-lane highway where you can''t change lanes, you must slow down to a reasonable speed below the posted limit.

## Right Turn on Red

Right turns on red are **allowed** in Connecticut after a complete stop — **unless a sign prohibits it**. Many Connecticut intersections, especially in cities like Hartford, New Haven, Stamford, and Bridgeport, post ''No Turn on Red'' signs. Always look up and check the sign before turning.

## Roundabouts and Rotaries

Connecticut has a growing number of **modern roundabouts** (smaller, single-lane) and older **rotaries** (larger, often multi-lane). The rules:

- **Yield to traffic already in the circle.**
- Signal your exit (right turn signal) as you approach the lane you''ll leave from.
- In a multi-lane rotary, choose your lane based on which exit you''ll take — the inner lane is generally for going more than halfway around.

The rotaries in places like Norwich and on Route 9 can be intimidating; practice with a parent before you tackle one solo.

## Headlights with Wipers

Connecticut law requires you to turn on your **headlights any time your windshield wipers are in continuous use** because of weather. Daytime running lights do not count — you need actual headlights on. This applies in rain, snow, fog, and sleet.

## School Buses

When a school bus is stopped with **flashing red lights** and the stop sign extended:

- All traffic in **both directions** must stop on undivided roads.
- On a divided highway with a physical median, only traffic in the **same direction** as the bus must stop.
- Stay stopped until the lights stop flashing.

Violating this carries a fine of around $450 for a first offense and is considered a moving violation that affects your record and insurance.

## Toll Roads (or Lack Thereof)

Connecticut **does not currently have tolls** on its highways, but neighboring New York and Massachusetts do. If you cross state lines on I-95, I-91, or the Merritt Parkway extension, be ready for tolls. Many bridges in the NYC area are cashless and bill by license plate.

## The Merritt Parkway

The Merritt Parkway (Route 15) is a Connecticut treasure and a quirk you should know:

- **No commercial vehicles allowed** (no trucks, no trailers).
- Speed limit is generally **55 mph**.
- The on-ramps and off-ramps are **very short** by modern standards — be ready to merge fast.
- Stone bridges and tight curves require attention; do not drive it for the first time at night.

## Snow and Ice

Connecticut winters bring real snow. Two rules to remember:

- **Clear all snow and ice from your vehicle** before driving — including the roof. Flying snow/ice that hits another car is illegal under the ''Ice Missile Law'' and carries fines up to $1,250.
- Studded tires are allowed only between **November 15 and April 30**.

## Drive Friendly

Finally, a cultural quirk: Connecticut drivers are notorious for **not zipper-merging** and for following close. Defensive driving is essential. Leave extra following distance, signal clearly, and don''t expect others to make room for you in heavy traffic on I-95 or I-84.', 30, 2
);
