INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_dc_getting-your-dc-learner-permit', 'module_dc_overlay', 'getting-your-dc-learner-permit', 'How to Get Your Learner Permit in the District of Columbia', '## Overview

In the District of Columbia, the learner permit is the first step in a three-stage graduated driver licensing (GDL) system administered by the **DC Department of Motor Vehicles (DC DMV)**. You must be at least **16 years old** to apply, and the permit you receive is what allows you to begin practicing on public roads with a qualified supervising driver.

## Eligibility Requirements

To qualify for a DC learner permit you must:

- Be at least **16 years of age** on the day of application.
- Have **parental or guardian consent** if you are under 18 (a parent or legal guardian must appear in person at the DMV to sign the application).
- Provide proof of **school enrollment, graduation, or a GED**. DC ties teen licensing to school attendance, and your school must verify good standing.
- Provide acceptable proof of **identity, Social Security number, and DC residency** under the District''s standard REAL ID document checklist.

## The Application Visit

DC requires teens to apply in person at a DC DMV service center (Georgetown, Southwest, Southeast, or Benning Ridge typically). Bring every required document the first time — the DMV will not accept photocopies for ID, Social Security, or residency proofs. Plan for an extended visit, because all of the following happen during the same trip:

1. **Document review** by a DMV clerk.
2. **Vision screening** (you can use corrective lenses; a restriction will be added to your permit if needed).
3. **Knowledge test** — a written/computer-based exam covering DC traffic laws, road signs, and safe driving practices, drawn from the DC DMV Driver Manual.
4. **Permit fee payment** and photo capture.

If you pass the knowledge test, the DMV issues your learner permit the same day.

## Studying for the Knowledge Test

The official **DC DMV Driver Manual** is the single best study resource. Focus on:

- DC''s GDL restrictions for permit and provisional drivers.
- Right-of-way rules at intersections, including traffic circles (DC has many).
- The District''s strict **hand-held device ban** and the total ban on cell phone use for drivers under 18.
- DC''s pedestrian and cyclist right-of-way rules, which are stricter than in most states.
- Parking signage, which is dense and tightly enforced in DC.

## Practicing Safely During the Permit Stage

Once you have your learner permit, you must:

- Be supervised at all times by a licensed driver **age 21 or older** in the front passenger seat.
- Log at least **40 hours of supervised practice**, with at least **10 hours at night**, before you can move to a provisional license.
- Hold the permit for a minimum of **6 months** without any moving violations or at-fault crashes. A violation can reset that clock.

Keep a written or app-based practice log signed by your supervising adult. The DMV may ask to see it when you apply for your provisional license.

## Next Step: The Provisional License

At age **16 years and 6 months**, after meeting the practice and clean-record requirements, you may return to the DMV to take the road skills test in your own (or your driving school''s) properly insured vehicle. Passing earns you a **provisional license** with the GDL restrictions covered in the next lesson.', 35, 0
);
