INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_dc_dc-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_dc_overlay', 'dc-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living with DC''s Graduated License Restrictions', '## Why GDL Restrictions Exist

New drivers, regardless of age, crash at far higher rates during their first year behind the wheel. DC''s **graduated driver licensing (GDL)** program limits when and with whom a young driver can be on the road during the months when risk is highest. Treat these as personal habits, not legal hoops — they are how you stay alive and keep your license.

## The DC Provisional License

Once you earn your provisional license (typically at 16 years 6 months), three categories of restrictions apply until you graduate to a full license.

### 1. Nighttime Driving Curfew

Provisional drivers in DC may not drive during late-night hours:

- **Sunday through Thursday:** no driving between **11:00 PM and 6:00 AM**.
- **Friday and Saturday:** no driving between **12:01 AM and 6:00 AM**.

Limited exceptions exist for driving to or from **work, school activities, or a documented medical emergency**, but you should be prepared to prove the purpose if stopped. "I was just heading home from a friend''s" is not an exception.

### 2. Passenger Limits

- **First 6 months of provisional licensing:** you may not carry any passenger under age 21 other than immediate family members (parents, siblings, your own child).
- **Months 7 through 12:** you may carry no more than **two passengers under 21** at a time.
- After 12 months of clean provisional driving, passenger limits ease.

The reason is data-driven: every additional teen passenger roughly doubles a young driver''s crash risk.

### 3. Cell Phone and Device Ban

DC''s distracted driving law is one of the strictest in the country, and it is especially strict for minors:

- **All drivers under 18:** no cell phone use at all while driving — **including hands-free**. Bluetooth, speakerphone, and earbuds are all prohibited.
- **Texting:** banned for every driver in DC, regardless of age.
- **Hand-held devices:** banned for every driver in DC.

Pull over and park legally before answering a call or touching your phone.

## Practical Daily Habits

- **Set up navigation before you put the car in drive.** Once you''re moving, your phone must be untouched.
- **Plan rides home that beat the curfew.** Working a Friday night shift that ends at 11:45 PM is allowed under the work exception, but a movie that ends at midnight is not.
- **Be honest with friends about the passenger rule.** A police stop with three under-21 passengers can cost you your license and your auto insurance rate for years.
- **Carry proof of any exception.** A work schedule, a school activity letter, or a medical appointment confirmation in the glove box solves a lot of late-night curfew questions.

## Consequences of Violations

A moving violation or at-fault crash during the provisional period can:

- **Extend** the time you must hold the provisional license.
- **Suspend** the provisional license entirely.
- **Reset** the clean-record clock for upgrading to a full license.
- Trigger an insurance premium increase that can follow you for three to five years.

## Graduating to a Full License

At age **18**, with a clean driving record during the provisional period, you may apply for a full unrestricted DC driver license. There is no additional road test required if your provisional license has been valid and in good standing.', 30, 1
);
