INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_dc_driving-in-the-district-quirks', 'module_dc_overlay', 'driving-in-the-district-quirks', 'Driving in the District: DC-Specific Rules and Quirks', '## A Dense, Federal, Pedestrian-First City

Driving in DC is unlike driving in most US jurisdictions. The District is small, dense, full of pedestrians and cyclists, packed with federal motorcades and protests, and built around a wheel-and-spoke street grid that includes more than 60 traffic circles. New drivers should plan to think like a pedestrian first and a motorist second.

## Traffic Circles (Roundabouts)

DC has many traffic circles — Dupont, Logan, Thomas, Washington, and Stanton among them. Rules:

- **Traffic already in the circle has the right of way.** Yield before entering.
- **Signal your exit**, not your entrance.
- The largest circles (like Dupont) have **through lanes** that pass under or around the circle. Read the lane markings carefully and choose the right lane well before you arrive.

## Pedestrian Right of Way

DC law gives pedestrians extraordinary protection:

- Drivers must **stop** — not just yield — for pedestrians in any marked or unmarked crosswalk.
- At intersections without signals, pedestrians always have the right of way.
- Turning right on red is legal in DC unless a sign prohibits it, but you must come to a complete stop and yield to pedestrians and cyclists in the crosswalk.

Failing to yield to a pedestrian in a crosswalk is one of the most heavily enforced violations in the District.

## Bus and Bike Lanes

- **Dedicated bus lanes** (red-painted in many corridors) are off-limits to private vehicles during posted hours. Cameras enforce this automatically.
- **Protected bike lanes** are everywhere in the District. Never drive, stop, or park in one — even briefly.
- When turning across a bike lane, **yield to cyclists going straight**, just as you would yield to a car in the next lane.

## Automated Enforcement

DC relies heavily on automated cameras:

- **Red-light cameras** at hundreds of intersections.
- **Speed cameras** on residential streets, school zones, and major arteries — many with very low posted limits (20–25 mph).
- **Stop-sign cameras** in some neighborhoods.
- **Bus-lane and crosswalk-blocking cameras**.

Tickets arrive in the mail and are tied to the registered vehicle owner — often your parent. Treat every posted speed limit as if a camera is watching, because it probably is.

## Motorcades, Protests, and Street Closures

DC routinely closes streets with little warning for presidential motorcades, foreign dignitaries, marches, and demonstrations. If a Metropolitan Police, Secret Service, or Capitol Police officer is directing traffic, **their instructions override** signals and signs. Stay calm, follow directions, and never try to squeeze through a closed intersection.

## Parking — A Discipline of Its Own

DC parking signage is famously dense, with multiple signs stacked on a single pole covering rush-hour restrictions, residential permit zones (RPP), street cleaning, and meter hours. Read **every** sign on the pole, from top to bottom, before leaving the car. When in doubt, drive another block.

## Snow Emergencies

When the Mayor declares a **Snow Emergency**, vehicles parked on designated Snow Emergency Routes (marked with red-and-white signs) must be moved or they will be ticketed and towed. Watch local alerts in winter.

## Reciprocity and Out-of-State Plates

Maryland and Virginia commuters fill DC streets. As a new DC driver you''ll share the road with drivers operating under three different sets of state rules. Drive defensively — assume the car next to you may not know DC''s pedestrian and bike-lane laws.', 30, 2
);
