INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_de_how-to-get-a-delaware-permit', 'module_de_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-delaware-permit', 'How to Get Your Delaware Level 1 Learner''s Permit', '# How to Get Your Delaware Level 1 Learner''s Permit

Delaware uses a two-tier **Graduated Driver License (GDL)** program administered by the **Delaware Division of Motor Vehicles (DMV)**. Your first credential is the **Level 1 Learner''s Permit**, and earning it is mostly about completing the state-approved driver education course and then walking into a DMV lane with the right paperwork.

## Step 1: Turn 16 (and enroll in driver ed first)

In Delaware you can apply for a Level 1 Permit at **age 16**, but the practical sequence is:

1. Enroll in an **approved Delaware driver education course** — typically offered free through your public high school in 10th grade, or through a DOE-approved private provider if you are home-schooled, in a private school that does not offer it, or otherwise need an alternate path.
2. Complete the required **30 hours of classroom instruction** and **7 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW)** training with a certified instructor.
3. Receive your signed completion paperwork from the school. Historically Delaware uses a colored certificate (sometimes called the "blue card" or course completion card) that you bring to the DMV.

You cannot simply walk in at 16 and take a knowledge test without the course — completion of approved driver education is a **prerequisite** for the Level 1 Permit for teens under 18.

## Step 2: Gather your documents

Delaware requires federally-compliant identification. Plan to bring:

- **Proof of identity** (certified birth certificate or valid U.S. passport)
- **Proof of Social Security number** (SSN card, W-2, or pay stub showing full SSN)
- **Two proofs of Delaware residency** (utility bill, lease, bank statement). If you are under 18 you can use a parent''s documents along with your school record.
- **Driver education completion certificate** from your approved course
- **Parent or legal guardian signature** on the application — a parent must accompany you to the DMV to sign for financial responsibility
- **Payment** for the permit fee

## Step 3: Visit a DMV lane

Delaware has four DMV locations: **Wilmington, New Castle, Dover, and Georgetown**. Appointments are strongly recommended and can be booked on the DMV website. At the lane you will:

- Submit your documents and pay the fee
- Pass a **vision screening**
- In most cases, the **knowledge test is waived** because you completed approved driver education — your course covered the same material. If you did not complete driver ed (rare for teens), you would need to pass the written knowledge test.
- Take a photo and receive your Level 1 Permit

## Step 4: Live with the Level 1 rules

Once you have the permit, the clock starts on a **mandatory 6-month conviction-free holding period** and a longer 12-month total period before you can move to a Level 2 (Intermediate) license. During Level 1 you must:

- Always drive with a **licensed driver 25 or older** in the front passenger seat
- Log **50 hours of supervised practice**, including **10 hours at night**
- Avoid all moving violations — a conviction restarts the 6-month clock
- Follow the strict **10 PM–6 AM curfew** and passenger limits (covered in the next lesson)

## What is next

After 12 months on the Level 1 Permit with no convictions in the last 6 months, you can return to the DMV with your **parent-certified log of 50 hours** and upgrade to a Level 2 license. At **age 17** with a clean record you become eligible for an unrestricted Class D license. Getting your permit is just the start — your driving behavior during the next year decides how quickly you reach full licensure.', 35, 0
);
