INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_de_delaware-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_de_overlay', 'delaware-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Delaware GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Delaware GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Getting the Level 1 Permit is exciting, but Delaware''s **Graduated Driver License (GDL)** program adds real day-to-day rules that affect when and with whom you can drive. These restrictions stretch from the moment you get your permit at 16 through your Level 2 intermediate license, and only fully lift at age 18.

## The two phases at a glance

- **Level 1 — Learner''s Permit (minimum 12 months, including 6 months conviction-free)**
- **Level 2 — Intermediate License (begins after Level 1 requirements are met, continues until age 17 with restrictions tapering)**
- **Class D — Full unrestricted license at age 17 (with continued under-18 cell phone rules)**

## Curfew: the 10 PM to 6 AM rule

While on a Level 1 Permit, you may not drive between **10:00 PM and 6:00 AM**. This curfew also applies during the early portion of the Level 2 intermediate phase. Practical implications:

- A movie that ends at 10:30 PM means you need a licensed adult 25+ driving you home, or you need to leave earlier.
- Late shifts at a part-time job can be a problem. Delaware does provide narrow exemptions for work, school, and religious activities, but you must be able to document the reason (a note from your employer, school activity slip, etc.) if stopped.
- The clock is based on **when you are driving**, not when you started — pulling into your driveway at 10:01 PM is still a violation.

## Passenger limits

**Level 1 (permit):** A licensed driver **25 or older** must occupy the front passenger seat at all times. You may also carry family members. Only **one** non-family passenger is allowed in addition to the supervising adult.

**Level 2 (intermediate):** During the first 6 months of the intermediate license you may carry only **one passenger** who is not an immediate family member. After 6 months, that limit eases somewhat, but **all passengers must wear seat belts** and you remain responsible for their behavior. Carrying a carload of friends to the beach on a summer Friday is exactly the scenario these rules are designed to prevent — multi-teen crashes are the single largest cause of teen driving deaths.

## The under-18 cell phone ban

Delaware is one of the strictest states for teen device use. Drivers **under 18** are prohibited from using **any** cell phone or wireless communication device while driving — **even hands-free**. This includes:

- Bluetooth headsets and in-car Bluetooth calling
- Voice-activated dialing
- Apple CarPlay / Android Auto voice commands for messages or calls
- Smartwatch notifications you interact with

The **only** allowed use is calling 911 in an emergency. For all Delaware drivers (any age), handheld device use is banned and texting while driving is illegal — but the under-18 rule sweeps in hands-free use too.

## Seat belts and passenger responsibility

Delaware is a **primary enforcement** seat belt state — officers can stop you solely for an unbelted occupant. As the teen driver you are legally responsible for **every passenger under 16** being properly restrained.

## What "conviction-free" really means

A single moving violation conviction during the Level 1 phase **restarts the 6-month conviction-free clock**. Two violations can extend the permit phase by a full year. "Conviction" includes things students often underestimate: speeding 10 over, rolling stops, failing to yield, and especially the cell phone ban itself. Treat the GDL period as a probation — because legally, it is.

## Insurance and parents

Violations also surface on your parents'' insurance policy, where you are almost certainly a listed driver. A single ticket during the GDL period can raise a family''s premiums by hundreds of dollars per year for three years. The financial cost often dwarfs the fine itself.', 30, 1
);
