INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_de_delaware-rules-and-quirks', 'module_de_overlay', 'delaware-rules-and-quirks', 'Delaware-Specific Rules and Road Quirks', '# Delaware-Specific Rules and Road Quirks

Delaware is the second-smallest state, but it has a surprising amount of road variety: I-95 truck traffic near Wilmington, two-lane Sussex County back roads, the heavy beach corridor on Route 1, and the **Delaware Memorial Bridge** as one of the busiest twin-span bridges in the country. Here are the Delaware-specific rules, hazards, and quirks every new driver should know.

## Move Over Law

Delaware has a **Move Over Law** requiring drivers to either change lanes away from stopped emergency vehicles (police, fire, EMS, tow trucks, DelDOT crews) showing flashing lights, or — if changing lanes is unsafe or impossible — slow to a reasonable speed below the posted limit. On I-95, I-495, and Route 1 this is rigorously enforced because shoulder workers are routinely struck. Plan to start moving over as soon as you spot flashing lights ahead, not at the last second.

## Tolls and EZ-Pass

Delaware has some of the most prominent tolls per mile of highway of any state:

- **I-95 Newark Toll Plaza** (near the Maryland line)
- **SR-1 (Route 1) tolls** at Biddles Corner and Dover
- **Delaware Memorial Bridge** (eastbound to New Jersey)

Most residents use **E-ZPass Delaware**. If you drive without a transponder you will be billed by license plate via **Toll-by-Plate**, with surcharges. Teens borrowing a parent''s car should know whether the transponder is in the windshield and how it works — toll evasion citations are a real GDL hazard.

## Route 1 and the beach corridor

**Delaware Route 1 (SR-1)** between Dover and the Cape Region (Rehoboth, Dewey, Bethany, Fenwick) is the state''s most crash-prone corridor in summer. Specific risks:

- Speed limit changes rapidly — 65 mph divided highway sections drop to 35 or 25 mph entering beach towns.
- Pedestrians and bicyclists cross Route 1 to reach beaches, often outside of crosswalks.
- Sudden stop-and-go traffic on Friday afternoons heading south and Sunday afternoons heading north.
- **Coastal Highway (Route 1)** in Dewey/Rehoboth requires extra alertness for inattentive pedestrians, scooters, and golf carts crossing.

## Slow-moving farm equipment

Sussex County (and parts of Kent) is heavily agricultural. You will encounter **tractors, combines, and grain trucks** on two-lane roads, especially in spring and fall. Slow-moving vehicles display an orange triangle. Pass only where legal and with full visibility — these vehicles can make sudden wide left turns into field driveways without much warning.

## School bus rules

Delaware law requires drivers to **stop at least 20 feet away** from a school bus with **flashing red lights and extended stop arm**, regardless of whether you are behind or approaching from the opposite direction on an undivided road. Only on a **divided highway with a physical median or barrier** may oncoming traffic proceed with caution. Camera enforcement on stop-arms is being deployed in many Delaware districts; a violation typically carries a fine of several hundred dollars and points.

## DUI and Zero Tolerance

Delaware has a **Zero Tolerance** law for drivers under 21: a BAC of **0.02 or higher** results in license revocation. The standard adult DUI threshold is 0.08, but for teens any measurable alcohol means losing your license — often for 2 months for a first offense and longer for repeats. Marijuana, even where decriminalized for adults in small amounts, remains **illegal to consume before or while driving** and triggers the same teen license consequences.

## Failure-to-yield at unprotected lefts

Delaware DMV examiners consistently report that the most common reason teens fail the road test is **failure to fully yield on unprotected left turns** — especially at busy intersections like those along Route 13 (DuPont Highway) and Route 40 (Pulaski Highway). Practice judging gaps with a parent before your road test.

## Weather: nor''easters and coastal flooding

Delaware sees occasional **nor''easters** that flood low-lying roads in Sussex County and along the Delaware Bay. Never drive through standing water — a foot of moving water can float a small car. Listen for DelDOT road closure alerts during major storms.

## Quirks worth remembering

- Delaware does **not** allow right turn on red where signs prohibit it; downtown Wilmington has several such intersections.
- The state issues a **REAL ID compliant** driver license; bring all federal-ID documents to your first DMV visit so you don''t have to come back.
- Delaware has **no sales tax** but does charge a **document fee** when titling a vehicle — important to know before your first car purchase.', 30, 2
);
