INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_fl_getting-your-florida-learners-license', 'module_fl_overlay', 'getting-your-florida-learners-license', 'Getting Your Florida Learner''s License', '# Getting Your Florida Learner''s License

In Florida, the first step toward a full driver license is the **Learner''s License**, sometimes called a learner''s permit. You can apply as early as your **15th birthday**, but the state requires you to complete several specific steps before the Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles (FLHSMV) will hand you that credential.

## Step 1: Complete the TLSAE (4-Hour Drug and Alcohol) Course

Every first-time driver in Florida, regardless of age, must complete the **Traffic Law and Substance Abuse Education (TLSAE)** course. It is commonly called the "4-hour Drug and Alcohol course" because it runs roughly four hours and focuses on the effects of alcohol and controlled substances on driving, Florida traffic laws, and safe-driving practices. The course can be taken in a classroom or online through a state-approved provider. When you finish, the provider electronically reports your completion to FLHSMV, so you usually do not need to bring a paper certificate to your appointment, but it is wise to keep your confirmation handy.

## Step 2: Pass the Class E Knowledge Exam

The Class E Knowledge Exam tests your understanding of road rules and safe-driving practices. It contains **50 multiple-choice questions** split between road rules and road signs, and you must answer at least **40 correctly (80%)** to pass. You can take the test online through an authorized vendor if you are under 18, or in person at a tax collector''s office. If you fail, you must wait before retesting and pay a re-exam fee.

## Step 3: Gather Your Documents

Florida is a REAL ID state, so you will need to bring originals (no photocopies) of:

- **Proof of identity** — usually a certified U.S. birth certificate or valid passport.
- **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN.
- **Two proofs of Florida residential address** — utility bills, school records, a parent''s address affidavit, etc.
- **Parental Consent Form (HSMV 71142)** signed by a parent or legal guardian if you are under 18. This same form is later used to certify your 50 hours of supervised practice.

## Step 4: Visit a Tax Collector or Driver License Office

In Florida, most driver license services are handled by **county tax collector offices** rather than a standalone DMV. Make an appointment — walk-ins routinely face multi-hour waits. At the appointment, staff will verify your documents, check your TLSAE and knowledge-test results in the state system, take your photo, screen your vision and hearing, and issue your Learner''s License.

## Step 5: Hold the Permit and Log Your Hours

Once issued, the Learner''s License has restrictions: you may only drive with a **licensed driver 21 or older** in the front passenger seat. For the **first three months**, driving is limited to **daylight hours only**. After three months, you may drive until **10 p.m.**

You must hold the learner''s license for at least **12 months** (or until age 18, whichever comes first) and complete **50 hours of supervised driving, including 10 hours at night**, certified by your parent or guardian on Form HSMV 71142. Bring the completed form to your road-test appointment.

Do not lose the form. Tax collector offices will not accept verbal claims of practice hours, and missing or incomplete forms are one of the most common reasons teens are turned away on road-test day.', 35, 0
);
