INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_fl_getting-your-florida-learners-license_4', 'quiz_fl_getting-your-florida-learners-license', 'During the first three months of holding a Florida Learner''s License, when may the learner drive?', '["Anytime, with no time restrictions","Daylight hours only","Until 10 p.m.","Until midnight on weekends"]', 1, 'For the first three months, learners may only drive during daylight hours. After three months, they may drive until 10 p.m.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_fl_florida-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_fl_overlay', 'florida-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Living With Florida''s GDL Restrictions', '# Living With Florida''s GDL Restrictions

Florida''s Graduated Driver License (GDL) program does not end the day you swap your learner''s license for a Class E license. Restrictions follow you until your **18th birthday**, and they touch everyday decisions like driving to a late shift, taking friends to the beach, or heading home from a football game. Understanding the rules — and the exceptions — will help you avoid tickets, insurance surcharges, and the suspension of a license you just worked a year to earn.

## The Core Nighttime Rules

Florida''s nighttime driving rules are **tied to your age**, not to how long you have held your license:

- **Age 16:** You may not drive between **11 p.m. and 6 a.m.**
- **Age 17:** You may not drive between **1 a.m. and 5 a.m.**

There are two main exceptions. You may drive during the restricted hours if you are:

1. **Accompanied by a licensed driver who is 21 or older** seated in the front passenger seat, or
2. **Driving directly to or from work.**

The "to or from work" exception is narrow. It does not cover stopping to pick up food, meeting friends after a shift, or running an errand on the way home. If a Florida Highway Patrol trooper pulls you over at 12:30 a.m. and your stated destination is not a workplace, expect a citation.

## Passengers

Unlike many states, **Florida''s GDL does not impose a specific passenger limit** on newly licensed teens. You may legally drive friends or siblings around. However, every passenger must be properly restrained, and any passenger under 18 in the front seat must be wearing a seatbelt — this is a primary offense, meaning law enforcement can stop you for that alone.

## Cell Phones and Distractions

Florida''s **Wireless Communications While Driving Law** bans **texting while driving** for every driver. It became a primary offense in 2019, meaning officers can pull you over solely for texting. In addition, **hand-held use** of a wireless device — including phone calls — is illegal in any **school zone or active work zone**. For teens, the practical advice is simple: put the phone in Do Not Disturb mode and stash it before you start the engine. A single distracted-driving citation can raise your insurance for years.

## Seat Belts

Florida law requires all front-seat occupants and all passengers under 18 to wear a seatbelt. For a teen driver, an unbuckled passenger under 18 is **your** ticket, not theirs. Make it a habit to look around before shifting into drive.

## What Happens If You Get a Ticket

Teen drivers in Florida face heightened consequences for moving violations. A driver under 18 who accumulates **6 points within 12 months** is automatically restricted to **business-purposes-only driving** for a year. Six points adds up faster than you think: speeding 15+ mph over the limit alone is four points; a crash you cause is six. Reckless driving and racing carry mandatory license actions regardless of point totals.

## Putting It Together

Florida''s GDL rules are most easily summarized as: **drive sober, drive belted, drive phone-down, and watch the clock**. The nighttime windows tighten and loosen by age, not by months held, so a teen who waits until 17 to get licensed still inherits the 1 a.m. cutoff. Plan rides home from late events accordingly, and never assume "I was almost home" will satisfy a trooper.', 30, 1
);
