INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_fl_florida-specific-road-rules-and-quirks', 'module_fl_overlay', 'florida-specific-road-rules-and-quirks', 'Florida-Specific Road Rules and Quirks', '# Florida-Specific Road Rules and Quirks

Florida''s roads carry a unique mix of tourist traffic, sudden weather, and laws that often surprise new drivers — even those who grew up here. This lesson covers the rules and conditions that show up on Florida road tests, in Florida crash reports, and in everyday driving that you will not necessarily learn from a generic national curriculum.

## The Move Over Law

Florida''s **Move Over Act** is one of the strictest in the country. When you approach **any stationary emergency vehicle, tow truck, sanitation vehicle, road or bridge maintenance vehicle, or utility vehicle** with flashing lights on the shoulder, you must:

- On a road with **two or more lanes** in your direction, **change lanes away** from the stopped vehicle as soon as it is safe.
- If you cannot safely change lanes (or are on a two-lane road), **slow to 20 mph below the posted speed limit**. If the limit is 20 mph or less, slow to **5 mph**.

Violations carry fines and three points on your license. Florida added garbage trucks and utility vehicles to the law in recent years, so the rule covers more than just police cruisers.

## Hurricane Season and Evacuation Driving

Florida''s hurricane season runs **June 1 through November 30**. During declared evacuations, the governor can authorize **shoulder use** and **contraflow** (reversing inbound lanes to outbound) on major interstates like I-75 and the Florida Turnpike. As a new driver, three rules matter:

1. **Obey all directional signs and law-enforcement officers**, even when they contradict normal lane markings.
2. **Top off fuel before the rush** — stations run dry quickly during mandatory evacuations.
3. **Never drive through standing water.** "Turn Around, Don''t Drown" is the Florida slogan. Six inches of moving water can sweep a car off the road; two feet will float most vehicles.

## Toll Roads and SunPass

Florida has a vast tolled highway network — the Turnpike, the Veterans Expressway, parts of I-95 express lanes, and many bridges. Most are **all-electronic** with no cash booths. If you pass through a toll without a **SunPass** transponder, the system photographs your license plate and bills the registered owner via **Toll-By-Plate**, typically with a surcharge. Borrowing a parent''s car without a transponder can easily generate a notice three weeks later.

## Yielding to Pedestrians and Cyclists

Florida consistently ranks among the most dangerous states for pedestrians and cyclists. State law requires drivers to **yield to pedestrians in any marked or unmarked crosswalk**, and to give cyclists **at least 3 feet of clearance** when passing. When making a right turn on red, you must come to a complete stop and check the crosswalk before proceeding.

## Funeral Processions, School Buses, and Headlights

- **Funeral processions** have the right of way through intersections once the lead vehicle has entered legally; do not break the line.
- **School buses:** On a two-way road with no divider, traffic in **both directions** must stop when a bus has its stop arm extended. On a divided highway with a raised barrier or unpaved median of at least 5 feet, only traffic **behind** the bus must stop.
- **Headlights** must be on from sunset to sunrise, in any weather condition that limits visibility to 1,000 feet, **and whenever windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to rain or fog. Daytime running lights alone do not satisfy this rule because they typically do not turn on the taillights.

## Wildlife and the "Florida Sun"

Florida''s flat geography means sun glare during morning and evening commutes can be blinding, particularly on east-west roads. Keep a clean windshield, a pair of polarized sunglasses in the car, and your visor accessible. Watch for alligators crossing rural roads near water, deer in the Panhandle, and panthers in the southwest — wildlife strikes are common and often deadly to the animal and the car.', 30, 2
);
