INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ga_how-to-get-a-georgia-permit', 'module_ga_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-georgia-permit', 'How to Get Your Class CP Permit in Georgia', '# How to Get Your Class CP Permit in Georgia

In Georgia, the first step toward a driver''s license is the **Class CP Instructional Permit**, issued by the **Georgia Department of Driver Services (DDS)**. Unlike some states that issue a learner''s permit at 14 or 14½, Georgia requires you to be at least **15 years old** to apply, and you must hold that permit for a full **12 months and 1 day** without any major traffic convictions before you can move up to a Class D provisional license.

## Who must be with you when you apply

If you are under 18, a **parent, legal guardian, or responsible adult over 21** must accompany you to a DDS Customer Service Center and sign the **Responsible Adult Affidavit**. That adult is taking on financial responsibility for you behind the wheel, so this is not a formality — they have to show up in person, present their own ID, and sign in front of a DDS examiner.

## Documents to bring

Georgia uses a **5 Document ID Requirement** built around federal REAL ID standards. You''ll need to bring originals (no photocopies) proving:

1. **Identity** — certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or approved immigration document.
2. **Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN.
3. **Two proofs of Georgia residency** — utility bill, bank statement, school record, or a parent''s documents paired with a parental-residency affidavit if you live with them.
4. **Proof of name change** (only if your current legal name differs from your birth certificate) — marriage license, court order, etc.
5. **Proof of school enrollment / attendance (Certificate of Attendance)** — required for all applicants under 18 under Georgia''s TADRA law. Your school counselor''s office issues this form, and it must be **dated within 30 days** of your DDS visit.

## The tests you will take

At the DDS office you will complete three checks:

- **Vision screening** — read a line on the eye chart with corrective lenses if you wear them.
- **Knowledge test (Road Rules)** — 20 multiple-choice questions on Georgia traffic law. You must get **15 correct (75%)**.
- **Knowledge test (Road Signs)** — 20 questions identifying standard signs. You must get **15 correct (75%)**.

Study from the current **Georgia Driver''s Manual**, which DDS publishes free online. The DDS also offers an official practice-test app and the optional **Online Permit Test** for residents who prefer to test at home before visiting an office.

## After you pass

You''ll pay the **$10 permit fee** (subject to change), have your photo taken, and walk out with a temporary paper permit; the plastic card arrives in the mail within about 30 days. From that moment, the **12-month-and-1-day clock starts**. Any conviction for a major violation during that year — speeding 24+ mph over the limit, racing, reckless driving, or a DUI — **restarts the clock**.

## What the permit lets you do

The Class CP permit lets you drive **only** when a licensed driver who is at least 21 years old (or a Georgia-licensed driving instructor) is seated in the front passenger seat. You may not drive alone, and the supervising adult must be alert and unimpaired. Use this year wisely: log every practice hour, vary your routes (highway, night, rain, parking lots), and build the **40 hours of supervised practice (6 at night)** required by Joshua''s Law before your Class D road test.', 35, 0
);
