INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ga_georgia-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ga_overlay', 'georgia-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Georgia GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Georgia GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Getting your Class D provisional license is a milestone, but in Georgia the law treats new teen drivers as a higher-risk group — and the **Teenage and Adult Driver Responsibility Act (TADRA)** wraps several restrictions around that Class D that look very different from a full Class C adult license. Knowing how those restrictions play out in real situations — Friday nights, ride-share invites, late shifts — keeps you legal and on track to upgrade to a full license at 18.

## The nighttime curfew

Class D drivers under 18 **may not drive between 12:00 a.m. and 6:00 a.m.** There are **no exceptions**. Many other states carve out exemptions for work, school events, or medical emergencies. Georgia does not. If your shift at the restaurant ends at 11:30 p.m. and you sit in the parking lot until 12:05 a.m., you are now in violation the moment you pull onto the road. Plan ahead: leave earlier, have a parent pick you up, or have a friend with a full Class C license drive.

## The passenger rule — three phases

Georgia phases passengers in over the first 12 months of holding a Class D:

- **Months 0–6:** No passengers other than members of your immediate family (parents, siblings, step-siblings, grandparents, spouses, children).
- **Months 6–12:** You may have **one** non-family passenger under age 21.
- **After 12 months (still under 18):** You may have up to **three** non-family passengers under age 21.

Passengers age 21 and older never count against your limit. Your siblings never count. But that carload of teammates you want to drive to the game in the first six months? Not legal until you''ve had your Class D for half a year.

## The cell-phone rule for teens

Every licensed driver in Georgia is subject to the **Hands-Free Georgia Act**, which forbids holding a phone while driving. Drivers under 18, however, face a stricter standard: **no wireless device use at all**, including hands-free, Bluetooth, voice-to-text, or speakerphone. The only exception is reporting an emergency. Even using a navigation app counts if it requires you to interact with the device while moving. Mount the phone, set the route before you shift into Drive, and don''t touch it again until you''ve parked.

## Seat belts and passengers in pickup beds

Georgia requires **all occupants under 18** to wear a seat belt in every seating position. Children under 8 must be in an age- and size-appropriate child restraint in the back seat. Riding in the open bed of a pickup truck is illegal for anyone under 18 on any road in Georgia (with narrow agricultural exceptions on farm property). As the driver, you are responsible for compliance — tickets go on **your** record.

## Consequences that bite

Under TADRA, certain convictions while you hold a Class CP or Class D **suspend your license automatically** — no warning, no points-style buildup. These include hit-and-run, racing, fleeing an officer, reckless driving, any drug offense (even one not involving a vehicle), and speeding 24+ mph over the limit. A single suspension can also **reset your 12-month permit clock** and disqualify you from the Class D bump-up. The takeaway: in your first two years of driving, the cost of one careless choice is measured in months, not dollars.

## Living with the rules

The restrictions lift at age 18, when you automatically convert to a Class C license. Until then, build habits — early departures, phone mounted and silenced, friends meeting you at the destination instead of riding along — that match the law. Drivers who treat the curfew and passenger rules as personal policy (not just legal minimums) post dramatically lower crash rates in their first year. That''s the entire point of Georgia''s GDL system.', 30, 1
);
