INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ga_georgia-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ga_overlay', 'georgia-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Georgia-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Georgia-Specific Rules and Quirks

Most of what you study in the national driver-ed curriculum applies in Georgia, but several rules are uniquely Georgian — either because the state legislature passed something stricter than the national norm, or because the geography and traffic patterns demanded a local answer. Knowing these saves you from preventable tickets and crashes.

## Joshua''s Law: the 30 + 40 + 6 rule

Named for Joshua Brown, a teenager killed in a 2003 crash, **Joshua''s Law** requires every applicant **under age 17** seeking a Class D license to complete:

- **30 hours of approved classroom driver education**, AND
- **40 hours of supervised driving practice** — at least **6 of which must be at night** — certified on **DDS Form DS-1** by a parent or guardian.

If you wait until you''re 17 or older to apply for Class D, Joshua''s Law no longer applies — but you still need 12 months and 1 day on the permit. Most Georgia families choose the Joshua''s Law route because insurance carriers offer steep discounts to teens with a certified driver-ed completion.

## Super Speeders

Georgia is one of the few states with a **Super Speeder law**. If you''re convicted of driving **75 mph or more on a two-lane road**, or **85 mph or more on any road**, the state tacks on an **additional $200 fee** on top of your local court fine. Miss that fee for 120 days and your license is suspended with an extra $50 reinstatement fee. For a teen driver, that single conviction can also trigger TADRA suspension.

## Move Over Law

Georgia''s Move Over Law requires drivers approaching any stationary emergency, utility, sanitation, **HERO (Highway Emergency Response Operator)**, or tow vehicle displaying flashing lights to **move one lane away** from the vehicle if safely possible. If traffic prevents a lane change, you must slow to a speed below the posted limit and be prepared to stop. Violations carry fines up to $500.

## Slowpoke Law (left-lane rule)

On interstates and limited-access highways with two or more lanes in each direction, Georgia law forbids driving in the **far-left lane** slower than the surrounding flow of traffic. The left lane is for passing. If a faster driver approaches behind you, you must move right — even if you''re already at the speed limit. This is one of the most ticketed rules on I-75 and I-285.

## HOV and HOT lanes around Atlanta

If you''ll be driving anywhere near metro Atlanta, you''ll encounter **HOV (High-Occupancy Vehicle)** lanes on I-75, I-85, and I-285. Most require **2 or more occupants** during operating hours; some sections are **HOT (High-Occupancy Toll)** lanes where solo drivers can buy in via a **Peach Pass** transponder. Crossing the solid double-white line to enter or exit between designated openings is a violation. Read the signs carefully — fines are stiff and cameras are everywhere.

## Headlights, wipers, and weather

Georgia requires headlights **30 minutes after sunset to 30 minutes before sunrise** and **any time visibility is less than 500 feet** — but also any time your **windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to rain, snow, or fog. Daytime running lights do not satisfy this rule; your full headlights must be on.

## School buses on divided highways

Most states require all directions of traffic to stop for a school bus with flashing red lights. Georgia is more nuanced: on a **divided highway with a physical median or barrier**, only traffic following the bus and traffic in lanes traveling the **same direction** must stop. Oncoming traffic separated by a median may proceed with caution. A painted center line or two-way left-turn lane does NOT count as a divided highway — in that case, **all** directions stop.

## DUI for under-21 drivers

The legal **BAC limit is 0.08** for adults, but Georgia''s **Zero Tolerance** law sets it at **0.02** for drivers under 21. A first conviction means a **6-month license suspension** plus the standard DUI penalties. Combine that with TADRA''s automatic suspension trigger for any drug offense, and the lesson is simple: in Georgia, under 21, the only safe number is zero.', 30, 2
);
