INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_hi_hawaii-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_hi_overlay', 'hawaii-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Hawaii GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Hawaii GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

The Hawaii **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** system is built around the idea that crash risk drops dramatically as new drivers gain experience in lower-risk conditions before facing higher-risk ones. The rules look simple on paper, but they shape almost every decision a teen driver makes — from when you can go to a beach bonfire to who can ride home with you after volleyball practice.

## The three GDL stages

1. **Instruction Permit** — minimum age 15.5; must be supervised at all times by a licensed adult 21+ in the front seat.
2. **Provisional License** — minimum age 16, after holding a permit at least 180 days and completing 50 hours of supervised practice. Carries night and passenger restrictions.
3. **Full (unrestricted) License** — minimum age 17, after holding a Provisional License for at least 180 days conviction-free.

This lesson focuses on what life looks like during the **Provisional** stage, because that is when most teens are actually driving solo.

## The nighttime restriction

Provisional license holders under 18 **may not drive between 11:00 PM and 5:00 AM**. There are narrow exceptions:

- A licensed parent or legal guardian is in the front passenger seat.
- You are driving directly to or from **work**, **school**, or a **school-sanctioned event**, and you carry documentation (pay stub, schedule, or note).
- You are responding to a documented **emergency**.

"My friend''s curfew got extended" is not an exception. Hawaii Police Department officers are familiar with provisional plates and license formats, and a violation can extend the provisional period and add fines.

## The passenger restriction

Provisional drivers under 18 **may not carry passengers under 18** other than immediate family members unless a licensed parent/guardian 21+ is also in the car. "Immediate family" means siblings, step-siblings, and others living in your household — not cousins, not classmates, not teammates.

This is the rule teens break most often, usually without thinking. A common scenario: practice ends, three friends need a ride to Zippy''s, you all live nearby. Under Hawaii law, you can take exactly **zero** of them unless one is your sibling. If you wouldn''t pick up a friend in front of a police officer, don''t pick them up at all.

## The cell phone rule that surprises everyone

Hawaii bans **handheld** device use for all drivers. But for drivers **under 18**, the rule is stricter: **no mobile electronic device use of any kind**, including hands-free and Bluetooth. The only exception is calling 911 in an emergency. That means:

- No Spotify changes from your phone, even if it is mounted and you tap the screen at a red light.
- No navigation tapping mid-trip — set the route before you shift into drive.
- No CarPlay/Android Auto interactions that count as "using" the device.
- Yes, this applies even when the car is stopped at a light. "Operating" includes being in control of a vehicle on a public roadway.

Fines start around $250 and increase in school and construction zones.

## Seat belts and passengers

Hawaii has a **primary seat belt law** — officers can stop you for an unbelted occupant alone. Children under 4 must be in a child safety seat; ages 4–7 require a booster unless they meet height/weight thresholds. As the driver, **you are legally responsible** for all passengers under 18 being properly restrained.

## Consequences of violations

A moving violation, GDL restriction violation, or at-fault crash during the Provisional stage typically:

- **Extends** the 180-day Provisional period — the clock restarts from the violation date.
- Adds **points** to your driving record (Hawaii uses an abstract/conviction system rather than formal points, but insurers and the court track each conviction).
- Can trigger **license suspension**, especially for any alcohol-related offense (Hawaii''s under-21 limit is **0.02% BAC**, effectively zero tolerance).

The GDL rules can feel inconvenient, but they exist because 16- and 17-year-old drivers crash at roughly three times the rate of drivers over 20. Following them isn''t just about avoiding tickets — it''s the actual mechanism by which you become a safer driver.', 40, 1
);
