INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_hi_hawaii-specific-road-rules-and-quirks', 'module_hi_overlay', 'hawaii-specific-road-rules-and-quirks', 'Hawaii-Specific Road Rules and Island Quirks', '# Hawaii-Specific Road Rules and Island Quirks

Driving in Hawaii is genuinely different from driving on the mainland. Roads are narrower, weather changes in minutes, the culture around horn-honking is unique, and a handful of state-specific laws routinely catch visitors and new drivers off guard. This lesson covers the rules and habits that make a driver actually competent in the islands.

## Speed limits and the "55 max" reality

Hawaii has one of the **lowest maximum speed limits** in the country: **60 mph on the H-1, H-2, and H-3 freeways on Oahu**, and **55 mph on essentially every other state highway**. Many rural two-lane roads are posted at **35–45 mph**. There are no 70 or 75 mph zones anywhere in the state. Speeding more than **30 mph over the limit** — or driving over **80 mph anywhere** — is **Excessive Speeding**, a *criminal* offense (not a regular traffic infraction) that can mean court appearance, license suspension, and even jail time for repeat offenses.

## Horn etiquette

On the mainland, a horn often means anger. In Hawaii, **horns are largely reserved for emergencies and accident-avoidance**. Honking at someone who is slow off a green light is considered extremely rude and aggressive. The cultural norm is patience: people stop to let cars merge, they wave "shaka" thanks, and drivers behind them wait without honking. Adopt the local pace — you will get there.

## One-lane bridges and yielding

Many roads — especially the **Hana Highway on Maui**, the **Hamakua Coast on Hawaii Island**, and the **north shore of Kauai** — have **one-lane bridges**. Standard rule: the **first vehicle to arrive crosses first**, but if a line has formed on the opposite side, you wait until that line clears, then your side proceeds as a group of **five to seven cars**. Watch the locals and follow their lead — never race a bridge.

## Pedestrians and the crosswalk law

Hawaii has a **very strong pedestrian right-of-way law**. Drivers must **stop and remain stopped** for pedestrians in any crosswalk (marked or unmarked) on the driver''s half of the roadway, plus when the pedestrian is approaching close enough to be in danger. Honolulu enforces this aggressively, with regular sting operations using plainclothes pedestrians. Fines start at $150 and climb sharply.

## Vog, rain, and rainbows

- **Vog** (volcanic smog from Kilauea on Hawaii Island) can drift across all islands, reducing visibility and irritating eyes. Treat it like fog: lower beams on, reduce speed, increase following distance.
- **Trade-wind showers** are intense and brief. Roads can go from dry to flooded in under a minute. Hawaii pavement, especially older asphalt with embedded coral, becomes **extremely slick in the first few minutes of rain** as oils rise. Slow down meaningfully.
- **Rainbows are not a reason to stop in the road.** Pull off completely.

## Flash flooding and gulches

Hawaii has more **flash flood**-related driving deaths per capita than most states. The classic cause: a driver enters a low-water crossing or gulch road with shallow-looking flowing water. **Turn around, don''t drown** — six inches of moving water can sweep a small car. Pay attention to flash flood warnings, especially on windward sides.

## Lava zones and active volcanic hazards (Hawaii Island)

If you drive on Hawaii Island, eruption activity can close roads with little notice. **Never drive across or near active flows**, and respect **road closure signs** even if you can see other cars beyond them — those are often emergency personnel.

## Honu (sea turtles), nene (geese), and feral animals

- Federally protected **Hawaiian green sea turtles** sometimes cross coastal roads. Stop, do not honk, and give them space.
- **Nene**, the state bird, are common road-crossers on Hawaii Island, Maui, and Kauai. They are slow and endangered — hitting one is a federal offense.
- Feral pigs, chickens, and dogs are common, especially at dawn and dusk.

## Documents to carry

Hawaii requires drivers to carry their **license, current registration, and proof of no-fault insurance** at all times. Hawaii is a **no-fault insurance state**, meaning your own policy pays your medical bills regardless of who caused a minor crash. Driving uninsured carries fines of **$500 and up** and possible license suspension.

## The bottom line

Islands are small but the roads are demanding. Lower speeds, gentler temperaments, and respect for the land and other drivers are not just cultural niceties — they are the rules of the road in Hawaii.', 40, 2
);
