INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ia_iowa-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_ia_overlay', 'iowa-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Iowa GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Living With Iowa''s Graduated Driver Licensing Rules

Getting your Iowa Intermediate License at 16 is a huge milestone, but the law still places real limits on when and how you can drive until you turn 17 and get a full license. These rules are called **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** restrictions, and Iowa law enforcement takes them seriously. This lesson translates the rulebook into the situations you''ll actually face.

## The intermediate license at a glance

After holding an Iowa Instruction Permit for 12 months without convictions and passing the behind-the-wheel road test, a 16-year-old can get an **Intermediate License**. This license lets you drive alone, but with three big categories of restrictions: **nighttime hours, passengers, and electronic devices.**

## Nighttime driving

From **12:30 a.m. to 5:00 a.m.**, an Iowa intermediate driver may not be behind the wheel unless one of these exceptions applies:

- A parent, guardian, or licensed driver age 21+ is riding in the front seat.
- You''re driving directly to or from work.
- You''re driving directly to or from a school or school-sponsored event.
- You''re driving for an authorized religious or charitable activity.

Real-life example: leaving a friend''s house at 1:00 a.m. on a Saturday isn''t allowed. Leaving your closing shift at the grocery store at 1:00 a.m. and driving straight home is allowed. If you get pulled over after midnight, expect the officer to ask where you''re coming from and where you''re going.

## Passenger limits

For the **first 6 months** of your intermediate license, you can transport **no more than one unrelated minor passenger** unless a parent, guardian, or licensed driver age 21+ is in the front seat. Family members (siblings, cousins who live with you) generally don''t count toward the limit, but unrelated friends do.

Why this matters: research consistently shows that crash risk for teen drivers multiplies with each additional teen passenger. Iowa''s law is designed to protect both you and your friends.

After 6 months of clean driving (no convictions), the passenger restriction lifts automatically - you do not have to file paperwork.

## Phones and electronic devices

Iowa is strict about distracted driving for teens:

- If you are **under 18** and hold a permit, school license, or intermediate license, you may **not use any handheld electronic communication or entertainment device** while driving. That includes phones, tablets, gaming devices, and music players.
- **Texting while driving is illegal for everyone** in Iowa, regardless of age.
- Iowa''s **hands-free law** (effective in 2025) prohibits all drivers from holding a phone while driving. You can use Bluetooth, a dashboard mount, or voice controls, but the phone cannot be in your hand.

A single phone-related citation can extend your GDL restrictions and may delay your full license.

## Seat belts and passengers

Iowa law requires every occupant in the front seat to wear a seat belt, and all passengers under 18 must be belted regardless of where they sit. As the driver, you can be ticketed for an unbelted minor passenger.

## What happens if you get a ticket

A moving violation conviction during your intermediate license phase can:

- Reset the 6-month clean-driving window required before passenger limits lift.
- Delay your full license eligibility past age 17.
- Trigger driver improvement requirements or license suspension for repeated offenses.

## When restrictions end

At age **17**, after holding the intermediate license without disqualifying convictions, Iowa drivers can upgrade to a **full unrestricted license**. The nighttime, passenger, and youth phone rules drop away - but the texting ban and hands-free rules continue to apply to every driver on the road.

Live within the rules for one year and you''ll graduate with both a clean record and the habits that keep you alive on Iowa roads.', 40, 1
);
