INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ia_iowa-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ia_overlay', 'iowa-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Iowa-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Iowa Road Rules You Won''t Find Everywhere

Every state has a handful of laws and driving situations that surprise newcomers. Iowa is no exception. Whether it''s the state''s distinctive **Minor School License**, the rules of a four-way stop in a small town, or how to share a rural highway with a tractor, this lesson covers the Iowa quirks that often catch new drivers off guard.

## The Minor School License (school permit)

Iowa is one of a small group of states that issues a **Minor School License** to students roughly age 14 and 6 months and older who live more than one mile from their school. With a school license you can drive:

- Directly between your home and your school.
- To and from school-approved extracurricular activities along designated routes.
- During hours approved by school officials.

To qualify, you need parental and school approval, completion of an approved driver education course, and a clean driving record. Violating the school license restrictions can lead to revocation and delay your standard licensing path.

## Move Over Law

Iowa''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers approaching any stationary emergency vehicle, tow truck, utility vehicle, or maintenance vehicle with flashing lights to:

- Move to a non-adjacent lane if you can do so safely, or
- Slow down well below the speed limit if moving over isn''t possible.

This applies on all roads, not just interstates. Fines escalate sharply if a worker or first responder is injured.

## Rural roads, gravel, and farm equipment

More than 60% of Iowa''s roads are rural, and many are gravel or chip-sealed. Key habits:

- **Reduce speed on gravel.** Loose surfaces dramatically lengthen stopping distance and reduce steering control. Pass oncoming vehicles slowly to avoid windshield damage from kicked-up rocks.
- **Watch for farm equipment.** Tractors, combines, and grain wagons often travel 15-25 mph and may take up part of your lane. The orange triangle (''slow-moving vehicle'' emblem) is your warning. Never pass on a hill, curve, or near a field entrance - the farmer may turn left into a field without warning.
- **Yield at uncontrolled rural intersections.** Many gravel-road intersections have no signs at all. Treat them as yield situations, slow significantly, and look both ways.

## Severe weather

Iowa drivers face all four seasons in extreme form:

- **Winter:** black ice, blowing snow, and ground blizzards can drop visibility to zero. Iowa DOT''s 511ia.org provides real-time road conditions. State law allows authorities to ban non-essential travel during severe storms.
- **Spring/summer:** thunderstorms, hail, and tornadoes. If you encounter a tornado warning, exit the highway and seek a sturdy building - do not shelter under an overpass.
- **Fall:** deer collisions peak in October and November. Use high beams when safe, scan ditches, and brake firmly if you see one deer (others usually follow).

## Headlights and wipers

Iowa law requires headlights from sunset to sunrise and any time visibility is less than 500 feet. If your **windshield wipers are on due to weather, your headlights must also be on** - a common ''wipers-on, lights-on'' rule that catches many new drivers.

## Bicycles and pedestrians

Bicycles are vehicles in Iowa and have the same right to the road. When passing a cyclist you must leave a safe distance (best practice and required equipment such as the ''Iowa Three Feet Please'' campaign guidance: give at least three feet). RAGBRAI, the annual cross-state bicycle ride, briefly turns rural highways into bike highways every July - plan ahead.

## Seat belts and child restraints

Iowa is a **primary seat belt state** for front-seat occupants, meaning an officer can pull you over solely for an unbelted driver or front passenger. All children under 18 must be properly restrained, and children under age 1 (or under 20 lbs) must be in a rear-facing child safety seat.

## Open container and alcohol

Iowa has a **zero-tolerance law** for drivers under 21: a blood alcohol concentration of 0.02% or higher triggers license suspension. Open alcohol containers in the passenger area of any vehicle are illegal, even for adults.

Understanding these Iowa-specific details will keep you safer and keep your license clean as you progress through the GDL system.', 35, 2
);
