INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_id_how-to-get-an-idaho-permit_4', 'quiz_id_how-to-get-an-idaho-permit', 'Who must accompany an Idaho SIP holder when driving?', '["Any licensed driver age 18 or older","A licensed driver age 21 or older, seated in the front passenger seat","A parent or legal guardian only","A certified driving instructor only"]', 1, 'A SIP holder must drive with a licensed driver at least 21 years old seated in the front passenger seat — not a parent specifically, but they must be 21+.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_id_idaho-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_id_overlay', 'idaho-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Idaho GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Idaho GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Passing the skills test and getting your Idaho driver''s license at 15 does **not** give you full driving privileges. Idaho operates a **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** system designed to ease new drivers into the riskiest situations — nighttime driving, peer passengers, and distractions — gradually. These restrictions stay in place until you turn **17**, no matter how skilled you become.

Understanding what you can and can''t do, day to day, helps you avoid tickets that could cost you your license — and helps your family plan around your driving.

## The nighttime restriction

Idaho restricts drivers under 17 from driving between **sunset and sunrise** unless accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older in the front passenger seat. Note that this is **sunset**, not a fixed clock time like 10 p.m. or midnight — which means the restriction window stretches longer in winter and shrinks in summer. In Boise in December, sunset is around 5:10 p.m.; in late June it''s nearly 9:30 p.m.

Practical examples:
- A 16-year-old who finishes a study session at the library at 6 p.m. on a December evening is already driving illegally if they''re alone.
- The same drive in June would be fine until well after 9 p.m.
- A high school basketball game ending at 10 p.m. in February requires a 21+ supervisor for the ride home.

There are limited exceptions for driving to or from authorized employment or a school-sanctioned activity, but you should carry documentation (a work schedule, a coach''s note) if you rely on these exceptions.

## The passenger restriction

During the **first 6 months** after getting your driver''s license, drivers under 17 may not transport **more than one passenger under age 17** who is not an immediate family member. ''Immediate family'' means siblings, stepsiblings, or other minors who live in your household.

Why this rule exists: national crash data show that a teen driver''s fatal crash risk roughly doubles with one teen passenger and quadruples with three or more. Idaho''s GDL aligns with that research.

Practical examples:
- You can drive your two younger siblings to school — both are immediate family.
- You can drive one friend to soccer practice — one non-family minor is allowed.
- You cannot drive three friends to a movie — that''s three non-family minors.
- After six violation-free months, the passenger restriction lifts (though the nighttime restriction continues until age 17).

## The cell phone rule

Idaho has a **statewide handheld device ban** for all drivers — not just teens. You may not hold a phone to talk, text, scroll, navigate, or take a video while driving. Hands-free use (Bluetooth, dashboard mount with voice commands) is allowed for adults, and emergency 911 calls are always allowed.

For SIP and GDL-restricted drivers, the safest and clearest standard is **no phone use at all** while the vehicle is in motion. Pull into a parking lot if you need to text, check directions, or change music.

First offense for handheld use is a fine (currently around $75); second and third offenses escalate quickly and can include points on your driving record.

## Zero tolerance for alcohol

Idaho enforces a **0.02% BAC** limit for drivers under 21. Practically, that''s zero tolerance — even a single drink can trigger a license suspension. For SIP and GDL drivers, any alcohol-related offense also resets your eligibility for an unrestricted license.

## Seat belts and child passengers

Idaho law requires all front-seat occupants to wear seat belts and all passengers under 18 to be belted, regardless of seating position. As the driver, **you are responsible** for every minor in your vehicle being properly restrained — even if they''re old enough to buckle themselves.

## Violations and consequences

Any moving violation during the GDL period can:
- Reset the 6-month clean record needed to remove the passenger restriction.
- Trigger a mandatory driver-improvement course.
- Result in a license suspension at 3 violations within 12 months for drivers under 17.

The simplest rule: **drive like every trip is being graded** — because for the first year or two, it effectively is.', 40, 1
);
