INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_il_how-to-get-an-illinois-instruction-permit', 'module_il_overlay', 'how-to-get-an-illinois-instruction-permit', 'How to Get Your Illinois Instruction Permit', '# How to Get Your Illinois Instruction Permit

Getting your instruction permit in Illinois is the first major milestone in the Secretary of State''s Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) program. Unlike many states where you can walk into a DMV at 15 and take a knowledge test on the spot, Illinois requires that teens between the ages of 15 and 17 first enroll in and begin a state-approved driver education course before they can even apply for a permit.

## Step 1: Enroll in Driver Education

If you are 15, 16, or 17, you must be enrolled in a driver education program that meets Illinois Secretary of State standards. This program consists of two parts: **30 hours of classroom instruction** and **6 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW) training**. The course can be taken at your high school or through a commercial driving school licensed by the state.

You cannot apply for your instruction permit until you have completed **at least 15 hours** of the classroom portion. Your driver education school will provide you with a course completion verification document — often called a **"blue slip"** or driver education enrollment certificate — that you''ll bring to the Secretary of State facility.

## Step 2: Gather Your Documents

When you visit a Secretary of State Driver Services facility, you will need to bring:

- **Proof of identity** (such as a certified birth certificate or passport)
- **Proof of your Social Security Number** (Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub)
- **Proof of Illinois residency** (two documents such as a utility bill, bank statement, school transcript, or report card)
- **Proof of signature** (a signed credit card, school ID, or canceled check)
- **Parent or legal guardian signature** on the application — they must accompany you to the facility if you are under 18
- **Driver education enrollment verification** from your school

If your name differs from the name on your birth certificate (for example, due to a legal name change), you''ll also need certified documentation of that change.

## Step 3: Pass the Required Tests

At the facility, you will take three tests:

1. **Vision screening** — basic eye test to confirm you meet Illinois''s minimum visual acuity standards
2. **Written knowledge test** — multiple-choice exam covering traffic laws, road signs, and safe driving practices from the Illinois Rules of the Road manual
3. **Sign identification** — recognizing standard road signs by shape, color, and meaning

You will **not** take a road test at this stage; that comes later when you apply for your full license.

## Step 4: Pay the Fee and Get Your Permit

The instruction permit fee is **$20** (subject to change). Once issued, your permit is valid for **24 months**.

## Step 5: Begin the 9-Month Permit Holding Period

This is the rule that surprises many Illinois teens: you must hold your instruction permit for a **minimum of 9 months** without any traffic convictions before you are eligible to apply for an initial driver''s license. If you receive a moving violation conviction during this period, the 9-month clock effectively restarts from the date of the conviction.

During these 9 months, you must:

- Always drive with a licensed adult age 21 or older (parent, guardian, or driving instructor) in the front passenger seat
- Log a minimum of **50 hours of supervised practice driving**, with at least **10 of those hours at night**
- Comply with all GDL nighttime curfew and passenger restrictions even while on the permit
- Wear a seatbelt and ensure all passengers do as well

Your parent or guardian will be required to sign an affidavit confirming the practice hours when you apply for your license.

## Common Pitfalls to Avoid

- **Don''t forget the parent signature.** Many teens are turned away at the facility because a parent didn''t come along.
- **Track your practice hours carefully.** Use a printed log or an app — "I think we drove enough" won''t satisfy the SOS.
- **A single ticket can reset your clock.** Take the 9-month holding period seriously.

Once you have your permit in hand, you''re officially in Phase 1 of Illinois GDL. The next lessons will cover what daily life looks like under these restrictions.', 25, 0
);
