INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_il_illinois-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_il_overlay', 'illinois-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Illinois-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Driver Should Know', '# Illinois-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Driver Should Know

Illinois shares most of its traffic laws with neighboring states, but a handful of rules trip up new drivers — especially those who grew up watching family members drive in another state or who learned bad habits from out-of-state YouTube channels. This lesson covers the Illinois-specific quirks that show up most often on the written test and in real-world traffic stops.

## Scott''s Law — The "Move Over" Law

Named after Lieutenant Scott Gillen of the Chicago Fire Department, who was struck and killed by an intoxicated driver while assisting at a crash scene, **Scott''s Law** is one of the most aggressively enforced laws in Illinois.

When approaching **any stationary emergency vehicle, tow truck, or maintenance vehicle** with flashing lights, you must:

1. **Slow down**, and
2. **Change lanes** away from the stopped vehicle if it is safe to do so.

Violations carry fines starting at **$250** and going up to **$10,000**, plus possible license suspension — and if a violation causes injury or death to a responder, it becomes a felony. Illinois State Police make Scott''s Law enforcement a top priority, and dashcam footage from troopers regularly appears on the news featuring tickets issued for failure to move over.

## Right Turn on Red — Mostly, But Not in Chicago Loop

Like most states, Illinois generally allows right turns on red after a complete stop and after yielding to pedestrians and cross traffic. However:

- **Watch for posted "No Turn on Red" signs**, which are common at downtown intersections.
- **Many intersections in the Chicago Loop and dense urban corridors prohibit it.**
- **Left turn on red is only permitted from a one-way street onto another one-way street.**

## Snow and Winter Driving

Illinois winters are real winters — particularly north of I-80. A few rules and conventions to know:

- **Headlights must be on whenever windshield wipers are in continuous use** (rain, snow, fog). This is the law, not just a suggestion.
- During declared **snow emergencies in Chicago and other cities**, parking on designated snow routes is prohibited and your car will be towed.
- Carry an emergency kit (blanket, shovel, flashlight, jumper cables) from November through March.

## The DUI Threshold for Drivers Under 21

Illinois has a **zero tolerance** law for drivers under 21: any detectable alcohol (BAC of 0.00 with any trace amount) results in an automatic license suspension — **3 months for a first offense, 1 year for a second**. For drivers 21 and over, the legal limit is 0.08, but for under-21 drivers, even a sip of beer at a wedding can cost you your license.

There are no "I only had one" exceptions for teens. Refusing a chemical test as a minor results in an even longer suspension.

## School Bus Stops

When a school bus is stopped with its red lights flashing and stop arm extended:

- **On a two-lane road:** All traffic in both directions must stop.
- **On a road with four or more lanes, with at least two lanes traveling in your direction:** Only traffic moving in the same direction as the bus must stop. Oncoming traffic may proceed with caution.

This is one of the most commonly misunderstood rules. The fine for illegally passing a stopped school bus starts at **$300** for a first offense and includes a **3-month license suspension**.

## Funeral Processions Have Right of Way

Illinois law gives the lead vehicle of a funeral procession the right to proceed through intersections — even against a red light — as long as a lead vehicle has lawfully entered the intersection. Following vehicles in the procession (typically marked with flags or hazard lights) may follow without stopping. **Do not cut through a funeral procession.**

## Roundabouts

Illinois has been steadily adding roundabouts to replace traditional intersections, particularly in suburban Chicagoland and around the I-39 / I-88 corridors. Rules:

- **Yield to traffic already in the circle.**
- **Enter only when there''s a safe gap** — do not stop in the roundabout unless necessary.
- **Use your right turn signal as you exit.**
- **Never change lanes inside the roundabout.**

## Bicyclists and "Dutch Reach"

Illinois recognizes bicycles as vehicles. Drivers must:

- Give cyclists at least **3 feet of clearance** when passing.
- Yield to cyclists in marked bike lanes when turning across them.
- Check for cyclists before opening a parked car''s door (the "Dutch Reach" — using your far hand — is taught in IL driver ed for this reason).

Chicago especially has dense bike infrastructure and a corresponding number of car-door collisions every year. "Dooring" a cyclist is illegal and you can be cited.

## Quirks on the Written Test

The Illinois Rules of the Road manual loves to test these specific points:

- Exact curfew hours by day of week
- Scott''s Law specifics
- BAC limits by age
- School bus stop rules by road configuration
- Distances for headlight and turn signal use

Study these directly from the manual rather than from generic online quizzes — Illinois has its own wording.', 25, 2
);
