INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_in_how-to-get-an-indiana-learners-permit', 'module_in_overlay', 'how-to-get-an-indiana-learners-permit', 'How to Get an Indiana Learner''s Permit', '# How to Get an Indiana Learner''s Permit

In Indiana, your driving journey starts at the Bureau of Motor Vehicles (BMV) with a learner''s permit. The permit lets you practice driving on public roads as long as a qualified licensed driver is in the front passenger seat. Here is exactly what you need to know to walk out of the BMV branch with a permit in hand.

## Age requirements

- **Age 15:** You may apply for a learner''s permit if you are enrolled in an Indiana BMV-approved driver education course. Your driver ed school will provide a Certificate of Enrollment (sometimes called the CDE) that you bring to the BMV.
- **Age 16:** You may apply for a learner''s permit even without driver ed enrollment.

If you want to be licensed before your 18th birthday, you are required to complete an approved driver ed course (30 hours classroom + 6 hours behind-the-wheel), so most teens choose the age-15 path.

## What to bring to the BMV

Indiana follows federal REAL ID document rules. You need to present originals (no photocopies) of:

1. **Proof of identity** — certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or Permanent Resident Card.
2. **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN.
3. **Proof of lawful status** — usually covered by the identity document above.
4. **Two proofs of Indiana residency** — utility bill, bank statement, school record, or a parent''s documents with a notarized affidavit if you live with them.
5. **Parental consent** — if you are under 18, a parent or legal guardian must appear in person to sign the application, OR provide a notarized consent form.
6. **Certificate of Driver Education Enrollment** — required if you are 15.

## The tests you must pass

At the branch, you will take:

- A **vision screening** (20/40 in at least one eye, with corrective lenses if needed).
- A **written knowledge test** based on the Indiana Driver''s Manual — 50 questions covering road signs, traffic laws, and safe-driving practices. You must score at least 84% (no more than 8 wrong).

You''ll also have your photo taken and pay the permit fee (currently around $9).

## After you have your permit

With the permit you may drive only when:

- A licensed driver age 25 or older (or a certified driver-ed instructor) is in the front passenger seat, AND
- That supervising driver is not under the influence of alcohol or drugs.

You must hold the permit for **at least 180 days (6 months)** before you can be issued a probationary license, and during that time you must log **50 hours of supervised practice driving, including 10 hours at night.** A parent or guardian signs the log.

## Common reasons applications get rejected

- Bringing a photocopy of the birth certificate instead of the original.
- Forgetting the second residency document.
- A 15-year-old arriving without the Certificate of Driver Ed Enrollment.
- A parent who isn''t present and didn''t notarize the consent form.

Call ahead to your local branch or use the BMV Connect online appointment tool — Indiana BMV strongly prefers appointments and walk-ins can wait hours.

Once you pass, the permit is valid for two years. Plenty of time to practice safely and build the habits you''ll need for the road test.', 35, 0
);
