INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_in_indiana-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_in_overlay', 'indiana-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Indiana-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Indiana-Specific Rules and Quirks

Most driving rules are similar across the country, but every state has a few quirks that surprise new drivers — and Indiana is no exception. The rules below show up on the BMV knowledge test and, more importantly, in everyday Hoosier driving.

## Roundabouts: Indiana loves them

Carmel, Indiana, has the most roundabouts of any city in the United States, and roundabouts are exploding in popularity statewide. Key rules:

- **Yield to traffic already in the circle** — left-lane vehicles in a multi-lane roundabout have right of way.
- **No stopping inside the circle.** If an emergency vehicle approaches, exit the roundabout first, then pull over.
- **Use your right turn signal as you approach your exit** — this signals to other drivers that the gap is opening.
- **Trucks and trailers** may need the full width; give them room and don''t pass alongside them in a roundabout.

Expect at least one roundabout question on the BMV written test.

## Move Over Law

Indiana''s Move Over Law requires drivers to:

- **Change lanes away** from any stopped emergency, utility, or road-maintenance vehicle with flashing lights when safely possible, OR
- **Slow to at least 10 mph below the posted speed limit** if changing lanes is not safe.

The law was expanded in recent years to include tow trucks, utility trucks, and any vehicle displaying flashing amber lights — not just police and fire.

## School buses — extra strict in Indiana

When a school bus stops with its **stop arm extended and red lights flashing**:

- **On a two-lane road:** Traffic in **both directions must stop.**
- **On a divided highway with a physical barrier or unpaved median:** Only traffic traveling in the same direction as the bus must stop. Oncoming traffic across the barrier may proceed with caution.
- **A painted line or center turn lane does NOT count as a divider.** Both directions must still stop.

Indiana increased penalties for passing a stopped school bus following several high-profile tragedies. A first offense is a Class A infraction with a fine up to $10,000 and a 90-day license suspension; injuring a child is a felony.

## Headlights — Indiana''s "wipers-on, lights-on" rule

Indiana law requires headlights to be on:

- From **sunset to sunrise.**
- Anytime weather conditions require windshield wipers (rain, snow, sleet, fog).
- When visibility is less than 500 feet.

Daytime running lights alone do not satisfy this rule — your tail lights must also be on, which usually requires the full headlight switch.

## Railroad crossings

Indiana has thousands of at-grade rail crossings. Buses, vehicles transporting hazardous materials, and certain large vehicles must come to a full stop at every crossing. For passenger vehicles, you must stop at any crossing where:

- Gates are down,
- Lights are flashing,
- A signal person is flagging you down, or
- A train is visibly approaching.

Never attempt to drive around lowered gates — it is both illegal and frequently fatal.

## Implied consent and zero tolerance

By holding an Indiana driver''s license, you give **implied consent** to chemical testing (breath, blood, urine) if a law-enforcement officer has probable cause to suspect impaired driving. Refusal automatically suspends your license for at least one year, even if you are later found not guilty of OWI.

For drivers **under 21**, Indiana uses a **zero-tolerance** standard: a Blood Alcohol Concentration of **0.02% or higher** is grounds for an OWI charge. That''s roughly half of one drink. For drivers 21+, the limit is 0.08%.

## Right turn on red

Right turns on a red light are permitted statewide after coming to a complete stop, unless a sign specifically prohibits it. **Left turn on red is permitted only from a one-way street onto another one-way street.**

## Indiana plates and registration

Indiana requires both front and rear license plates... actually no — Indiana is a **rear plate only** state. Don''t drill mounting holes in your front bumper. Your registration sticker goes on the rear plate, top-right corner.

Know these quirks and you''ll drive like a lifelong Hoosier — and pass your test the first time.', 30, 2
);
