INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ks_kansas-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ks_overlay', 'kansas-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living With Kansas GDL Restrictions', '# Living With Kansas GDL Restrictions

Getting your Kansas Restricted License is exciting, but it comes with real limits that shape your daily life. Understanding these restrictions — and planning for them — keeps you legal, keeps your parents trusting you, and keeps your license in your wallet.

## The three GDL stages

Kansas''s Graduated Driver Licensing system has three stages:

1. **Instruction Permit** (age 14+) — supervised driving only.
2. **Restricted License** (age 15 with driver ed, or 16 without) — limited solo driving.
3. **Full (Unrestricted) License** (age 16.5+ with one year of clean restricted driving, or age 17) — full driving privileges.

This lesson focuses on the Restricted License stage — what you can and cannot do once you''re driving alone.

## Nighttime restriction

If you hold a Kansas Restricted License, you **cannot drive between 9:00 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.** unless you are:

- Going directly to or from **work**,
- Going directly to or from a **school-sponsored activity**, or
- Going directly to or from a **religious activity**.

Notice the word **directly**. You cannot stop at a friend''s house on the way home from your shift. If a police officer stops you at 10:30 p.m., they may ask where you are coming from and where you are going. Keeping a pay stub, a school schedule, or a coach''s note in the car can help if you are questioned.

## Passenger restriction

Kansas restricted drivers may carry **no more than one passenger under age 18 who is not a sibling**. The intent is to reduce the documented risk of crashes that goes up sharply with every additional teen passenger. Family members in your immediate household generally don''t count toward the limit, but check the latest KDOR rules — exemptions can change.

Examples:

- You + your younger sister + one friend = **legal** (sibling doesn''t count).
- You + two non-sibling friends = **not legal**.
- You + your cousin (who lives elsewhere) + one friend = **probably not legal**, since cousins are not siblings.

## Cell phone and electronics

Kansas bans **all wireless communication device use** for drivers under 18 who hold an Instruction Permit or Restricted License, except to report an illegal activity, a medical emergency, or a safety hazard. That means:

- No talking on the phone, even hands-free.
- No texting, ever.
- No scrolling social media at a red light.
- No using map apps with your hands while moving.

Set up your music and navigation **before** you put the car in drive. If a call is truly urgent, pull over safely first.

All Kansas drivers — not just teens — are banned from **texting** while driving. This is a primary offense, meaning an officer can pull you over for texting alone.

## Seatbelts

Kansas requires every occupant under 18 to wear a seatbelt or be in an appropriate child restraint. As the driver, **you are legally responsible** for ensuring your underage passengers are buckled. Tickets for unbelted teen passengers go on **your** record, not theirs.

## What happens if you break a restriction?

Violating a GDL restriction is a moving violation. Consequences can include:

- A fine.
- Points on your driving record.
- Extension of your restricted period.
- Suspension of your license.

Worse, conviction of two moving violations in a year (or one serious one) while on a restricted license can delay your full license — sometimes for many months.

## Practical tips

- **Plan your night out backward.** Whose car gets used after 9:00 p.m.? Often, a parent or older friend.
- **Keep proof in the car.** A laminated copy of your work schedule and any school activity sheet protects you if questioned.
- **Be the safe driver, not the chauffeur.** Friends will pressure you to drive everyone. Practice saying "I can only take one — meet you there."
- **Put your phone in the glove box.** Out of sight is out of mind.

The restrictions feel inconvenient, but the year you spend on a restricted license is the single most dangerous year you will ever drive. Kansas''s GDL rules exist because data — not opinion — shows they save teen lives.', 30, 1
);
