INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ks_kansas-rules-of-the-road-quirks', 'module_ks_overlay', 'kansas-rules-of-the-road-quirks', 'Kansas Rules of the Road and Local Quirks', '# Kansas Rules of the Road and Local Quirks

Every state has driving rules that surprise newcomers, and Kansas is no exception. Between rural two-lane highways, wide-open interstates, sudden severe weather, and a healthy population of farm equipment on public roads, Kansas drivers face challenges that drivers in dense urban states do not. This lesson covers the rules and habits that keep you safe — and legal — on Kansas roads.

## Speed limits

Kansas sets some of the higher rural speed limits in the country:

- **Rural interstates and the Kansas Turnpike (I-70, I-35, I-135, I-335):** 75 mph in many segments.
- **Other rural four-lane divided highways:** typically 70 mph.
- **Two-lane state and U.S. highways:** typically 65 mph.
- **Urban interstates:** typically 60 to 70 mph depending on the segment.
- **Residential streets:** 20 to 30 mph unless posted otherwise.
- **School zones:** 20 mph when children are present.

The Kansas Turnpike is a toll road; pay attention to overhead signs, and have a K-TAG or be ready to take a paper ticket at the entry plaza.

## Move Over Law

Kansas''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers approaching any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, road maintenance vehicle, or utility vehicle with flashing lights to:

1. **Move over** one lane away from the stopped vehicle if it is safe to do so, OR
2. **Slow down significantly** below the posted speed limit if you cannot change lanes.

This applies to law enforcement, ambulances, fire trucks, tow trucks, and Kansas Department of Transportation crews. The fines are steep, and the law exists because roadside workers are killed every year in Kansas by drivers who didn''t move over.

## Severe weather driving

Kansas weather is famously dramatic. As a Kansas driver, you must be ready for:

- **Sudden thunderstorms and hail.** Pull off the road if hail is large enough to crack your windshield. Do **not** park under an overpass — this blocks traffic and creates a wind tunnel that is dangerous in tornadoes.
- **Tornadoes.** If you see a tornado while driving, do not try to outrun it laterally. Drive perpendicular to its path if you can, or abandon the vehicle and lie flat in a low ditch away from the car.
- **Blizzards and ice storms.** Black ice forms on bridges and overpasses first. Slow down, increase following distance to at least 8 seconds, and avoid sudden inputs.
- **High winds.** Crosswinds can push high-profile vehicles (trucks, RVs, empty trailers) across lanes. Reduce speed and keep both hands on the wheel.

## Farm equipment and slow-moving vehicles

On rural roads you will encounter combines, tractors, and grain trucks — often during planting (April–May) and harvest (September–October). Slow-moving vehicles display an **orange triangular reflector** on the back. The law:

- You may pass a slow-moving farm vehicle when safe and legal.
- Farm equipment often makes **wide left turns** — never pass a tractor on the left near a driveway or field entrance.
- Combines and headers can be **wider than one lane**. Move as far right as safely possible when meeting them.

## Right turn on red and four-way stops

Kansas allows **right turn on red** after a complete stop unless a sign prohibits it. You must yield to pedestrians and cross traffic. **Left turn on red** is allowed only from a one-way street onto another one-way street.

At four-way stops, the rule is **first to arrive, first to go**. When two vehicles arrive simultaneously, the one on the **right** has the right of way. When two vehicles facing each other arrive at the same time, both may go straight or turn right; the left-turning vehicle yields.

## Open container and DUI

Kansas is a **zero-tolerance state for drivers under 21**. Any measurable blood alcohol concentration (BAC of 0.02% or higher) is a violation and results in license suspension. For drivers 21 and over, the legal limit is **0.08%**, or **0.04%** for commercial drivers. Kansas''s **implied consent** law means that by driving in Kansas you have already agreed to a breath, blood, or urine test if lawfully arrested — refusal carries an automatic one-year suspension for a first offense.

Open alcohol containers are illegal in the passenger area of a moving vehicle.

## Quirks worth knowing

- **Headlights with wipers.** If your windshield wipers are on because of weather, your headlights must be on too.
- **Funeral processions.** Vehicles in a marked funeral procession have the right of way through intersections, even on red lights, once the lead vehicle has entered.
- **School buses.** Stop in **both directions** on undivided roads when a school bus has its red lights flashing and stop arm extended. On a divided highway with a physical median, only the side traveling the same direction as the bus must stop.
- **Deer.** Kansas has more than 10,000 reported deer-vehicle crashes per year. Dawn and dusk in fall are peak times. If a deer is in your path, brake hard but do not swerve — most fatalities happen when drivers swerve into oncoming traffic or roll the vehicle.

Driving in Kansas rewards drivers who anticipate. The roads are often long, straight, and empty — until suddenly they aren''t.', 30, 2
);
