INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit', 'module_ky_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit', 'How to Get Your Kentucky Instruction Permit', '# How to Get Your Kentucky Instruction Permit

Kentucky issues teen drivers an **Instruction Permit** through the Kentucky Transportation Cabinet, Division of Driver Licensing. This is the first stage of Kentucky''s three-stage Graduated Licensing program, and it is the only legal way for a teen to practice on public roads.

## Minimum age and prerequisites

You must be **at least 16 years old** to apply for an instruction permit in Kentucky. Before you walk into a regional driver licensing office, gather the documents you will need:

- **Proof of identity** — certified birth certificate or U.S. passport
- **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card or W-2
- **Two proofs of Kentucky residency** — utility bill, lease, bank statement, or school record showing your name and physical address
- **Parent or legal guardian consent** — a parent or guardian must appear in person with you to sign the application if you are under 18
- **School Compliance Verification Form** — required under Kentucky''s *No Pass No Drive* law (see Lesson 3), proving you are enrolled and academically compliant
- **Application fee** — payable at the licensing office (currently a modest fee for the permit itself)

If you are pursuing a federally compliant **REAL ID** credential, bring originals (not copies) of all identity documents.

## The knowledge test and vision screening

At the regional office you will take:

1. A **vision screening** to confirm you meet Kentucky''s minimum visual acuity standard (20/40 in at least one eye, with or without corrective lenses).
2. A **written knowledge test** covering Kentucky traffic laws, road signs, signals, and safe driving practices. The test is based on the current *Kentucky Driver Manual*, which you should download from drive.ky.gov and read cover to cover before testing.

Most questions are multiple choice. If you fail, Kentucky requires a waiting period before you can retest — typically the next business day, but rules vary by office.

## What the permit lets you do

Once issued, your Kentucky instruction permit allows you to drive **only when accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older** who is seated in the front passenger seat and has at least one year of licensed driving experience. The supervising driver must be alert and unimpaired.

Key rules during the permit phase:

- You must hold the permit for a **minimum of 180 days (6 months)** before applying for the intermediate license.
- You must log a **minimum of 60 hours of supervised practice driving**, including **at least 10 hours at night**.
- You must remain conviction-free of any moving violations or alcohol/drug offenses during the permit period — otherwise the 180-day clock resets.
- You cannot drive alone under any circumstance, even briefly.

## Tracking your practice hours

Kentucky requires you to maintain a **driving log** that your parent or guardian signs. The log must show date, duration, weather/road conditions, and the supervising driver''s signature. When you apply for the intermediate license, you will present this signed log as proof.

We recommend logging hours digitally inside this LMS — your parent can sign electronically and the totals are calculated automatically.

## Moving to the next stage

After holding the permit for 180 days, logging 60+ hours of supervised driving (10+ at night), reaching age 16.5, and remaining conviction-free, you can schedule the **road skills test** at a Kentucky State Police testing location. Passing the road test moves you to the **Intermediate License**, which we cover in detail in the next lesson.', 25, 0
);
