INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit_2', 'quiz_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit', 'How many total supervised practice hours, and how many of those at night, must a Kentucky permit holder log?', '["30 total / 5 at night","40 total / 10 at night","50 total / 15 at night","60 total / 10 at night"]', 3, 'Kentucky requires 60 hours of supervised practice, including at least 10 hours of nighttime driving.', 2
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit_3', 'quiz_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit', 'Who may supervise a Kentucky permit holder during practice driving?', '["Any licensed driver 18 or older","A licensed driver age 21 or older with at least one year of licensed experience, seated in the front","Only a parent or guardian","Any adult passenger"]', 1, 'The supervisor must be a licensed driver age 21+, have at least one year of licensed experience, and ride in the front passenger seat.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit_4', 'quiz_ky_how-to-get-a-kentucky-permit', 'What happens if a Kentucky permit holder is convicted of a moving violation during the permit period?', '["Nothing, violations don''t apply to permits","The permit is permanently revoked","The 180-day permit holding clock resets","The driver loses 10 practice hours"]', 2, 'A moving violation conviction during the permit phase resets the 180-day clock, delaying eligibility for the intermediate license.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ky_kentucky-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ky_overlay', 'kentucky-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Kentucky GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Kentucky GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Once you pass your road test, Kentucky issues an **Intermediate License**. This license lets you drive without a supervisor, but it comes with restrictions designed to reduce the highest-risk situations for new drivers: late nights, distracting passengers, and electronic devices. These rules apply for at least **180 days**, and longer if you are convicted of any moving violation or alcohol/drug offense.

This lesson walks through what the intermediate stage means for real-life situations — going to school, weekend plans, after-school jobs, and family errands.

## The nighttime curfew

Kentucky intermediate license holders **may not drive between midnight and 6:00 a.m.** unless one of these exceptions applies:

- A licensed parent, guardian, or person in loco parentis is in the front passenger seat
- You are driving directly to or from work
- You are driving directly to or from a school-sanctioned activity
- A documented emergency requires it (medical, safety)

**What this means in practice:** A Friday-night movie that ends at 11:45 p.m. is fine if you go straight home. A late shift at a restaurant that ends at 12:30 a.m. is allowed *only if* you go directly home and can document the work schedule if asked. Going from work to a friend''s house at 1 a.m. is a violation.

## The passenger rule

During the intermediate phase you may **not carry more than one passenger under age 20** who is not an immediate family member. Immediate family — siblings, stepsiblings, children — do not count toward the limit.

**What this means in practice:** You can drive your little sister and one friend to school. You cannot drive three teammates home from practice. Carpooling has to be planned around this rule, and parents should help arrange alternates so the new driver is not pressured into violating it.

## The phone and device rule

Kentucky bans **all use of personal communication devices** by drivers under 18 — this includes both handheld and hands-free use. That means:

- No phone calls (even on Bluetooth or speaker)
- No texting, snapping, scrolling, navigating, or music app changes while moving
- No video chats, even if the phone is mounted

For all drivers regardless of age, **texting while driving is illegal**. The only narrow exception is using a navigation app that is configured before you start moving and not actively touched while driving — and even then, drivers under 18 are technically prohibited.

**Best practice:** put your phone in Do Not Disturb / Driving Mode before you start the engine, and stow it where you cannot reach it. If you need to take a call or change a route, pull off the road safely first.

## Seat belt and passenger safety

Kentucky has a primary seat belt law — meaning officers can stop you solely for an unbelted driver or passenger. As the driver, you are responsible for ensuring every passenger under 18 is properly restrained. Children under 8 and shorter than 57 inches must be in an appropriate child safety or booster seat.

## Zero tolerance for alcohol

Kentucky has a **zero-tolerance law** for drivers under 21: a blood alcohol concentration of **0.02% or higher** is grounds for license suspension. For context, that is roughly one drink — not a margin you can manage. A conviction also restarts your intermediate restrictions and can extend them well past your 17th birthday.

## Moving to a full license

To move from the intermediate license to a **full, unrestricted license** you must:

- Hold the intermediate license for at least **180 days**
- Have **no moving violation convictions** during that period
- Have **no alcohol or drug convictions**
- Be at least **17 years old**

If you stay clean, your full license is largely automatic at the next renewal. If you collect violations, the clock resets each time — making the difference between getting your full license at 17 and getting it at 18 or later.', 25, 1
);
