INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ky_kentucky-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ky_overlay', 'kentucky-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Kentucky-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Teen Should Know', '# Kentucky-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Teen Should Know

Some of Kentucky''s most important driving rules are not obvious from a generic national driver''s manual. This lesson covers the Bluegrass State quirks that get new drivers cited, suspended, or worse — and the practical things every Kentucky teen should know before getting behind the wheel.

## The "No Pass No Drive" law

Kentucky links your driving privilege to your school performance. Under KRS 159.051 — commonly called the **No Pass No Drive law** — students under 18 can lose their permit, intermediate license, or full license if they:

- Accumulate **9 or more unexcused absences** in a school year, OR
- **Drop out** of school, OR
- Fail to maintain satisfactory academic progress as defined by their school district

Schools report non-compliance directly to the Transportation Cabinet, which then suspends the credential. To get your license back you must show a **School Compliance Verification Form** signed by your school. This is also required when you first apply for the permit.

**Practical takeaway:** skipping class can literally cost you your license. Track attendance carefully and talk to your school counselor immediately if you have an attendance or grade problem brewing.

## The yellow plate / restricted plate

In many Kentucky counties, instruction-permit and intermediate-license drivers historically had distinctive license plates or decals so officers could quickly identify a new driver. Even when not required by your county, expect that officers know the look of a young driver and will pay closer attention to curfew and passenger compliance.

## Move Over law

Kentucky''s **Move Over law** requires drivers to either change lanes away from, or significantly slow down for, any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, utility truck, KYTC vehicle, or other vehicle with flashing lights on the shoulder. Failure to move over is a primary offense and a frequent citation against new drivers who don''t anticipate it.

## Rural roads, ridge roads, and deer

Kentucky has thousands of miles of two-lane rural and mountain roads. New drivers need to know:

- **Deer collisions** peak October through December, especially at dawn and dusk. If a deer enters the road, brake firmly and stay in your lane — swerving into oncoming traffic or off a shoulder is far more dangerous than the collision itself.
- **No-passing zones** on hilly two-lane roads exist for a reason. Passing on a blind crest or curve in eastern or central Kentucky is a recipe for a head-on crash.
- **Coal trucks, farm equipment, and Amish buggies** share many rural routes. Expect very slow vehicles around the next bend and pass only in marked zones with full visibility.

## Weather: ice, fog, and flash floods

- **Black ice** is common on bridges and overpasses from late November through March even when air temperatures are above freezing. Bridges freeze first.
- **Valley fog** in central and western Kentucky river valleys can drop visibility to near zero at sunrise. Slow down, use low-beam headlights (not high beams), and increase following distance.
- **Flash flooding** is a recurring hazard, especially in eastern Kentucky hollers. The state''s slogan is **Turn Around, Don''t Drown** — never drive into water of unknown depth. Six inches of moving water can sweep a small car off the road.

## School buses and stop-arm law

On any **two-lane road**, traffic in **both directions** must stop for a school bus displaying flashing red lights and an extended stop arm. On a divided highway with a physical median or barrier, only traffic on the same side as the bus must stop. Violations are heavily penalized and frequently caught on bus-mounted cameras.

## Insurance and registration in the car

Kentucky requires you to carry **proof of insurance** in the vehicle at all times. The minimum liability coverage is 25/50/25 (25k bodily injury per person / 50k per accident / 25k property damage). New drivers should also know where the registration and insurance card are stored *before* they are ever pulled over.

## After a crash

Kentucky law requires you to:

1. Stop immediately at the scene
2. Render reasonable aid to anyone injured
3. Exchange information (name, address, registration, insurance) with other drivers
4. Notify police if anyone is injured, killed, or if property damage exceeds **$500**

Leaving the scene of even a minor crash is a serious criminal offense — far worse than the original fender bender.', 25, 2
);
