INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_la_louisiana-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_la_overlay', 'louisiana-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Louisiana-Specific Rules, Roads, and Quirks', '## Driving in Louisiana Is Not Like Driving Anywhere Else

Between parish-by-parish road quality, hurricane evacuations, parade season, and bayou wildlife, Louisiana throws driving scenarios at you that the generic national driver''s manual doesn''t cover. This lesson walks through the Louisiana-specific rules and quirks every new driver should know.

### Contraflow and Hurricane Evacuations

Louisiana is one of the few states that activates **contraflow** — reversing the direction of inbound interstate lanes so all lanes carry traffic away from the coast — during major hurricane evacuations. If you are driving when contraflow is activated:

- **Follow the posted detour signs and state troopers'' directions exactly.** GPS will not be updated in real time.
- Be aware that on-ramps, exits, and rest stops are closed or repurposed.
- Fuel up before you leave — gas stations along contraflow routes run dry quickly.
- Keep an emergency kit (water, snacks, phone charger, paper map) in your car during hurricane season (June through November).

### Parade Season and Street Closures

From **Twelfth Night (January 6) through Mardi Gras**, parade routes shut down major streets across the state — not just in New Orleans. Lafayette, Baton Rouge, Houma, and Lake Charles all run multi-week parade calendars. Key rules:

- **It is illegal to cross a parade route** while a parade is active. Plan your trips around posted parade schedules.
- **Ladders, chairs, and coolers** staked out along parade routes have informal but vigorously defended priority — don''t park where they''re set up.
- **Throwing or catching beads/throws while driving** is illegal and dangerous.

### Right Turn on Red and Left Turn on Red

Louisiana follows the standard U.S. rule: **right turn on red is allowed** after a complete stop, unless a sign prohibits it. Louisiana also allows a **left turn on red from a one-way street onto another one-way street** moving in the legal direction — common in downtown New Orleans, Baton Rouge, and Shreveport.

### Move-Over Law

Louisiana''s **Move-Over law** requires drivers to change lanes away from any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, utility vehicle, or sanitation truck displaying flashing lights. If you can''t safely change lanes, you must **slow to at least 25 mph below the posted speed limit** (or 10 mph if the limit is under 25). Violations carry stiff fines.

### Funeral Processions

Louisiana law gives **funeral processions the right-of-way** at intersections once the lead vehicle has legally entered. Do not cut through a procession even if your light turns green. Processions are typically marked by purple or orange flags and hazard lights.

### Bridges, Causeways, and Elevated Highways

- The **Lake Pontchartrain Causeway** (about 24 miles) is one of the longest bridges in the world. There is no shoulder for most of it, and crossing in fog or high winds requires extra caution. Authorities sometimes close lanes or require escort convoys.
- **Atchafalaya Basin Bridge (I-10)** crosses 18 miles of swamp west of Baton Rouge. Sudden rain bands and standing water are common.
- Many older elevated highways flood at the on-ramps during heavy rain — never attempt to cross standing water of unknown depth. "**Turn around, don''t drown**" is the official state slogan.

### Wildlife and Livestock

Rural Louisiana parishes are home to **alligators, deer, wild hogs, and the occasional escaped cow**. Open-range laws still apply in a handful of parishes. At dawn and dusk, scan ditches and tree lines. If an animal crosses your path, brake firmly in a straight line — do not swerve.

### Open Container and DWI

Louisiana has unusually permissive open-container norms for passengers in some parishes (and famously allows go-cups for pedestrians on Bourbon Street), **but it is illegal for the driver to have an open alcoholic beverage** anywhere in the state, and the legal BAC is **0.02% for drivers under 21** — effectively zero tolerance. A first DWI as a minor results in license suspension and mandatory substance-abuse evaluation.

### Insurance Requirements

Louisiana requires minimum liability insurance of **$15,000 / $30,000 / $25,000**. Driving without proof of insurance can result in your license plate being seized at the roadside. Always keep a current insurance card (paper or digital) in the vehicle.

### Quick Quirks Cheat Sheet

- Parishes, not counties.
- ''Neutral ground'' = median.
- ''Banquette'' = sidewalk (mostly New Orleans).
- ''Making groceries'' = grocery shopping (heard on the road, not a driving rule, but you''ll hear it).
- Yellow flashing left arrows are increasingly common in Baton Rouge — they mean you may turn left but must yield to oncoming traffic.', 30, 2
);
