INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ma_how-to-get-a-permit-in-massachusetts', 'module_ma_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-massachusetts', 'How to Get a Learner''s Permit in Massachusetts', '# Getting Your Massachusetts Learner''s Permit

In Massachusetts, the Registry of Motor Vehicles (RMV) issues Learner''s Permits to applicants who are at least 16 years old. The learner''s permit is the first credential in the Massachusetts Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) system, and you must hold it for at least 6 months before you can take the road test for a Junior Operator License (JOL).

## Step 1: Meet the Age Requirement

You must be at least 16 years old on the day you apply. There is no younger age tier in Massachusetts — 16 is the minimum.

## Step 2: Gather Your Documents

Massachusetts uses a strict identity verification process. You will need to bring documents that prove:

- **Lawful presence and identity** (e.g., U.S. passport or birth certificate)
- **Social Security Number** (your SSN card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN)
- **Massachusetts residency** (two documents, such as a utility bill, bank statement, or signed lease — school records or a parent''s documents with a residency affidavit are accepted for minors)
- **Signature of a parent or legal guardian** if you are under 18 (the parent must appear in person at the RMV or sign the application before a notary)

If you want a REAL ID-compliant permit, the document requirements are slightly stricter. A Standard permit is fine for in-state driving but won''t be accepted for federal purposes (like boarding domestic flights starting in May 2025).

## Step 3: Schedule and Take the Knowledge Test

The Learner''s Permit knowledge exam covers Massachusetts road signs, rules of the road, and safe driving practices. You can study using the **Massachusetts Driver''s Manual**, available free from the RMV website. The test is 25 multiple-choice questions, and you must answer at least 18 correctly (72%) to pass. The test is offered in multiple languages including Spanish, Portuguese, Chinese, Vietnamese, and several others.

You must make a permit appointment at an RMV Service Center — walk-ins are generally not accepted. Bring all your documents and the application fee.

## Step 4: Pass the Vision Screening

At the RMV, you''ll take a vision screening. If you wear glasses or contacts, bring them — you''ll be tested with corrective lenses if you use them, and a corrective lens restriction will be added to your permit.

## Step 5: Pay the Fee and Get Your Permit

Once you pass the knowledge test and vision screening, you''ll pay the permit fee and receive your learner''s permit the same day.

## What You Can and Can''t Do With a Permit

With a Massachusetts learner''s permit, you may only drive when accompanied by a **licensed driver who is at least 21 years old, has at least one year of driving experience, and is seated next to you in the front seat**. You may **not** drive between 12:00 a.m. and 5:00 a.m. under any circumstances.

## Step 6: Complete Driver Education

If you are under 18, you must complete a state-approved Driver Education program before you can take the road test. This program includes 30 hours of classroom, 12 hours of behind-the-wheel, and 6 hours of observation. Your parent or guardian must also complete a 2-hour Parent Class.

After holding your permit for at least 6 months with no moving violations, completing driver ed, and logging 40 hours of supervised practice (30 of which must be with a parent/guardian), you''ll be eligible to schedule your road test.', 35, 0
);
