INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ma_ma-jol-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ma_overlay', 'ma-jol-restrictions-daily-life', 'Massachusetts JOL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Living With a Junior Operator License (JOL)

When a Massachusetts driver under 18 passes the road test, they receive a **Junior Operator License (JOL)** — not a full unrestricted license. The JOL comes with serious restrictions that affect how you drive every day, and Massachusetts has some of the strictest teen driving penalties in the country.

## The Nighttime Restriction

JOL holders may **not drive between 12:30 a.m. and 5:00 a.m.** unless accompanied by a parent or legal guardian. This is sometimes called the "curfew" rule. There is no exception for work, school events, or emergencies (other than a true emergency where you should call 911). Coming home late from a friend''s house, a concert, or a late-night shift at your part-time job means you need to plan your drive home before 12:30 a.m.

## The Passenger Restriction

For the **first 6 months** after getting your JOL, you may not transport any passenger under age 18 unless a licensed driver who is at least 21 years old with one year of experience is also in the car. Siblings are exempt — you can always drive your brothers and sisters.

This means: no driving friends to school, no carpooling teammates to practice, no giving a younger cousin a ride to the mall during your first 6 months. This restriction is heavily enforced, and police can pull you over for violating it.

## Cell Phone and Electronic Devices

Massachusetts has a **complete ban on any electronic device use by JOL holders** while driving. This includes:

- Handheld cell phones
- **Hands-free systems** (yes, even Bluetooth)
- Texting
- Using GPS apps on a phone
- Headphones or earbuds

If you need GPS navigation, you must set the route before you start driving and use a vehicle-mounted system or have a passenger operate the device. Adults in Massachusetts may use hands-free devices, but under-18 drivers may not.

## Speeding and Moving Violations Are Brutal

Massachusetts treats teen speeding extraordinarily harshly:

- **First speeding offense**: 90-day license suspension, $50 reinstatement fee, mandatory attendance at a state-approved Driver Attitudinal Retraining course, and a $500 license reinstatement fee. You''ll also need to retake both the knowledge test and the road test.
- **Drag racing or speeding while passing a school bus**: 1-year suspension.
- **Second speeding offense**: 1-year suspension.

Any moving violation results in a 60-day suspension and required completion of a State Courts Against Road Rage (SCARR) program.

## Seatbelts

All occupants of a vehicle operated by a JOL holder must wear seatbelts. As the driver, you can be cited if any passenger under 18 is unbuckled.

## Alcohol — Zero Tolerance

Massachusetts has a Zero Tolerance law for drivers under 21. A BAC of 0.02% or higher results in a 180-day license suspension on the first offense, plus possible additional penalties. Combined with the under-21 OUI penalties, the consequences are severe — including a 1-year suspension for refusing the breath test.

## When Do the Restrictions End?

The passenger restriction lifts after 6 months. The nighttime restriction, cell phone ban, and JOL designation remain until you turn 18. On your 18th birthday, you can apply to convert your JOL to a full Class D license at no charge.

## Planning Your Daily Routine

Practical tips:

- Set a personal "home by midnight" rule to give yourself a 30-minute buffer before the 12:30 a.m. cutoff.
- Use a car-mounted GPS or have a passenger handle navigation.
- Tell your friends about the passenger rule early so they''re not surprised when you can''t give them rides.
- Keep your phone in your bag or glove box while driving — out of sight, out of mind.', 30, 1
);
