INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ma_ma-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ma_overlay', 'ma-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Massachusetts-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Driving in Massachusetts: Rules and Quirks You Won''t Find Elsewhere

Massachusetts has a driving culture and a set of rules shaped by colonial-era street grids, dense urban traffic in Greater Boston, and some of the oldest roads in the United States. Beyond the basics, there are several state-specific rules and quirks every new Massachusetts driver should understand.

## Rotaries (Roundabouts)

Massachusetts loves rotaries — what most of the country calls roundabouts. The rule in Massachusetts is straightforward but often misunderstood: **traffic already in the rotary has the right of way**. Drivers entering must yield. Decades ago the rule was the opposite, and many older drivers still get confused, so always be cautious and prepared to brake when entering. Signal right when you''re about to exit so drivers waiting to enter know what you''re doing.

## The Right on Red (and the Many Exceptions)

Right turns on red are generally allowed after a complete stop — but **not in downtown Boston in many locations**, and not where signs prohibit it. Always look for a "No Turn on Red" sign, which Boston posts liberally. Some Cambridge and Brookline intersections also restrict it.

## Pedestrian Right of Way Is Sacred

Massachusetts law gives pedestrians in any marked crosswalk the **absolute right of way**. Drivers must stop — not just yield — when a pedestrian is in a crosswalk on the driver''s side of the road, or approaching from the opposite side and within 10 feet. Failing to stop is a $200 fine and is enforced. In pedestrian-heavy cities like Boston, Cambridge, Somerville, and Northampton, expect pedestrians to step into crosswalks without looking — they have the legal right, even when it''s unwise.

## The Move Over Law

Massachusetts requires drivers to move over one lane (when safe) for stopped emergency vehicles, tow trucks, highway maintenance vehicles, and any vehicle with flashing lights on the shoulder. If you can''t change lanes safely, slow down significantly.

## Snow and Ice Rules

Massachusetts has a law (sometimes called "Jessica''s Law") that requires drivers to **clear snow and ice from their vehicles — including the roof — before driving**. Failing to clear snow that then flies off and damages another vehicle or injures someone can result in fines from $40 to $200, plus civil liability.

During declared snow emergencies in Boston and other cities, parking restrictions kick in immediately — your car will be ticketed and towed from designated snow emergency routes. Sign up for city alerts.

## Headlight Use

Massachusetts requires headlights to be on:

- From 30 minutes after sunset to 30 minutes before sunrise
- **Whenever your windshield wipers are in use** due to weather (rain, snow, fog, sleet)
- When visibility is less than 500 feet

Daytime running lights do NOT count — your full headlights, including tail lights, must be on.

## The Massachusetts Inspection Sticker

Every registered passenger vehicle in Massachusetts must pass an annual safety and emissions inspection at a licensed station. The sticker goes on the lower passenger side of the windshield and shows the month it expires. Driving with an expired sticker is a $40 ticket and can be enforced after a 1-month grace period.

## OUI vs. DUI

Massachusetts calls drunk driving **OUI (Operating Under the Influence)** rather than DUI. The legal limit is 0.08% for drivers 21+ and 0.02% for drivers under 21. "Operating" in Massachusetts case law is broad — you can be charged for OUI even while sitting in a parked car with the keys in the ignition.

## School Buses

When a school bus has its red lights flashing and stop arm extended, **all traffic in both directions must stop** — even on divided highways unless separated by a physical median or barrier. The fine is $250 for a first offense and the violation can affect your insurance for years.

## The Big Dig and Boston Driving

If you''ll drive in Boston, know that the city is famous for confusing one-way streets, unmarked lane changes, and aggressive drivers. Tips:

- Use GPS but set the route before you start driving.
- Watch for pedestrians and cyclists — Boston has aggressive bike commuters and many protected bike lanes.
- Storrow Drive and Memorial Drive have **low clearances** — moving trucks famously get stuck there every September during college move-in ("Storrowing").

## EZ-Pass and Tolls

The Mass Pike (I-90), Tobin Bridge, and several tunnels use all-electronic tolling. There are no toll booths to stop at — cameras read your transponder or photograph your plate, and a bill is mailed to the registered owner. Get an EZ-Pass MA transponder for the lowest rates.', 30, 2
);
