INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_md_maryland-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_md_overlay', 'maryland-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Maryland GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Maryland GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

The Maryland *Rookie Driver* graduated licensing system is designed to ease new drivers into full driving privileges. The middle stage — the **Provisional License** — is when you first drive alone, and it is also when most teens get tripped up by rules they did not realize applied to a normal Friday night. This lesson translates Maryland''s GDL rulebook into the real-life decisions you will face.

## The three stages, in plain English

1. **Learner''s Permit** — supervised driving only, age 15 years 9 months and up.
2. **Provisional License** — solo driving allowed, but with curfew and passenger limits. Issued at age 16 years 6 months at the earliest.
3. **Full Driver''s License** — issued once you are 18, or after holding the provisional license for at least 18 months conviction-free, whichever comes first.

The provisional stage is the one that affects daily life the most, so the rest of this lesson focuses there.

## The midnight-to-5 a.m. curfew

Provisional drivers may not drive between **midnight and 5:00 a.m.** unless:

- A qualified supervising driver (21+, three years licensed) is in the front passenger seat, **or**
- You are driving to/from school, work, or a school-sanctioned activity, **or**
- You are responding to a volunteer fire/EMS call.

If you work a closing shift at a restaurant, keep your work schedule or a recent pay stub in the car. If you are coming home from a football game that ran late, that is *not* automatically covered — ''school-sanctioned'' means the school officially organized the event. A friend''s house at 1 a.m. is a clear violation.

## The first-5-months passenger rule

For the **first 151 days** (about 5 months) after your provisional license is issued, you may not transport **anyone under 18** unless:

- They are an **immediate family member** (sibling, etc.), or
- A qualified supervising driver (21+, three years licensed) is in the front passenger seat.

In practical terms: do not drive your friends to school, the movies, or practice during those first five months. One under-18 passenger who is not your sibling is enough for a citation, and the citation will reset your conviction-free clock and delay your full license.

## The zero-tolerance phone rule

Drivers under 18 in Maryland — whether on a permit or a provisional license — **cannot use any wireless device while driving**. That includes:

- Holding a phone.
- Speakerphone calls.
- Bluetooth or hands-free calls.
- Voice-to-text or ''just one quick text.''

The **only** exception is calling 911. Adult Maryland drivers are allowed hands-free calls, but minors are not. Put the phone in ''Do Not Disturb While Driving'' before you start the car.

## Seatbelts, BAC, and other constants

- **Seatbelts**: every occupant, every trip. As the driver you are responsible for passengers under 16.
- **BAC**: 0.00% for any driver under 21. Even a sip is a violation under Maryland''s underage drinking and driving laws.
- **Speeding and reckless driving**: any moving conviction during the provisional period can extend the time you must spend in that stage and may trigger MVA-mandated remedial driver improvement classes.

## What happens if you get a ticket

A single conviction during the provisional period typically means:

1. An MVA notice extending your provisional period.
2. Possible required attendance at a Driver Improvement Program.
3. A second conviction within the period can lead to a 30-day suspension; a third can lead to a 180-day suspension and revocation of the license.

## Daily-life rules of thumb

- **Plan around the curfew.** If a movie ends at 11:45 p.m. and you are 25 minutes from home, you are gambling.
- **Treat the phone like contraband.** Even at red lights — Maryland''s handheld ban applies any time the car is on a public roadway.
- **No friends in the car for five months.** This is the single most violated rule. Build the habit early.
- **Keep documentation handy.** Work schedules, school activity rosters, and your Practice and Skills Log live in the glove box, not in your room.

Get through 18 months of provisional driving with no convictions and Maryland upgrades you to a full license automatically when you reach 18 — no extra test required.', 30, 1
);
