INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_md_maryland-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_md_overlay', 'maryland-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Maryland-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Maryland-Specific Rules and Quirks

Every state has driving rules that surprise newcomers, and Maryland is no exception. Some of these are codified in the *Maryland Vehicle Law*; others are local conventions you only learn by driving on I-695 or trying to merge onto the Capital Beltway. This lesson covers the Maryland-specific quirks that show up on the MVA knowledge test and on every commute.

## Move Over Law — broader than most states

Maryland''s **Move Over Law** requires you to change lanes away from any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, service vehicle, transportation vehicle, or waste/recycling truck that is displaying flashing lights on the shoulder or in an adjacent lane. If you cannot safely change lanes, you must **slow to a reasonable and prudent speed**. Maryland expanded this law to cover utility, transportation, and even waste vehicles — broader than most states — and fines can exceed $500 if the violation contributes to a crash.

## Speed cameras and red light cameras

Maryland is a heavy user of **automated enforcement**. Speed cameras operate in school zones and on portions of I-83, I-95, and other work zones. A speed camera citation is a civil fine (typically $40) that **does not add points** to your license, but it is mailed to the registered owner of the car and must be paid. Red light cameras issue similar civil citations. Two practical implications:

- Just because nothing happened on your dashboard does not mean you were not photographed.
- If your parent owns the car and you were driving, the citation will arrive at home regardless.

## Headlights and wipers

Maryland law requires headlights any time **windshield wipers are in continuous or intermittent use** due to weather. Daytime running lights do not satisfy this rule — your taillights must also be on so that vehicles behind you can see you in rain or fog. It is a common Maryland ticket for out-of-state drivers.

## Right turn on red

Right turn on red is permitted statewide unless a sign prohibits it, **except in most of downtown Baltimore**, where signs frequently ban it. Always look for the sign before turning — and remember that pedestrians have the right of way in the crosswalk even when your light turns green.

## Roundabouts

Maryland has built dozens of roundabouts (especially in Howard, Anne Arundel, and Frederick counties). Rules:

- **Yield to traffic already in the circle.**
- Enter to the right, travel counter-clockwise.
- Do not stop inside the roundabout.
- Use your right turn signal when exiting.

The MVA knowledge test almost always includes a roundabout question.

## Bicycles and the 3-foot rule

When passing a bicycle, Maryland law requires at least **3 feet of clearance**. If you cannot give 3 feet, you must wait until you can. This applies on every road, including narrow city streets. You may legally cross a double yellow line to pass a bicycle if the lane is clear and it is safe to do so.

## School buses

When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and stop arm extended, **all traffic in both directions must stop**, unless you are on a divided highway with a physical median or barrier — then only traffic behind the bus must stop. A painted center turn lane does **not** count as a physical median. Maryland uses school bus stop-arm cameras, so violations are caught on video.

## HOV lanes

If you drive in the I-270 corridor, you will encounter **HOV-2 lanes** (two or more occupants required during posted hours). Plug-in electric vehicles with the Maryland Clean Energy plate may use HOV lanes solo. Violations are routinely enforced by Maryland State Police.

## Express toll lanes and E-ZPass

Maryland is **cashless** on every major toll facility: the Bay Bridge, Fort McHenry Tunnel, Harbor Tunnel, ICC (Intercounty Connector), and I-95 Express Toll Lanes. If you do not have an E-ZPass, a ''Video Toll'' is mailed to the registered owner at a higher rate. Set up E-ZPass before you start commuting on any of these.

## Studded tires and chains

Studded tires are **only legal from November 1 through March 31**, and chains are only permitted during snow or ice conditions. Most Maryland drivers never need either, but if you ski in western Maryland, know the dates.

## Quirky local conventions

- **The ''Maryland merge''** on the Beltway: drivers often merge late at the last moment. Defensive driving means leaving a gap.
- **''Jughandle'' style left turns** exist on some U.S. routes on the Eastern Shore — you turn right onto a ramp to make a left.
- **Reversible lanes** on US-50 to the Bay Bridge and on I-695 — always check the overhead lane signals before entering.

Master these and you will drive Maryland roads like a local — and pass the MVA knowledge test on the first try.', 30, 2
);
