INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_me_maine-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_me_overlay', 'maine-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Maine GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Living with Maine''s Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) Restrictions

Getting your **intermediate license** in Maine doesn''t mean you can drive however you want. For the first **9 months**, Maine law places real limits on *when* you can drive and *who* you can take with you. Violating these rules can extend the restriction period and result in license suspension. This lesson explains what the rules look like in everyday situations.

## The nighttime restriction

During your first 9 months as an intermediate licensee, and as long as you are under 18, you **may not drive between midnight and 5:00 a.m.**

There are limited exceptions:

- Driving to or from **employment** (you should carry a note from your employer if asked).
- Driving to or from **school activities**.
- An **emergency** (medical, family safety, etc.).

### Real-world examples

- Leaving a friend''s house at 12:15 a.m. on a Saturday — **not allowed**.
- Driving home from your restaurant job at 1:00 a.m. — allowed (employment exception).
- Driving a friend home from a movie that ends at 11:45 p.m. — allowed if you go straight home and arrive by midnight.

## The passenger restriction

During the same first 9 months, you **may not transport passengers** other than:

- **Immediate family members** (parents, siblings, stepsiblings, grandparents living in the same household), or
- Anyone, if accompanied by a **licensed driver age 20 or older with at least 2 years of licensing experience** sitting in the front passenger seat.

### Real-world examples

- Driving your younger brother to soccer practice — allowed (family).
- Picking up two classmates for a study group — **not allowed** (non-family passengers without a qualified adult).
- Going to the beach with three friends while your older sister (age 22, licensed 4 years) rides in the front seat — allowed.

## The cell phone and handheld device rule

Maine has one of the country''s stricter teen distracted-driving laws. If you are **under 18**, you may **not use any handheld electronic device or mobile phone** while driving — *even hands-free use is prohibited*. This includes:

- Talking on the phone (hand-held **or** Bluetooth/speaker).
- Texting or reading messages.
- Using GPS apps interactively.
- Streaming music from your phone while tapping controls.

A first offense is a traffic infraction with a fine and can extend your intermediate-license restrictions. Set your destination *before* you start driving, hand your phone to a passenger, or place it in ''do not disturb while driving'' mode.

## Seat belts

Everyone in your vehicle must be buckled in Maine — but as the driver, **you** are responsible if any passenger under 18 is unbelted. Make ''buckle up'' part of starting the car.

## What happens if you break a GDL rule?

Maine treats GDL violations seriously. Common consequences include:

- **Extension of the 9-month restriction period** — the clock restarts.
- License **suspension** for 30 days (first offense) or longer for repeat offenses.
- Higher insurance premiums for years afterward.
- For cell phone violations, additional fines that escalate with each offense.

## After the 9 months

Once you complete 9 months of intermediate driving with no violations *and* turn 18, you graduate to a full unrestricted license. The cell phone ban for under-18 drivers no longer applies — but Maine''s general bans on **texting** and on **handheld phone use** apply to drivers of all ages, so safe habits matter for life.', 30, 1
);
