INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mi_how-to-get-a-permit-in-michigan', 'module_mi_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-michigan', 'How to Get a Level 1 Permit in Michigan', '## Michigan''s Three-Step GDL Program

Michigan licenses new teen drivers through a Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) program administered by the Michigan Secretary of State (SOS). It has three steps: **Level 1 (Temporary Instruction Permit)**, **Level 2 (Intermediate License)**, and **Level 3 (Full License)**. You cannot skip ahead — each level has minimum age, time-held, training, and clean-record requirements.

## Step 1: Enroll in Segment 1 Driver Education

Before you can apply for your Level 1 permit, you must complete **Segment 1** at a Michigan-approved driver education provider. Segment 1 includes:

- **24 hours of classroom instruction** (covering traffic laws, signs, signals, defensive driving, the dangers of impaired and distracted driving, and Michigan-specific rules).
- **6 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW) instruction** with a certified instructor.
- **4 hours of in-car observation** while another student drives.

You may **start Segment 1 as early as age 14 years 8 months**. You must pass the Segment 1 classroom test and the BTW evaluation before your school issues your completion certificate.

## Step 2: Apply for the Level 1 Permit

Once Segment 1 is complete, your parent or legal guardian must take you to a Secretary of State office. You must be **at least 14 years 9 months old**. Bring:

- Your Segment 1 completion certificate.
- Proof of identity, Michigan residency, and legal presence (a certified birth certificate or passport, plus residency documents in the parent''s name).
- Your Social Security number.
- The Level 1 license fee (currently $25, subject to change).
- A parent or legal guardian to sign the application — Michigan parents assume **financial responsibility** for the minor driver.

You will take a **vision screening** and a **knowledge (written) test** covering traffic signs and Michigan law. If you pass, you receive your Level 1 license the same day.

## Step 3: Drive Under Level 1 Rules

With a Level 1, you may only drive when **a licensed parent, legal guardian, or designated adult age 21 or older with a valid license** is seated next to you in the front seat. You cannot drive alone, ever, under Level 1. You must also **wear seat belts**, and Michigan''s hands-free law plus the GDL cell phone ban mean **no phone use of any kind while driving**.

## Step 4: Log Practice and Complete Segment 2

While holding your Level 1, you must:

- Log **at least 50 hours of supervised driving practice**, of which **at least 10 hours must be at night**, in a parent-signed log.
- Complete **Segment 2** (a 6-hour classroom course) **after** you have held your Level 1 for at least 3 months and logged at least 30 of those 50 hours (including 2 night hours). Segment 2 cannot be taken earlier.

## Step 5: Move Up to Level 2

To apply for a Level 2 Intermediate License, you must be **at least 16 years old**, have held the Level 1 for **at least 6 months**, have **no moving violations, alcohol/drug convictions, or at-fault crashes in the previous 90 days**, complete Segment 2, finish all 50 practice hours, and pass the **road skills test** at a state-approved third-party testing organization.

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- Not logging practice hours in real time — the SOS or your testing center may ask to see the log.
- Scheduling Segment 2 before the 3-month/30-hour minimum.
- Driving without an eligible adult in the front passenger seat — even one violation can delay your Level 2 application by 90 days.
', 35, 0
);
