INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mi_michigan-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_mi_overlay', 'michigan-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living With Michigan''s Level 2 GDL Restrictions', '## What Changes at Level 2

Reaching the **Level 2 Intermediate License** is a big step — you can finally drive **alone** in Michigan. But the state still treats you as a new driver, and two restrictions shape almost every trip: a **nighttime curfew** and a **teen passenger limit**. These rules apply until you turn 17 and move up to Level 3.

## The Nighttime Driving Rule

Level 2 drivers may **not** drive between **10:00 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.**

Michigan allows four exceptions:

1. You are **driving to or from work** (or driving during work as part of the job).
2. You are **driving to or from an authorized activity** sponsored by a school, civic, or religious organization.
3. You are **accompanied by a parent, legal guardian, or a licensed driver 21 or older** in the front passenger seat.
4. You are responding to a **bona fide emergency**.

Day-to-day, that means: late-night movie with friends? Either be home by 10:00 or have a parent ride along. Closing shift at a restaurant? Allowed — but keep a recent pay stub or schedule in the glove box in case you are pulled over.

## The Teen Passenger Rule

Level 2 drivers may carry **no more than one passenger under age 21** at a time.

Exceptions:

- The extra passengers are **immediate family members** (siblings, step-siblings, etc.).
- You are **driving to or from school or a school-sanctioned event**.
- A **parent, legal guardian, or licensed driver 21+** is in the vehicle.

This rule trips up a lot of new drivers. Three friends piling into the back to grab tacos = a violation. Two siblings plus one friend = fine, because siblings don''t count toward the limit. Driving the carpool to a school robotics meet = fine, because it is a school-sanctioned activity.

## Why These Restrictions Exist

National crash data shows the **first 6–12 months of unsupervised teen driving** are by far the most dangerous period of a person''s driving career. Two of the highest-risk factors are **late-night driving** (fatigue + lower visibility + higher impaired-driver share) and **teen passengers** (each additional teen in the car raises crash risk substantially). Michigan''s GDL restrictions are designed to remove the most dangerous combinations while you build experience.

## Consequences of Violating Level 2 Restrictions

A GDL restriction violation is a **civil infraction**. It goes on your driving record and:

- Triggers a **letter to your parents**.
- May **reset the 90-day clean-record clock** required before you can move up to Level 3.
- Can lead to **license suspension or restriction** if violations accumulate.
- Will likely **raise your family''s auto insurance premium**.

Getting caught with a phone in your hand carries an additional fine under Michigan''s hands-free law, even if you weren''t otherwise breaking a GDL rule.

## Practical Tips

- **Use a curfew alarm.** Set your phone to remind you at 9:30 p.m. to start heading home.
- **Count heads before you pull out of the driveway.** If you have more than one passenger under 21 and they aren''t all family or school-bound, you are not legal to drive.
- **Keep proof of work/school activity** in the car for nighttime exceptions.
- **Mount your phone before you start the car** and use voice commands only — both the GDL and the hands-free law forbid touching it while driving.

## Moving to Level 3

At **age 17**, after holding Level 2 for at least **6 months with no moving violations or at-fault crashes in the prior 12 months**, your full Level 3 license can be issued — and the nighttime and passenger restrictions drop away.
', 30, 1
);
