INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mn_mn-blue-card-permit-process', 'module_mn_overlay', 'mn-blue-card-permit-process', 'How to Get Your Minnesota Instruction Permit (the Blue Card Process)', '# How to Get Your Minnesota Instruction Permit

Minnesota uses a Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) system, which means new drivers earn full driving privileges in stages. The very first stage is the **Instruction Permit**, and getting it requires a special document called the **Blue Card**. This lesson walks you through every step.

## Who Issues What

Two organizations are involved in getting your permit:

- **Your driver education school** (that''s us) issues the **Blue Card** once you finish the classroom portion.
- The **Minnesota Department of Public Safety - Driver and Vehicle Services (DVS)** issues the **Instruction Permit** after you pass the knowledge test.

You cannot take the knowledge test without the Blue Card. The Blue Card is your proof to DVS that you completed the required classroom training.

## Step 1: Be at Least 15 Years Old

Minnesota law requires you to be **at least 15 years old** before you can hold an instruction permit. You can start classroom driver education before your 15th birthday, but you cannot take the DVS knowledge test or receive your permit until you turn 15.

## Step 2: Complete 30 Hours of Classroom Instruction

Minnesota requires **30 hours of classroom driver education** from a state-approved provider. These hours cover traffic laws, signs and signals, defensive driving, the dangers of impaired and distracted driving, and Minnesota-specific rules.

You must attend the full 30 hours. There are no shortcuts and no test-out option in Minnesota for the classroom requirement. Most schools spread the hours across several weeks of evening or weekend sessions.

## Step 3: Parent or Guardian Enrollment in the Supervised Driving Program

Before the Blue Card can be issued, a parent or legal guardian must complete a brief **online supplemental parental awareness course** (approximately 90 minutes, offered free by DPS). This course explains the GDL system, the supervised driving log, and the parent''s role in keeping the new driver safe. Parents receive a certificate when they finish, and that certificate is part of the permit application packet.

## Step 4: Receive Your Blue Card

Once you have completed all 30 classroom hours and your parent has finished the awareness course, your driver education school will issue you a **Blue Card** (officially the *Driver Education Classroom Completion Certificate*). This is a physical paper document - keep it safe and do not lose it.

## Step 5: Take the Knowledge Test at DVS

Bring the following to a DVS exam station:

- Your Blue Card.
- Proof of identity (birth certificate or passport).
- Proof of Minnesota residence.
- Social Security number.
- A parent or guardian to sign the application (if you are under 18).
- The application fee.

The knowledge test has 40 questions on Minnesota traffic laws, road signs, and safe driving practices. You must score **80% or higher** to pass. If you fail, you can retake it (usually after a one-day waiting period and an additional fee).

## Step 6: Hold the Permit for at Least 6 Months

Once you receive the permit, you must hold it for a **minimum of six months** before you can apply for a provisional license - and that six months must be **violation-free** for the last six months. During this time, you must always drive with a licensed driver age 21 or older in the front passenger seat.

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- Losing the Blue Card (replacements require contacting your school).
- Forgetting to bring a parent to sign at DVS.
- Assuming a passed final exam in class = a permit. It doesn''t. You still need DVS.
- Letting the parent awareness course slip - it blocks Blue Card issuance.

Finish all 30 hours, get the parent course done, collect your Blue Card, and head to DVS. That''s the Minnesota permit path.', 35, 0
);
