INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions_0', 'quiz_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions', 'During the first six months of a Minnesota provisional license, what is the nighttime driving rule?', '["No driving between 10:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m. under any circumstances","No driving between midnight and 5:00 a.m. unless accompanied by a licensed driver age 25+, driving to/from work, or driving for an employer","No driving after 9:00 p.m. unless accompanied by any licensed adult","There is no nighttime restriction on a provisional license"]', 1, 'Minnesota''s GDL prohibits provisional license holders from driving between midnight and 5:00 a.m. during the first six months, with exceptions for driving with a licensed driver 25+, for work-related travel, or for an employer.', 0
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions_1', 'quiz_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions', 'During the first six months of a provisional license, how many passengers under 20 (not counting immediate family) can a teen driver carry?', '["Zero","No more than one","No more than three","Unlimited"]', 1, 'First six months: maximum of one passenger under age 20 (excluding immediate family). Second six months: maximum of three passengers under 20.', 1
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions_2', 'quiz_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions', 'Under Minnesota''s teen driver phone rules, when may a driver under 18 with a permit or provisional license use a cell phone while driving?', '["Anytime, as long as it is hands-free","Only for navigation via voice commands","Only to call 911 in an emergency","Only when the vehicle is moving under 25 mph"]', 2, 'Drivers under 18 with a permit or provisional license may not use a cell phone at all while driving - handheld or hands-free - with the only exception being a 911 emergency call.', 2
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions_3', 'quiz_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions', 'Minnesota is what type of seat belt enforcement state?', '["Secondary enforcement - officers can only cite for seat belts after stopping for another violation","Primary enforcement - officers can stop a vehicle for a seat belt violation alone, and all occupants must be belted","Optional - adults are exempt","Front seat only - back seat passengers do not need to be belted"]', 1, 'Minnesota is a primary enforcement state. Officers can pull you over solely for a seat belt violation, and every occupant in every seating position must be belted.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions_4', 'quiz_mn_mn-gdl-restrictions', 'What happens after a SECOND GDL violation on a provisional license in Minnesota?', '["A warning letter and a fine","A 30-day license suspension","A 180-day license suspension plus driver improvement programs","Immediate revocation until age 21"]', 1, 'A second GDL violation results in a 30-day license suspension. A first violation triggers a warning and fine; a third violation triggers a 180-day suspension plus additional driver improvement requirements.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mn_mn-rules-and-quirks', 'module_mn_overlay', 'mn-rules-and-quirks', 'Minnesota Road Rules and Quirks Every Driver Should Know', '# Minnesota Road Rules and Quirks

Every state has rules that surprise drivers from somewhere else - and a few that surprise the locals too. This lesson covers the Minnesota-specific traffic laws and driving conditions you need to understand to drive safely and pass the road test.

## Move Over Law (Ted Foss Law)

Minnesota''s **Ted Foss Move Over Law** is named for a State Patrol trooper killed by a passing vehicle during a traffic stop in 2000. On any road with two or more lanes in your direction, when you approach a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, road maintenance vehicle, construction vehicle, or utility vehicle with flashing lights, you must:

- **Move over one full lane away** from the stopped vehicle if it is safe to do so, OR
- If you cannot safely move over, **slow down to a safe and reasonable speed** below the posted limit.

Violations carry a fine of around $100 plus court fees. This is one of the most-tested laws on the Minnesota knowledge exam.

## Headlights On When Wipers Are On

Minnesota law requires you to **turn on your headlights anytime your windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to weather conditions (rain, snow, fog, sleet). Daytime running lights do not satisfy this requirement - you must turn on the full headlight circuit so your taillights also illuminate, making you visible from behind.

## Roundabouts

Minnesota has built hundreds of roundabouts in the last two decades. The rules:

- **Yield to traffic already in the roundabout** (traffic on your left).
- Do not stop in the roundabout.
- Use your right turn signal when you intend to exit.
- For multi-lane roundabouts, choose your lane based on your exit before entering: right lane for the first exit/right turns, left lane for further exits/left turns or U-turns.
- **Always yield to pedestrians** in crosswalks at the entry and exit.
- If an emergency vehicle approaches, exit the roundabout first, then pull over - do not stop inside the circle.

## Winter Driving Reality

Minnesota winters are not optional knowledge - they will be part of your driving life. Key rules:

- **Studded tires are illegal** for most passenger vehicles in Minnesota. Use proper all-season or dedicated winter tires instead.
- **Snow emergencies** in cities like Minneapolis and St. Paul trigger temporary parking restrictions; violations result in tickets and towing. Sign up for snow emergency alerts wherever you live.
- **Black ice** forms on bridges and overpasses first because cold air circulates underneath. Reduce speed on bridges in cold weather even if pavement looks clear.
- **Do not use cruise control on wet, snowy, or icy roads** - the cruise will keep applying power on a slick surface and send you into a skid.

## School Bus Stop Arms

When a school bus stops and extends its stop arm with red lights flashing:

- **All traffic in both directions must stop** on a two-lane road or any undivided road.
- On a divided highway with a physical median or barrier, only traffic following the bus must stop. Oncoming traffic across the median may proceed with caution.
- Stay stopped until the arm retracts and the red lights stop flashing.

Violations are aggressively enforced and carry fines of $500 or more.

## Funeral Processions

Minnesota grants funeral processions the right to proceed through intersections together once the lead vehicle has legally entered. Other drivers must yield to the procession, even at green lights. Procession vehicles typically have headlights on, hazard flashers, and small flags or markers.

## DWI and the Not-a-Drop Law

Minnesota''s general DWI limit is **0.08% BAC** for drivers 21 and older. But for drivers **under 21**, Minnesota has a **"Not a Drop" law**: any detectable alcohol in your system results in a DWI charge and license suspension. There is no acceptable amount of alcohol for an under-21 driver. Marijuana, even where legal recreationally, is also illegal to use while driving and during the GDL phase is treated harshly.

## Booster Seat and Child Restraint

Children must use a child restraint until they are **at least 8 years old or 4 feet 9 inches tall**, whichever comes first. As a teen driver who may be transporting younger siblings, this is your responsibility to enforce before you put the car in gear.

Learn these Minnesota-specific rules cold. They appear on the knowledge test, on the road test, and - more importantly - in your daily driving for the rest of your life in this state.', 30, 2
);
