INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mo_missouri-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_mo_overlay', 'missouri-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Missouri GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Living With Missouri''s GDL Restrictions

Once you turn 16 and pass your driving test, you''ll receive an **Intermediate License**. This isn''t the same as a full driver license - it carries restrictions designed to ease you into independent driving during your highest-risk years. Understanding these rules isn''t just about avoiding tickets; it''s about keeping yourself, your passengers, and other drivers safe.

## The Nighttime Driving Rule

Missouri intermediate license holders **may not drive between 1:00 a.m. and 5:00 a.m.** unless one of these exceptions applies:

- You''re driving to or from a **school activity**
- You''re driving to or from your **job**
- You''re responding to an **emergency**
- You''re accompanied by a parent, guardian, or qualified driver age 21+

This matters in everyday situations: leaving a friend''s house at 1:30 a.m., heading home from a late movie, or picking someone up from the airport. Plan ahead. If your shift ends at midnight, you''re fine to drive home - but if you stop for food and leave the restaurant at 1:15 a.m., you''re now in violation unless you can show the drive is part of getting home from work.

## Passenger Limits

For your **first 6 months** on an intermediate license, you may carry **no more than one passenger under age 19** who is not an immediate family member. After 6 months, that limit increases to **no more than three passengers under age 19** who are not immediate family.

Immediate family (parents, siblings, grandparents, your own children) don''t count toward the limit. The reasoning is well-established by research: teen drivers with teen passengers are dramatically more likely to crash, and risk increases with each additional teen passenger.

Real-world example: it''s homecoming weekend and four friends want a ride. If you''ve been licensed three months, you can only take one. If you''ve been licensed eight months, you can take three. Either way, consider whether someone with a full license should drive.

## Seat Belt Rule

Under Missouri law, every person in the vehicle must wear a seat belt when the driver is under 18. There is no "backseat exemption" for teen drivers as there can be for adult drivers in Missouri. If a passenger is unbelted, you - the driver - can be cited.

## Cell Phones and Hands-Free Law

Missouri''s **Siddens Bening Hands Free Law** (effective August 2023) prohibits all drivers from physically holding or supporting a cell phone or other electronic communication device while driving. For drivers **under 21**, the law is even stricter: any use of a hand-held electronic communication device while operating a motor vehicle is prohibited.

This means:

- **No texting**, ever
- **No holding** the phone to talk
- **No scrolling, watching video, or social media** while driving
- Hands-free (Bluetooth, dashboard mount, voice commands) is the only acceptable use for adults; for under-21 drivers, even hands-free use is restricted in many situations

Mount your phone before you start driving. Set up navigation, your playlist, and your texts-to-respond before you put the car in gear.

## Consequences for Violations

Violating intermediate license restrictions can extend the time before you''re eligible for a full license, add points to your record, and trigger insurance rate increases. In Missouri, accumulating **8 points in 18 months** results in license suspension. Teen drivers face additional scrutiny - some violations that wouldn''t suspend an adult license can suspend a teen''s.

## Moving to a Full License

At **age 18**, if you have a clean record (no alcohol-related convictions, no traffic convictions in the prior 12 months for serious offenses), your intermediate license converts to a full driver license. Some drivers need to visit the license office; others receive it automatically. Check your status before your 18th birthday.', 30, 1
);
