INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mo_missouri-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_mo_overlay', 'missouri-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Missouri-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Rules and Quirks Unique to Driving in Missouri

Every state has its own combination of traffic laws, road designs, and driving culture. Missouri is no exception. Here are the rules and conditions that can trip up newer drivers - and even out-of-state visitors - if they don''t know what to expect.

## The Missouri Stoplight Law (Dead Red Law)

Missouri is one of a handful of states with a "Dead Red Law." If you arrive at a traffic signal that fails to detect your vehicle (often the case on motorcycles or in early-morning hours when sensors miss small cars), you may proceed through the red light **after waiting a reasonable amount of time** - generally accepted as a full signal cycle or more - and **only after determining it''s safe**. This is one of the few legal exceptions to running a red light in the state. It is intended for malfunctioning lights, not for impatience.

## Right Turn on Red

Missouri allows right turns on red after a complete stop, unless a sign specifically prohibits it. Some intersections in St. Louis, Kansas City, and college towns post **"No Turn on Red"** signs, especially in heavy pedestrian areas. Always look for the sign before turning.

## Move Over Law

Missouri''s Move Over law requires drivers approaching a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, MoDOT vehicle, or utility vehicle with flashing lights to **change lanes away from the vehicle** if it''s safe to do so. If you can''t change lanes, you must **slow down and proceed with caution**. This applies on all roads, not just interstates. Penalties are stiff and increase when emergency workers are injured.

## School Bus Stop-Arm Rule

When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and stop-arm extended, **all traffic in both directions must stop** on a two-lane road. On a **divided highway with a physical median or barrier**, only traffic traveling in the same direction as the bus must stop. This is a common point of confusion: a painted center line is NOT a median - you must still stop. Penalties include fines, points, and possible license suspension.

## Headlights and Wipers

Missouri law requires headlights to be turned on **30 minutes after sunset until 30 minutes before sunrise**, and **any time visibility is less than 500 feet** due to weather. While Missouri does not have an explicit "wipers on, lights on" statute like some states, the low-visibility rule effectively requires headlights any time you''re using your wipers continuously in rain or fog.

## Severe Weather Awareness

Missouri sits in a region that sees **tornadoes, ice storms, flash flooding, and dense fog**. A few specific rules and habits:

- **Never drive through standing water.** "Turn Around, Don''t Drown" is law-enforcement guidance with the force of common sense - it takes only 6-12 inches of moving water to sweep a car away. Many low-water crossings in rural Missouri have signs and depth markers.
- During a **tornado warning**, do not try to outrun a tornado in your car. Exit the vehicle and seek shelter in a sturdy building or low-lying ditch away from the vehicle.
- On **icy bridges and overpasses**, slow down. Bridges freeze before roads because they''re exposed to cold air on all sides.

## Deer Country

Missouri has a substantial deer population, and **deer-vehicle collisions** spike during fall rut (October-December) and at dawn/dusk year-round. If a deer enters the road:

- **Brake firmly, but do not swerve.** Swerving causes loss-of-control crashes that are often worse than the deer strike.
- Use **high beams when possible** on rural roads to spot eye-shine from the shoulder.
- If you hit a deer, pull over safely, call local authorities, and do not approach a wounded animal.

## Highway and Interstate Quirks

Missouri uses **lettered routes** (Route Z, Route AA, Route DD) for state-maintained secondary roads, in addition to numbered highways. These are sometimes called "supplemental routes" and are common in rural areas. They can be narrow, winding, and lightly maintained - drive accordingly.

The **I-70 corridor** between St. Louis and Kansas City sees heavy truck traffic. Keep right except to pass, and watch for sudden slowdowns near major interchanges. Many sections have ongoing construction.

## Real ID and Your License

Missouri offers both a **REAL ID-compliant** license (marked with a star) and a non-compliant license. Starting May 7, 2025, only REAL ID-compliant licenses are accepted for boarding domestic flights and entering federal facilities. When you apply for your full license at 18, ask about REAL ID requirements and bring the additional documents required.', 30, 2
);
