INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ms_how-to-get-a-mississippi-learners-permit', 'module_ms_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-mississippi-learners-permit', 'How to Get a Mississippi Learner''s Permit', '# Getting Your Mississippi Learner''s Permit

Mississippi uses a three-stage Graduated Driver License (GDL) system designed to ease new drivers into full driving privileges. The journey starts with the Learner''s Permit, issued by the Mississippi Department of Public Safety (DPS) through its Driver Service Bureau examination stations located across the state.

## Eligibility

To apply for a Mississippi Learner''s Permit, you must:

- Be at least **15 years old**
- Be enrolled in school, have graduated, or have a high school equivalency (Mississippi has school attendance requirements tied to licensing for those under 18)
- Have parental or guardian consent if under 18
- Pass a vision screening
- Pass the written knowledge test

## Documents to Bring

When you visit a Driver Service Bureau location, plan to bring:

1. **Proof of identity** - a certified birth certificate or U.S. passport
2. **Proof of Social Security number** - your Social Security card or a W-2
3. **Two proofs of Mississippi residency** - a utility bill, lease, school record, or similar document showing your name and Mississippi address (parent''s documents work for minors)
4. **Proof of school enrollment or graduation** - a current report card, transcript, or letter from your school certifying enrollment and satisfactory attendance, or a diploma/GED
5. **Parental consent** - a parent or legal guardian must sign the application in person
6. **Payment** - the permit fee (currently around $5 for the learner''s permit, separate from later license fees)

Always check the DPS website before going - document and fee requirements occasionally change.

## The Knowledge Test

The written test is based on the **Mississippi Driver''s Manual**, which you can download free from the DPS website. The test covers:

- Mississippi traffic laws
- Road signs and pavement markings
- Safe driving practices
- Right-of-way rules
- Effects of alcohol and drugs on driving

The test is typically multiple choice. Study the manual thoroughly - many first-time test-takers fail because they relied only on online practice quizzes. If you fail, Mississippi requires a waiting period before retesting.

## Vision Screening

DPS will check your vision on-site. You must meet minimum acuity standards (generally 20/40 with or without corrective lenses). If you wear glasses or contacts for the test, your permit and later license will be marked with a corrective-lens restriction.

## After You Pass

With permit in hand, you may drive **only when accompanied by a licensed driver 21 years of age or older** seated in the front passenger seat. The supervising driver must be alert and able to take control if needed - they are legally responsible for your driving.

## Holding Period

You must hold the Learner''s Permit for **at least 12 months** (or until age 16, whichever is longer) before you are eligible to apply for an Intermediate License. Use this year to log practice in varied conditions: daytime, nighttime, rain, highway, parking lots, and residential streets.

## What''s Next?

After 12 months of permit-holding and on or after your 16th birthday, you can return to DPS for the road skills test to earn your Intermediate License - the second stage of the Mississippi GDL.', 35, 0
);
