INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mt_how-to-get-a-montana-permit', 'module_mt_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-montana-permit', 'How to Get Your Montana Traffic Education Learner License', '# How to Get Your Montana Traffic Education Learner License

Montana lets teens start the licensing process earlier than many other states, but only if you go through an approved Traffic Education program. This lesson walks you through exactly what you need to do, in the right order, to get your **Traffic Education Learner License (TELL)** from the Montana Motor Vehicle Division (MVD).

## Step 1: Confirm you''re eligible

To apply for a Traffic Education Learner License you must be **at least 14 years and 6 months old** on the day you apply. If you do not enroll in an approved traffic education course, you cannot get a learner license until you turn 16. That six-month head start is the whole reason most Montana teens take driver education.

You must also be enrolled in school (or have completed school) and be making satisfactory progress. Montana requires proof that you are not a habitual truant.

## Step 2: Enroll in an approved Traffic Education course

Approved courses are offered through public high schools (overseen by the Montana Office of Public Instruction, OPI) and through commercial driving schools licensed by OPI. A complete course includes:

- **Classroom instruction** (around 30 hours of seat time on traffic law, risk awareness, vehicle systems, impairment, and Montana-specific topics).
- **Behind-the-wheel (BTW) instruction** with a certified instructor (about 6 hours of actual driving, typically paired with observation time).
- **Parent or guardian involvement**, including a parent meeting and a signed log of at-home practice.

Once you''ve enrolled, the school can issue paperwork that lets you apply for the learner license so you can start practicing with a parent between BTW sessions.

## Step 3: Gather your documents

When you visit an MVD county driver exam station, bring:

- **Proof of identity** (certified birth certificate or U.S. passport).
- **Proof of Social Security number** (Social Security card, W-2, or paystub showing the full SSN).
- **Two proofs of Montana residency** (utility bill, school record, lease, etc.) in a parent''s name is acceptable if you live with them.
- **Parent or guardian signature** on the application. A parent or legal guardian must sign in person to accept financial responsibility.
- **Traffic education enrollment verification** from your course provider.
- **Application fee** (check the current MVD fee schedule).

If you wear glasses or contacts, bring them — you''ll take a vision screening.

## Step 4: Pass the knowledge and vision tests

The knowledge test is based on the current **Montana Driver Manual**, which you can download free from the MVD website. Expect questions on right-of-way, speed limits (including Montana''s basic rule), road signs, alcohol and drug laws, and GDL restrictions. The vision screening checks acuity and peripheral vision.

## Step 5: Practice safely while you hold the permit

With your Traffic Education Learner License you can drive **only when accompanied by a licensed driver 18 or older** who is seated next to you. You must hold the permit for **at least 6 months with a clean record** (no alcohol/drug offenses, no major violations) and log **50 hours of supervised driving, including 10 hours at night**, before you''re eligible for the next step — the restricted (provisional) license at age 15.

## Common mistakes to avoid

- Showing up without **both** parents'' or guardians'' required documents.
- Letting the permit lapse — if it expires you''ll have to start over.
- Driving without your supervising adult in the front seat, even "just down the block." That ends the permit and resets the clock.
- Forgetting to log practice hours. Most schools require the log before they sign off your course completion certificate.

Driver education in Montana isn''t just a class — it''s the legal gateway to driving before 16. Treat the permit period as the most important practice time of your life.', 45, 0
);
