INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mt_mt-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_mt_overlay', 'mt-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Montana GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Montana GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Once you upgrade from your learner license to a **restricted (provisional) license** at age 15, you can finally drive alone. But Montana''s Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) law puts real limits on **when** you can drive and **who** you can carry. These limits aren''t just legal trivia — they show up every weekend, every late shift, and every time your friends ask for a ride.

## The two rules that matter most

### 1. The nighttime rule

During the **first six months** of holding a restricted license, you may not drive between **11:00 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.** unless one of the following is true:

- A licensed parent or legal guardian is in the front passenger seat.
- You are driving to or from work, and you have documentation (pay stub, schedule).
- You are driving to or from a school event or school-sanctioned activity.

That means "my friend''s house" or "a late movie" do **not** qualify. If you get pulled over at 11:45 p.m. coming back from a friend''s, you can be cited for a GDL violation, and the clock on your six-month restriction can restart.

### 2. The passenger rule

For the **first six months** of the restricted license, you may carry **no more than one passenger under age 18** who is not an immediate family member.

For the **second six months**, that limit increases to **no more than three passengers under age 18** who are not immediate family.

Siblings, step-siblings, and other immediate family members don''t count toward the limit, but everyone in the car must still be seat-belted.

## Why these rules exist

Crash data is brutally clear: teen drivers are several times more likely to crash with multiple teen passengers in the car, and night driving roughly doubles fatal crash risk for new drivers. Montana''s rural roads — long distances between towns, animals on the road, ice from October through April — make those risks even sharper. The GDL rules are designed to keep your highest-risk situations (late at night, distracted by friends) from happening before you have the experience to handle them.

## Real-life scenarios

- **Friday night football game ends at 10:45 p.m.** You can drive home from a school activity even past 11:00 p.m. Keep the game schedule or a coach''s note in the glove box in case you''re stopped.
- **Closing shift at a restaurant ends at midnight.** Legal — bring your work schedule or pay stub. Don''t make a side trip to get food with co-workers; that''s no longer "to or from work."
- **Three friends want a ride home from practice.** In your first six months, you can only take one non-family passenger. The others need another ride.
- **Driving your little sister and her two friends to a sleepover at 9 p.m.** Your sister doesn''t count; the two friends are two passengers under 18. In your first six months, that''s a violation.

## Seat belts, alcohol, and phones

- **Seat belts:** Everyone in the car must be belted. Montana''s seat belt law is a secondary offense for adults but is enforced strictly for GDL holders.
- **Alcohol/drugs:** Montana has a **zero-tolerance** law for drivers under 21. Any detectable alcohol (0.02% BAC or above) is a violation, which will reset your GDL clock and can suspend your license.
- **Cell phones:** Montana has no statewide handheld ban, but many Montana cities do (Billings, Bozeman, Missoula, Helena, Whitefish, and others). As a restricted license holder, treat any handheld phone use as a violation — it''s the single biggest distraction risk for new drivers.

## What happens if you break a GDL rule

A GDL violation can result in a citation, fines, and — most importantly — a **restart of the six-month restriction clock**. Two violations can extend your restricted-license period until you are 18. Insurance rates will also jump.

The restricted license is freedom with training wheels. Respect the limits and you''ll roll into a full license at 16 with a clean record.', 40, 1
);
