INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_mt_montana-specific-driving-rules-and-quirks', 'module_mt_overlay', 'montana-specific-driving-rules-and-quirks', 'Montana-Specific Rules, Hazards, and Quirks', '# Montana-Specific Rules, Hazards, and Quirks

Montana drivers face conditions you simply don''t see in most other states: 70+ mph rural interstates, long stretches of road with no cell service, snow and ice for half the year, open-range cattle that genuinely have right-of-way over your bumper, and wildlife that can total a car in a single second. This lesson covers the Montana-specific rules and conditions every new driver should internalize before heading out alone.

## Speed limits and the "basic rule"

Montana''s maximum daytime speed limit is **80 mph on rural interstates** and **70 mph on most other rural highways**. In urban interstates the limit drops to **65 mph**, and on city streets the default urban speed limit is **25 mph** unless posted otherwise.

But posted limits are only the ceiling. Montana law applies a **"basic rule"**: you must drive at a speed that is **reasonable and prudent** for the conditions. In a snowstorm, on black ice, in heavy smoke from a wildfire, or behind a slow-moving farm tractor, the safe speed is well below the posted limit — and you can be cited for driving "too fast for conditions" even if you were under the sign.

## Open range and livestock on the road

Much of central and eastern Montana is **open range**, meaning livestock can lawfully roam onto highways. In open-range country, if you hit a cow, **you (or your insurance) may be liable for the value of the animal**, not the rancher. Watch for:

- **Cattle guards** in the pavement marking range boundaries.
- **"Open Range" signs** with silhouettes of cattle.
- Cows, horses, or sheep on the shoulder, especially at dawn and dusk.

Slow down, give animals a wide berth, and never assume they will move out of your way.

## Wildlife collisions

Montana is one of the highest states in the nation for animal-vehicle collisions. **Deer, elk, antelope, moose, and even bears** routinely cross highways, especially:

- **Dawn and dusk** (the highest-risk windows).
- **Fall rut season** (October–November) for deer and elk.
- **Spring** when animals move to greener pastures and follow water.

If an animal is in the road, **brake hard in a straight line** rather than swerving. Swerving causes rollovers, head-on collisions, and run-off-road crashes — usually far worse than hitting the animal. Use your **high beams** on dark rural roads when no oncoming traffic is present so you have more time to see eyeshine.

## Winter driving

From roughly October through April you should expect snow, ice, blowing snow, and rapid temperature swings. Practical rules:

- Carry a **winter survival kit**: blanket, water, snacks, jumper cables, flashlight, ice scraper, traction aid (sand or kitty litter), and a charged phone.
- Slow down well before bridges and overpasses — they freeze first.
- Use the Montana 511 system (call **511** or visit the MDT 511 website) for road conditions before any trip over 50 miles in winter.
- Don''t use cruise control on slick roads.

## Cell phone laws by city

There is **no statewide handheld or texting ban** in Montana, which surprises drivers from other states. However, many cities and counties **do** ban texting and/or handheld use, including Billings, Bozeman, Missoula, Helena, Whitefish, and Butte-Silver Bow. The rule changes as you cross a city limit sign. The safe approach: **never touch your phone while driving in Montana**, regardless of where you are.

## Move Over Law and emergency vehicles

Montana''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers to change lanes away from any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or highway maintenance vehicle with flashing lights. If you can''t safely change lanes, slow down significantly. Volunteer firefighters with blue flashing lights are also covered.

## Headlights and visibility

Montana requires headlights to be on **from a half-hour after sunset to a half-hour before sunrise** and **whenever weather conditions reduce visibility** such that you can''t clearly see persons or vehicles 500 feet away. "Daytime running lights" are not the same as headlights — your taillights are off, which is dangerous in rain, snow, or smoke.

## Putting it together

Montana driving rewards drivers who plan ahead: check road conditions, slow for animals and weather, never assume the next town is close, and treat the basic-rule standard as your real speed limit. Posted signs are written for perfect conditions — and perfect conditions are rare in Montana.', 40, 2
);
