INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nc_how-to-get-a-permit-in-north-carolina', 'module_nc_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-north-carolina', 'How to Get Your Limited Learner Permit in North Carolina', '## Getting Your Limited Learner Permit (Level 1) in North Carolina

North Carolina uses a three-stage Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) system. The first stage is the **Limited Learner Permit**, also called **Level 1**. You can apply as soon as you turn **15**, but several requirements have to line up before the NCDMV will hand over that permit.

### Step 1: Complete a state-approved driver education course

Before you can even apply, anyone under 18 must finish an NCDMV-approved driver education program. The standard course is:

- **30 hours of classroom instruction**
- **6 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW) instruction** with a certified driver education instructor

Driver education is offered free of charge through North Carolina public high schools, though many districts contract delivery to private providers. When you finish, your instructor (or the school) gives you a **Driver Education Certificate (form DL-300)**. Keep this safe — it has an expiration window and you cannot get a permit without it.

### Step 2: Get a Driving Eligibility Certificate (DEC)

North Carolina is one of the few states that ties driving privileges directly to school performance. Under the **"Lose Control, Lose Your License"** law, anyone under 18 must present a **Driving Eligibility Certificate (DEC)** signed by their school principal or designee. The DEC certifies that the student is:

- Enrolled in school (or has graduated, has a GED, or meets a hardship exemption), **and**
- Making adequate academic progress, **and**
- Has not been suspended for certain disciplinary reasons within the last academic semester

The DEC is valid for **30 days** from issuance — schedule your NCDMV appointment accordingly.

### Step 3: Gather your documents

When you visit a NCDMV Driver License Office, bring:

- Your **Driver Education Certificate (DL-300)**
- Your **Driving Eligibility Certificate (DEC)**
- Proof of identity and date of birth (certified birth certificate or valid U.S. passport)
- Proof of Social Security number
- **Two** proofs of North Carolina residency (utility bill, lease, school record, etc.)
- A **parent or legal guardian** who must sign the liability statement in person
- The permit fee (currently in the low-$20 range; check NCDMV.gov for current amount)

### Step 4: Pass the tests

At the office you will take:

- A **vision screening**
- A **traffic sign identification** test
- A **25-question written knowledge test** (you must answer at least 20 correctly — 80%)

The knowledge test is drawn from the **North Carolina Driver''s Handbook**, which is free to download from NCDMV.gov. Read it cover-to-cover at least once — the questions cover right-of-way, signs and signals, alcohol law, and NC-specific GDL rules.

### Step 5: Drive on Level 1

Once you pass, your Limited Learner Permit is valid for **18 months** and you must hold it for **at least 12 months** with no convictions for moving violations in the last 6 months before you can move up to Level 2. While on Level 1 you must:

- Always drive with a **supervising driver** (parent, guardian, or person approved by parent) age 21+ who is licensed and seated in the front passenger seat
- For the **first 6 months**, drive only between **5:00 a.m. and 9:00 p.m.**
- After 6 months, you may drive any time with the supervising driver
- Log **at least 60 hours** of supervised practice (including at least 10 hours at night) before advancing to Level 2
- Have every occupant wear a seat belt

Plan your 12-month permit phase deliberately — every supervised hour counts.', 35, 0
);
