INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nc_nc-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_nc_overlay', 'nc-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Living With NC GDL Restrictions: Levels 1, 2, and 3', '## What North Carolina''s GDL Restrictions Actually Look Like Day-to-Day

The NC Graduated Driver Licensing program has three levels, and the restrictions tighten or loosen at each step. Understanding exactly what you can and cannot do — and what counts as a violation — keeps you on track for full licensure at 16.5.

### Level 1 — Limited Learner Permit (age 15+)

Level 1 is the supervised-only phase.

- **Supervisor required at all times.** A parent, legal guardian, or other adult age 21+ approved by your parent must sit in the front passenger seat. They must have a valid driver license and have held it at least 5 years.
- **Time-of-day restriction.** For the first 6 months: 5 a.m. to 9 p.m. only. After 6 months: any time, still with supervisor.
- **Passengers.** Only the supervisor in the front seat. Back-seat passengers must be **immediate family** or other **fellow driver-education students**. No carloads of friends.
- **Seat belts.** Every passenger, every seat, every trip. No exceptions.
- **Phone.** Under 18, no mobile phone use of any kind while driving (see Lesson 3).
- **Clean record.** No moving-violation convictions in the last 6 months before applying for Level 2.

### Level 2 — Limited Provisional License (age 16+)

This is when many teens think they have a "real" license — but it''s still restricted.

To qualify you must have held Level 1 for **at least 12 months**, completed your **60 supervised hours**, passed the **road test**, and presented a **fresh DEC**.

Restrictions:

- **No driving between 9:00 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.** unless: driving directly to or from work, volunteer fire/rescue/EMS service, or a supervising driver is in the front passenger seat.
- **Passenger limit.** No more than **one passenger under age 21** who is not an immediate family member — unless a parent or supervising driver is in the front seat. "Immediate family" means parents, stepparents, siblings (including half- and stepsiblings), and children.
- **Seat belts and phone rules** still apply (and the phone rule applies to all drivers under 18 regardless of level).

Real-world examples:

- Driving your little sister and one teammate to practice at 4 p.m.: **OK** (sister is immediate family; one non-family teen under 21 is the limit).
- Driving three friends from school: **violation** (too many under-21 non-family passengers).
- Coming home from a closing shift at a restaurant at 11:30 p.m. with your work apron still on: **OK** (work exception applies — keep your schedule or paystub in the car).
- Driving to a friend''s house at 10 p.m. just to hang out: **violation** (no work, no rescue, no supervisor).

### Level 3 — Full Provisional License (age 16.5+)

To qualify you must hold Level 2 for **at least 6 months**, log another **12 hours of supervised driving** (6 at night), and present another DEC. Once granted, **all GDL restrictions are lifted** — but you still:

- Cannot use a mobile phone while driving until age 18
- Must obey the .00 BAC zero-tolerance law (any detectable alcohol = DWI for under-21)
- Lose your license if convicted of certain school-related offenses (Lose Control, Lose Your License)

### Consequences of breaking a GDL restriction

A GDL violation is itself a moving violation. Conviction can:

- Reset your 6-month "clean record" requirement, delaying advancement
- Add points to your license (NC uses both DMV points and insurance points)
- Trigger a license suspension if combined with other violations

Treat the restrictions as a contract: follow them precisely for the duration, and the next level arrives on schedule.', 30, 1
);
