INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nc_nc-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_nc_overlay', 'nc-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'North Carolina Rules and Quirks You Won''t Find in Other States', '## NC-Specific Rules That Trip Up New Drivers

A lot of driving law is the same coast to coast — stop at red, yield to pedestrians, signal before you turn. But North Carolina has a handful of rules and quirks that are either unique to the state or stricter than what teens see in driver education videos from elsewhere. Knowing them keeps your record clean and your license intact.

### 1. "Lose Control, Lose Your License" (the DEC law)

North Carolina is one of the most aggressive states in tying driving privileges to school behavior. Under N.C.G.S. § 20-11(n1), a driver under 18 loses their permit or license if they:

- Drop out of school, **or**
- Fail to make adequate academic progress (typically passing 70% of courses), **or**
- Are suspended for more than 10 consecutive days for specific offenses (weapons, drugs/alcohol on campus, assault on a teacher, etc.)

If the school revokes your Driving Eligibility Certificate, NCDMV will suspend your driving privilege — often for a full year. Re-earning it requires a new DEC showing you''re back in good standing.

### 2. Cell phone ban for under-18 drivers

NC General Statute § 20-137.3 prohibits drivers under 18 from using **any** mobile phone or wireless communication device while operating a vehicle — including hands-free systems, Bluetooth, and earbuds. The only exceptions are:

- Calling a parent, legal guardian, or spouse
- Calling 911 in an emergency
- The vehicle is lawfully stopped or parked

Texting while driving is illegal for **all** NC drivers under § 20-137.4A, regardless of age.

### 3. Move Over Law — and it''s broad

NC requires drivers to **change lanes** (or slow significantly if changing lanes is unsafe) when approaching any stopped vehicle on the shoulder displaying flashing lights — including law enforcement, fire, EMS, **wreckers/tow trucks**, utility vehicles, and even maintenance/construction vehicles with amber lights. Violation is a Class 2 misdemeanor and a moving violation.

### 4. Open container — including for passengers

NC''s open container law applies to the **passenger area of the vehicle**, not just the driver. An open beer in the cupholder on the passenger side is a violation against the driver. For drivers under 21, having **any** alcohol in the passenger area — open or closed — unless in the trunk or behind the rearmost upright seat is illegal.

### 5. Zero tolerance for under-21

North Carolina''s DWI threshold is 0.08% BAC for adults — but for anyone under 21, **any** detectable alcohol (a BAC above 0.00) is a per se DWI. Conviction means automatic license revocation for one year, no limited driving privilege, plus court costs and possible jail.

### 6. Headlights with wipers

Under § 20-129(a)(3), if your **windshield wipers are on continuously** because of rain, snow, sleet, or fog, your **headlights must also be on** — not parking lights, headlights. Daytime running lights do not satisfy this rule because the taillights also need to be lit.

### 7. School bus stop-arm: full stop on undivided roads

When a school bus stops with its stop arm extended on a road **without a physical median or unpaved separation**, **all** traffic in both directions must stop. On a divided highway with a median, only traffic traveling in the same direction as the bus must stop. NC has "Hannah''s Law," which created enhanced penalties for passing a stopped school bus — including felony charges if a child is struck.

### 8. Right turn on red after a complete stop

Legal at most intersections unless a sign prohibits it. The catch many teens miss: you must come to a **complete** stop (wheels not rolling) before turning, and yield to all pedestrians and cross traffic. Rolling "California stops" routinely result in tickets at camera-monitored NC intersections.

### 9. Insurance is required at the time of registration

NC is one of the strictest states for verifying continuous insurance. A lapse — even one day — triggers an automatic notice from NCDMV and can result in license plate revocation and a civil penalty. As a teen added to a parent''s policy, make sure the policy is active before you drive.', 30, 2
);
