INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nd_how-to-get-a-permit-in-north-dakota', 'module_nd_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-north-dakota', 'How to Get an Instruction Permit in North Dakota', '## Earning Your North Dakota Instruction Permit

North Dakota lets teens begin the licensing process earlier than almost any other state. You can apply for an **Instruction Permit** as soon as you turn **14 years old**, a rule shaped by the state''s wide-open geography and the practical reality that many farm and ranch families rely on young drivers. Even though you can start at 14, the process still demands paperwork, parental involvement, testing, and proof that you have completed a state-approved driver education course.

### Step 1: Enroll in Approved Driver Education

If you are **under 16**, North Dakota requires you to complete an approved driver education program *before* you can be issued a Class D license. The program must include at least **30 hours of classroom instruction** and **6 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW) training** with a certified instructor. Most students take driver education through their public or private high school, but commercial driving schools licensed by the NDDOT are also acceptable. Save your completion certificate — you will hand it to the examiner.

### Step 2: Gather Your Documents

Bring the following to a **North Dakota Driver License Site**:

- **Proof of identity** (certified birth certificate or valid passport)
- **Proof of Social Security number** (Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub)
- **Two proofs of North Dakota residency** (utility bill, school record, lease)
- A **parent or legal guardian** who will sign the application — required for anyone under 18
- Your **driver education completion certificate** (if under 16)
- The **permit fee** (currently a few dollars; confirm the latest amount on the NDDOT site)

If you want a **REAL ID-compliant** permit, the document checklist is slightly stricter — bring originals, not photocopies.

### Step 3: Pass the Knowledge and Vision Tests

At the license site you will take:

1. A **vision screening** (20/40 in at least one eye, with or without corrective lenses).
2. A **written knowledge test** covering the *North Dakota Driver License Manual* — signs, signals, right-of-way, alcohol laws, and safe driving practices.
3. A **road sign identification test**.

Study the official manual cover-to-cover; the questions are pulled directly from it. Many license sites will let you retake the test the same day or after a short waiting period if you do not pass.

### Step 4: Drive With Your Permit

Once issued, the instruction permit allows you to operate a vehicle **only when accompanied by a licensed driver age 18 or older who is seated next to you in the front seat**. You must hold the permit for a minimum of **six months** before you can apply for a license, and you must remain violation-free during that period. Use this time to log the recommended **50 hours of supervised practice**, including a portion at night and in challenging conditions — winter weather is not optional in North Dakota.

### Step 5: Move to a Restricted or Full License

At **age 15** (after holding the permit for six months and completing driver education) you can test for a **restricted Class D license**, which still carries nighttime limits. At **age 16**, those restrictions lift and you become eligible for a full Class D license.

Keep the long view: every test pass, every supervised mile, and every parent signature is a step toward independence — and toward the responsibility of safely sharing North Dakota''s roads with semis, combines, and winter ice.', 35, 0
);
