INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'module_ne_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'How to Get a Permit in Nebraska', '## Overview

Nebraska''s path to driving starts with a learner''s permit issued by the Nebraska Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV). There are actually two flavors of learner''s permit, and which one you get depends on whether you are enrolled in an approved driver education course.

### The two learner''s permits

- **Learner''s Permit for Driver Education (LPE):** Issued to students who are at least 15 years old and are currently enrolled in (or about to enroll in) an approved driver education course. You only need to pass the vision and written knowledge tests to get an LPE.
- **Learner''s Permit (LPD):** Issued to applicants who are at least 15 years old but are *not* enrolled in driver education. Same vision and knowledge tests, but the LPD must be held longer before you can move up to a Provisional Operator''s Permit (POP).

Both permits require a parent or legal guardian''s signed consent if you are under 18.

### What to bring to the DMV

Nebraska is a federal REAL ID state, so you should plan to provide:

1. **Proof of identity** — certified birth certificate or U.S. passport.
2. **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN.
3. **Two proofs of Nebraska residency** — utility bill, bank statement, school enrollment letter, or similar document showing your name and Nebraska address. If you are a minor, your parent''s documents combined with a parental affidavit usually work.
4. **Parental consent form** signed in front of the DMV examiner or notarized in advance.
5. **Fees** — bring a method of payment accepted at your local office (cash, check, and most cards are typically accepted).

### The tests

- **Vision screening** — done at the counter; corrective lenses are fine and will be noted as a restriction.
- **Written knowledge test** — multiple-choice, drawn from the Nebraska Driver''s Manual. Topics include signs, signals, right-of-way, sharing the road, impaired driving laws, and Nebraska''s GDL rules. You must score at least 80% to pass.

You do *not* take a behind-the-wheel test for the learner''s permit — that comes later when you upgrade to a POP.

### After you have the permit

With either permit, you may only drive when accompanied by a licensed driver who is at least 21 years old (or a parent/guardian/spouse who is at least 19) seated in the front passenger seat. You may not use any wireless device — handheld *or* hands-free — while driving. Texting is illegal regardless of permit status.

If you are using the LPE, your time enrolled in driver education and your behind-the-wheel hours with your instructor count toward eligibility for the POP at age 16. If you are using the LPD and skipping driver education, you must hold the LPD for at least six months and self-certify 50 hours of supervised practice (including 10 nighttime hours) before applying for a POP.

### Practical tip

Most Nebraska teens choose the LPE route because it shortens the path to a license and removes the 50-hour log requirement. Confirm that your driver education provider is on the Nebraska DMV''s approved list before you enroll — only approved courses count.', 35, 0
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz (id, lessonId, title, passingScore, shuffleQuestions) VALUES (
  'quiz_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'lesson_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'Nebraska Permit Basics', 80, 1
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit_0', 'quiz_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'What is the minimum age to apply for a Nebraska learner''s permit (LPE or LPD)?', '["14","15","16","17"]', 1, 'Nebraska issues both the LPE and LPD beginning at age 15.', 0
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit_1', 'quiz_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'Which permit is issued to a 15-year-old enrolled in an approved driver education course?', '["POP (Provisional Operator''s Permit)","LPD (Learner''s Permit)","LPE (Learner''s Permit for Driver Education)","SCP (School Permit)"]', 2, 'The LPE is specifically for students enrolled in an approved Nebraska driver education course.', 1
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit_2', 'quiz_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'If a Nebraska teen does NOT take driver education, how long must they hold an LPD and how many supervised practice hours are required?', '["3 months and 25 hours","6 months and 50 hours (10 at night)","12 months and 100 hours","No minimum holding period; no hours required"]', 1, 'Without driver education, Nebraska requires a 6-month LPD holding period and 50 logged supervised hours, including 10 at night.', 2
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit_3', 'quiz_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'When driving with a Nebraska learner''s permit, who must accompany you in the front passenger seat?', '["Any licensed driver, any age","A licensed driver at least 21 (or parent/guardian/spouse at least 19)","A driving instructor only","No supervisor is required during daylight"]', 1, 'Nebraska requires a licensed driver age 21+ in the front seat, or an immediate family member age 19+.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit_4', 'quiz_ne_how-to-get-a-nebraska-permit', 'What score is required to pass Nebraska''s written knowledge test?', '["70%","75%","80%","90%"]', 2, 'Nebraska requires at least 80% on the written knowledge test.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ne_ne-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ne_overlay', 'ne-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Nebraska GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '## The Provisional Operator''s Permit (POP)

Once a Nebraska teen turns 16 and meets the permit and practice requirements, they upgrade to a Provisional Operator''s Permit (POP). The POP looks like a regular driver''s license, but it carries several restrictions that shape what driving looks like day-to-day until you turn 18 (or until you''ve held the POP for 12 months without violations and qualify for early restriction lifting in some cases).

### Nighttime driving

POP holders may not drive between **midnight and 6:00 a.m.** This window covers most late-night social activity. The only built-in exceptions are:

- Driving to or from work (with documentation in the vehicle).
- Driving to or from a school-sponsored activity (with documentation).
- Driving in an emergency.

"Documentation" usually means a note from your employer or school, signed and dated, that you carry in the car. A friend''s house, a movie that ran late, or hanging out at a 24-hour diner is *not* an exception — and "I was on my way home" is not a valid defense if it''s after midnight.

### Passenger limits

For the **first 6 months** with a POP, you may not transport more than one passenger under age 19 who is not a member of your immediate family. "Immediate family" includes siblings, step-siblings, and children of the driver. This is the rule that most often surprises new drivers — carpooling four friends to football practice is illegal, even if everyone has parental permission.

After 6 violation-free months, the passenger restriction lifts and you can drive a normal car-full of friends.

### Phones and devices

Nebraska prohibits drivers **under 18** from using any wireless communication device while driving — that includes *hands-free* setups. Bluetooth, speakerphone, voice-to-text, and dash-mounted phone use are all off limits. Adults can use hands-free, but minors cannot. **Texting is illegal for everyone, regardless of age.** Cell phone violations for POP holders can trigger license suspension and reset the clean-record clock.

### Seat belts and passengers

Nebraska is a primary seat-belt state for front-seat occupants and a secondary law for back-seat passengers age 18+, but for POP holders the safe assumption is: everyone buckled, every trip. Carrying an unrestrained passenger under 18 can result in a citation for the driver.

### Consequences of violations

Getting cited while on a POP doesn''t just mean a ticket. Each conviction adds points to your license. Accumulate too many points within a rolling period and the DMV will suspend your driving privileges. A suspension while you are still a POP holder usually restarts the 12-month clean-record period you need to qualify for an unrestricted Class O Operator''s License before age 18.

### Living with the rules

The practical takeaway: plan ahead. Know who is in your car, know what time it is, and put your phone in the glove box. A POP is a privilege the state can revoke at any time, and the GDL rules exist because crash data shows that nighttime driving, peer passengers, and phone use are the three biggest killers of teen drivers.', 30, 1
);
