INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nh_how-to-get-licensed-in-new-hampshire', 'module_nh_overlay', 'how-to-get-licensed-in-new-hampshire', 'How to Get Licensed in New Hampshire (No Permit Required)', '## New Hampshire Does Things Differently

If you''ve talked to friends in Massachusetts, Vermont, or Maine about getting their learner permit, you may be surprised to learn that **New Hampshire does not issue a learner permit to teens**. The Granite State is one of the only states in the country with this approach. Instead, your enrollment in a state-approved driver education program acts as your authorization to practice driving under supervision.

This lesson walks you through the full path from "I want to drive" to holding a Youth Operator License (YOL) in your wallet.

## Step 1: Enroll in Driver Education at Age 15 1/2

You can begin a state-approved driver education course as early as **age 15 years and 6 months**. The course must be approved by the New Hampshire Department of Education and meet these minimums:

- **30 hours of classroom instruction** (this can be in-person or, increasingly, online with a state-approved provider)
- **10 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW) instruction** with a certified instructor
- **6 hours of in-car observation** while another student drives

Once you enroll, your school will register you with the state and you will receive documentation showing you are an active driver education student. **This is what authorizes you to practice drive** with a supervising adult.

## Step 2: Practice with a Licensed Adult 25 or Older

While enrolled, you may drive any time of day with a licensed driver **25 years of age or older** in the front passenger seat. New Hampshire law requires you to complete at least **40 hours of supervised practice driving**, with **10 of those hours at night**, before applying for your license.

Your parent or guardian must sign a log verifying these practice hours. Keep this log carefully — you''ll submit it when you apply for your Youth Operator License.

## Step 3: Turn 16 and Complete Driver Education

You must be **at least 16 years old** AND have completed all driver education requirements before you can be licensed. There is no minimum waiting period after course completion (unlike states that require holding a permit for 6–12 months).

## Step 4: Pass the Knowledge and Road Tests

At your local DMV office, you will:

1. Present your driver education certificate of completion
2. Present your 40-hour parental log (signed by parent or guardian)
3. Show proof of identity, residency, and your Social Security number
4. Have a parent or guardian sign the financial responsibility form (they are legally liable for your driving until age 18)
5. Pass a **vision screening**
6. Pass a **written knowledge test** based on the NH Driver Manual
7. Pass an **on-road driving test** administered by a DMV examiner

## Step 5: Receive Your Youth Operator License

If you pass everything, you will be issued a **Youth Operator License**. This is your real license — you may drive alone — but it comes with the Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) restrictions covered in Lesson 2.

## What You Will Pay

Expect to budget for: driver education tuition (varies by school), the road test fee, and the license issuance fee. Your driving school will give you an itemized breakdown before you enroll.

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- **Driving alone before you are licensed.** Your enrollment authorizes supervised practice only.
- **Practicing with a supervisor under 25.** NH requires the supervising driver to be at least 25.
- **Forgetting the practice log.** Without 40 documented hours (10 at night), the DMV will turn you away on test day.
- **Assuming the course alone is enough.** You must also pass the DMV knowledge and road tests.', 45, 0
);
