INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_nh_overlay', 'nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living Under the NH Youth Operator License: GDL Restrictions', '## You Got Your License — Now What?

Receiving your Youth Operator License (YOL) is a big milestone, but in New Hampshire your license comes with **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** restrictions that apply until your 18th birthday. These rules exist because crash data shows that newly licensed teens are dramatically more likely to be involved in a serious crash during their first year of solo driving, especially at night and with friends in the car.

This lesson explains what you can and cannot do, how those rules affect your everyday life, and what happens if you break them.

## The Nighttime Curfew

**Between 1:00 a.m. and 4:00 a.m.**, drivers under 18 may not operate a motor vehicle unless they are:

- Accompanied by a parent or legal guardian, OR
- Driving to or from work, OR
- Driving to or from a school-sanctioned event, OR
- Responding to a bona fide emergency

For most teens, this means coming home from a late movie or a friend''s house before 1 a.m. — or arranging a different ride. The curfew lifts on your 18th birthday.

## The Passenger Restriction (First 6 Months)

For the **first 6 months** after you receive your YOL, you may not transport **more than one passenger under age 25** unless one of the following is true:

- A licensed driver age 25 or older is in the vehicle with you, OR
- The additional passengers are members of your immediate family (parents, siblings)

This is the rule most teens find inconvenient — you can''t pile four friends into the car to head to a concert during your first six months. The data is unambiguous: each additional teen passenger sharply increases crash risk for new drivers.

## Cell Phones and Electronic Devices

For drivers under 18, **all use of a handheld electronic communication device is prohibited while driving** — this includes calls, texting, social media, GPS adjustments, and music app fiddling. Even a Bluetooth-connected hands-free conversation is discouraged.

Additionally, New Hampshire''s general **handheld ban applies to drivers of all ages**: you must use hands-free technology to make calls. Holding your phone while driving is a primary offense, meaning an officer can pull you over for that alone.

If you need to use your phone for navigation, set the route **before you start driving** and mount the phone where you don''t have to hold it.

## Seat Belts

New Hampshire is the only state in the U.S. without a mandatory adult seat belt law — but **everyone under age 18 is required to wear one**, no matter where they are seated in the vehicle. This applies to you and every passenger under 18 in your car.

## What Happens If You Violate a GDL Rule?

Violations of the YOL restrictions can result in:

- Fines
- **License suspension** — typically 20 days for a first conviction, longer for subsequent ones
- Demerit points on your record (which can also raise insurance premiums significantly)
- Required reinstatement fees and possible re-testing

A suspension is reported to your insurance company, and that can mean **hundreds of dollars per year in higher premiums** for years to come.

## Planning Your Life Around the Restrictions

Smart teen drivers plan ahead:

- **Set a phone alarm for 12:30 a.m.** to start heading home if you''re out late.
- **Use a group text** to coordinate rides so you never end up over the passenger limit.
- **Mount your phone** before turning the key, and turn on Do Not Disturb While Driving.
- **Mark your 6-month milestone** on a calendar so you know when the passenger limit lifts.

When you turn 18, all GDL restrictions are automatically removed — no extra paperwork required.', 40, 1
);
