INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life_2', 'quiz_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Which of the following is permitted for a 17-year-old NH driver using their phone?', '["Texting at a red light","Holding the phone to make a quick hands-free call","Using a phone mounted to the dashboard with the route set before driving","Scrolling a music app while driving below 25 mph"]', 2, 'Drivers under 18 cannot use any handheld electronic communication device. Setting up navigation before you drive and using a hands-free mount is the safest legal approach.', 2
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life_3', 'quiz_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'True or false: New Hampshire requires all occupants under 18 to wear a seat belt.', '["False — NH has no seat belt laws","True — anyone under 18 must wear a seat belt in any seat","Only the driver under 18 must wear a seat belt","Only front-seat passengers under 18 must wear a seat belt"]', 1, 'While NH has no adult seat belt mandate, all occupants under 18 must be belted regardless of seating position.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life_4', 'quiz_nh_nh-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'What is a likely consequence of a first conviction for violating a YOL restriction?', '["A warning with no record","Permanent license revocation","A roughly 20-day license suspension, fines, and possible insurance impact","Immediate jail time"]', 2, 'A first conviction commonly results in a 20-day license suspension, fines, and a record that affects insurance premiums. Subsequent violations bring longer suspensions.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nh_nh-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_nh_overlay', 'nh-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'New Hampshire-Specific Rules and Driving Quirks', '## Driving in the Granite State

New Hampshire''s roads have a personality all their own — winding mountain passes through the White Mountains, dense moose habitat in the North Country, rotaries (traffic circles) that confuse out-of-state visitors, and winter conditions that can change from clear to whiteout in minutes. This lesson covers the NH-specific rules and quirks every new driver should know.

## "Live Free or Die" — and the Seat Belt Quirk

New Hampshire is famously the **only U.S. state without a mandatory adult seat belt law**. Drivers and passengers 18 and older are not legally required to wear seat belts. **However**: everyone under 18 must be belted, and crash statistics make clear that wearing a belt cuts your fatality risk roughly in half. The state''s libertarian motto doesn''t make physics optional.

## Rotaries (Traffic Circles)

NH still uses many **rotaries** — the older, larger cousin of the modern roundabout. Key rules:

- **Vehicles already in the rotary have the right of way.** You yield when entering.
- **Stay in your lane** as you circle and signal before exiting.
- **Do not stop in the rotary** unless required to avoid a collision — stopping creates rear-end crashes.

Famous rotaries include the Portsmouth Circle (I-95/US 1/US 4) and the Concord Heights traffic circle.

## Moose and Wildlife

New Hampshire has roughly 3,500–4,000 moose, concentrated in the **North Country and around the White Mountains**. A moose can weigh over 1,000 pounds, and its body sits at windshield height — collisions are frequently fatal.

- **Slow down at dusk and dawn**, especially May through October.
- **Watch for "Brake for Moose" signs** — they mark high-collision zones.
- **If a moose is in the road, brake hard and stay in your lane** — swerving often causes worse crashes (rollover, head-on collision).
- High-beam use on dark rural roads helps you spot eye-shine sooner.

## Winter Driving and the "Move Over" Law

Winter in NH is serious. Studded snow tires are legal from approximately mid-September through late April. Black ice is common on bridges and shaded curves even when air temperatures seem above freezing.

New Hampshire''s **Move Over Law ("Kevin''s Law")** requires drivers approaching any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or maintenance vehicle with flashing lights to:

- **Move over one lane** if it is safe to do so, OR
- **Slow to a reasonable and prudent speed** if moving over is not possible.

Violations carry fines and demerit points. The law exists because roadside workers have been killed by inattentive drivers.

## Open Container and DUI

New Hampshire has a **zero-tolerance law** for drivers under 21: a blood alcohol concentration of **0.02 or higher** results in DUI charges. For drivers 21+, the limit is 0.08. NH does not have an open-container law for passengers on most roads, but **the driver may never have an open container**.

A teen DUI conviction means license loss for **at least one year**, mandatory alcohol education, and significant fines. It also stays on your driving record and can affect college admissions and job applications.

## E-ZPass and Toll Roads

NH''s major toll roads (I-95, the Spaulding Turnpike, the Everett Turnpike, parts of I-93) use **E-ZPass** transponders. Many tolls are now all-electronic — there is no cash booth, and the system photographs your license plate to bill you by mail if you don''t have a transponder. Set up an account before a long highway trip to avoid the mailed-bill surcharge.

## Headlight and Wiper Rule

**If your windshield wipers are on, your headlights must be on.** This applies day and night and helps other drivers see you in rain, snow, or fog.

## School Buses

When a school bus stops with its **red lights flashing and stop arm extended**, all traffic in both directions must stop — except on a divided highway with a physical median, where only traffic behind the bus must stop. Penalties for passing a stopped school bus are severe and include heavy fines and license suspension.

## Quick Granite State Driving Checklist

- Belt yourself and every passenger — the law for kids, common sense for everyone.
- Treat every rotary as a yield-on-entry, stay-in-your-lane situation.
- Drop your speed in moose country at dusk and dawn.
- Move over (or slow down) for any flashing-light vehicle on the shoulder.
- Wipers on means headlights on.', 40, 2
);
