INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nj_how-to-get-a-nj-permit', 'module_nj_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-nj-permit', 'How to Get a Learner''s Permit in New Jersey', '## Two paths to a New Jersey learner''s permit

New Jersey offers teens two different routes to a learner''s permit, and the path you choose at age 16 versus 17 changes the requirements significantly. Understanding which permit applies to you is the first step.

### The Special Learner''s Permit (age 16)

If you are at least 16 years old but under 17, you can only obtain a Special Learner''s Permit through a New Jersey licensed driving school. You cannot walk into a Motor Vehicle Commission (MVC) agency on your own at this age. The driving school enrolls you, administers the knowledge test on-site, and submits your paperwork to the MVC.

To qualify for the Special Learner''s Permit, you must:

- Be at least 16 years old
- Enroll in a Behind-the-Wheel driver training course at a licensed New Jersey driving school
- Pass a vision screening
- Pass the written knowledge test (administered by the driving school)
- Have parental or guardian consent if under 18
- Complete 6 hours of behind-the-wheel instruction with a certified driving instructor

### The Examination Permit (age 17+)

If you are 17 or older, you may apply directly at an MVC licensing center for an Examination Permit. This path does not require enrollment in a driving school, though many teens still choose to take lessons. You will need to:

- Visit an MVC licensing center in person
- Present 6 Points of ID (a combination of primary and secondary identification documents totaling 6 points)
- Pay the permit fee
- Pass a vision screening
- Pass the written knowledge test
- Have parental or guardian consent if under 18

### Required 6 Points of ID

New Jersey uses a points-based identity verification system. You''ll need to combine primary documents (like a U.S. birth certificate or passport, worth 4 points) with secondary documents (like a school photo ID or Social Security card) and proof of address to reach 6 points total. Bring originals — photocopies are not accepted.

### After you receive the permit

Once issued, your permit must be validated before you can drive. For the Special Learner''s Permit, validation happens after you complete the behind-the-wheel training. For the Examination Permit, validation occurs at the MVC.

The holding period is 6 months minimum before you can take the road test. During this time, you must:

- Always have a supervising driver age 21 or older with at least 3 years of driving experience seated in the front passenger seat
- Display the red GDL decals on both the front and rear license plates of any vehicle you drive (more on this in Lesson 2)
- Follow the GDL curfew (no driving between 11:01 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.)
- Carry no more than one additional passenger (with limited family exceptions)
- Never use a cell phone or any electronic device while driving
- Always wear a seat belt, and ensure all passengers are belted

### Knowledge test topics

The written test draws from the New Jersey Driver Manual and covers road signs, right-of-way rules, safe-driving practices, sharing the road, alcohol and drug laws, and New Jersey-specific GDL rules. The MVC offers practice tests online, and most driving schools include test prep in their curriculum.

### Costs to expect

Budget for the permit fee, the driving school tuition if you take the Special Learner''s Permit route, the red decal pair (a small one-time fee), and eventually the road test and license fees. Ask your driving school for an itemized list before enrolling.', 30, 0
);
