INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_nj_how-to-get-a-nj-permit_3', 'quiz_nj_how-to-get-a-nj-permit', 'New Jersey verifies your identity at the MVC using which system?', '["A single government-issued photo ID","A notarized affidavit from a parent","The 6 Points of ID system","A Social Security card alone"]', 2, 'New Jersey requires applicants to provide documents totaling 6 points of identification, combining primary, secondary, and proof-of-address documents.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_nj_how-to-get-a-nj-permit_4', 'quiz_nj_how-to-get-a-nj-permit', 'Who must be in the vehicle with a New Jersey permit holder while practicing?', '["Any licensed driver age 18 or older","A supervising driver age 21 or older with at least 3 years of driving experience, seated in the front passenger seat","A parent or legal guardian only","A certified driving instructor only"]', 1, 'New Jersey requires the supervising adult to be at least 21, have at least 3 years of driving experience, and be seated in the front passenger seat.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nj_nj-gdl-daily-life-and-red-decal', 'module_nj_overlay', 'nj-gdl-daily-life-and-red-decal', 'Living with New Jersey''s GDL Restrictions and the Red Decal Rule', '## Kyleigh''s Law and the red decal requirement

New Jersey is the only state in the country that requires young drivers to display a special decal on their vehicle. The law, known as Kyleigh''s Law, took effect on May 1, 2010, and is named after Kyleigh D''Alessio, a 16-year-old passenger who died in a 2006 crash involving a teen driver.

### What the decal looks like and where it goes

The decal is a small, red, reflective sticker — about one inch square — that must be displayed on both the front and rear license plates of any vehicle a GDL permit holder or probationary license holder under 21 is driving. The decals are sold in pairs at MVC agencies for a small fee.

The decals attach to the upper left corner of each plate using a removable clip. They are designed to be easy to take on and off, since the same vehicle may also be driven by adults who are not subject to GDL rules. If a parent shares their car with a teen, the decals go on while the teen drives and come off when the parent drives alone.

### Why the decal matters

The purpose of the decal is to help law enforcement identify GDL drivers and enforce the curfew, passenger limit, and cell phone restrictions. Officers can spot a decal-bearing vehicle on the road and know that special rules apply.

Driving without the required decals is a violation that carries a fine. More importantly, if you are stopped for any reason without your decals displayed, the officer will know you are not in compliance with GDL rules.

### The GDL curfew

New Jersey prohibits GDL permit and probationary license holders from driving between 11:01 p.m. and 5:00 a.m. There are limited exceptions for documented employment or religious observance, but you must carry written proof from the employer or religious organization.

Planning your evenings matters. If you work a late shift or attend evening activities, you''ll need to be off the road before 11:01 p.m. or have your documentation ready in case you are stopped.

### The passenger limit

GDL drivers under 21 may carry only one additional passenger in the vehicle. This rule exists because crash data consistently shows that teen drivers are dramatically more likely to be involved in a serious crash when multiple peer passengers are in the car.

There are two important exceptions:

- A parent or legal guardian in the front passenger seat
- Dependents of the driver (if you have your own children, for example)

If any of these exceptions apply, the one-passenger limit does not. But friends, classmates, teammates, and siblings all count toward the limit.

### The cell phone ban

New Jersey bans all cell phone use for GDL drivers — both handheld and hands-free. This is stricter than the rule for fully licensed adult drivers, who may use hands-free devices. For GDL drivers, the phone goes in a bag, glove box, or out of reach. No calls, no texts, no music app changes, no GPS adjustments while moving.

The only exception is a true emergency requiring you to contact police, fire, or medical services.

### Seat belts for everyone

All occupants of a vehicle driven by a GDL holder must wear seat belts, regardless of seating position. As the driver, you are legally responsible for ensuring every passenger is buckled before you put the car in motion.

### Consequences for violations

GDL violations carry fines, and accumulating points or violations can extend your probationary period, delay your full unrestricted license, or trigger a suspension. Some violations also require completion of an MVC-approved driver-improvement program.

### Daily-life planning tips

Think ahead about rides home from late events. Coordinate with friends so the group doesn''t accidentally pile into one car. Keep your decals clean and visible. Park your phone before you start the engine. These small habits keep you legal and, more importantly, safe.', 30, 1
);
