INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nj_nj-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_nj_overlay', 'nj-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'New Jersey-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Driver Should Know', '## Driving rules that surprise out-of-staters

New Jersey has several driving laws and customs that often catch newcomers — and even some lifelong residents — off guard. Knowing them keeps you out of trouble and helps you drive confidently across the Garden State.

### No self-serve gasoline

New Jersey is the only state in the country that prohibits self-service gasoline at every retail station. The rule has been in place since 1949 under the Retail Gasoline Dispensing Safety Act. Drivers must stay in or near the vehicle while a station attendant pumps the fuel.

If you cross into Pennsylvania, New York, or Delaware, you''ll need to pump your own gas. New Jersey teens often experience this for the first time on a road trip and find it genuinely confusing — every other state expects you to know how to operate a pump.

### Probationary license at 17, full license at 18

New Jersey is also unique in that the standard minimum age for an unrestricted license is 18. At 17, after completing the 6-month permit period and passing the road test, you receive a probationary license — not a full license. The probationary period lasts a full year, during which all GDL restrictions (curfew, passenger limit, cell phone ban, red decals, seat belts for all) continue to apply.

Only after completing the probationary year without violations, and after turning 18, do you become eligible for the basic (unrestricted) driver''s license.

### No left turns from the left lane on many highways: the jughandle

Across much of New Jersey, especially on state and U.S. highways, you cannot make a left turn directly from the left lane. Instead, you must use a jughandle — a ramp on the right side of the road that loops around and brings you to a traffic signal at the intersection, where you cross perpendicular to the highway.

There are three common jughandle configurations: forward (most common, before the intersection), reverse (after the intersection), and U-turn jughandles. Pay close attention to overhead signs that say ''All Turns From Right Lane'' or ''Left Turn From Right Lane.'' Missing a jughandle often means a long detour to find a legal way to turn around.

### Keep right except to pass

New Jersey law requires drivers to use the right lane on multi-lane highways except when passing. The left lane is for passing only. Camping in the left lane can earn you a ticket and is a major source of road rage in the state.

### Move Over Law

When approaching a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or highway maintenance vehicle with flashing lights on the shoulder, you must either change lanes away from the vehicle (if safe to do so) or significantly reduce your speed. Violations carry steep fines.

### Right turn on red

Right turn on red is generally allowed in New Jersey after a complete stop, unless a sign specifically prohibits it. However, in many urban areas — especially parts of Jersey City, Newark, and Hoboken — signs commonly prohibit right on red, and the rule is enforced strictly.

### Studded tires and chains

Studded tires are permitted only between November 15 and April 1. Outside of that window, they are illegal in New Jersey.

### School bus rules

When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and stop arm extended, all traffic in both directions must stop — even on undivided roads. On divided highways with a physical barrier or median, only traffic traveling in the same direction as the bus must stop. Violations carry significant fines and points.

### Headlight rule: wipers on, lights on

New Jersey law requires headlights to be on any time your windshield wipers are in use — including in light rain, snow, sleet, or fog. Daytime running lights alone do not satisfy this requirement; your full headlights (which also activate your tail lights) must be on.

### Move Over for funeral processions

New Jersey drivers are expected to yield to funeral processions. Do not cut into the line of vehicles, even at a green light, once the procession has begun crossing an intersection.

### Tolls and EZ-Pass

The New Jersey Turnpike, Garden State Parkway, and Atlantic City Expressway are all toll roads. EZ-Pass is widely used and significantly faster than cash lanes. Some plazas have moved to all-electronic tolling with no cash option — driving through without a transponder triggers a mailed bill or a violation notice.', 30, 2
);
