INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nm_how-to-get-a-permit-in-new-mexico', 'module_nm_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-new-mexico', 'How to Get an Instructional Permit in New Mexico', '## Overview

In New Mexico, the first step in the Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) system is the **Instructional Permit**, issued by the New Mexico Motor Vehicle Division (MVD), a part of the Taxation and Revenue Department. You must hold the permit for at least **6 months** before you can move up to a Provisional License. This lesson walks through eligibility, required documents, the testing process, and what to expect at your MVD or MVD Express appointment.

## Who Can Apply

You may apply for an Instructional Permit when you turn **15 years old**. If you are under 18, New Mexico requires you to:

- Be enrolled in or have completed an approved driver education course (30 hours classroom plus 7 hours behind-the-wheel), and
- Have a parent or legal guardian sign the application in person at the MVD.

Applicants 18 and older are not required to take driver education, but completing a course is still strongly encouraged.

## Documents You Must Bring

New Mexico has an **identification points system**. You must present documents that together satisfy proofs of:

1. **Identification number** (Social Security card, W-2, or SSA letter).
2. **Identity and age** (certified birth certificate, U.S. passport, or permanent resident card).
3. **Two proofs of New Mexico residency** (utility bill, lease, school enrollment letter, parent’s residency documents combined with a parent affidavit).
4. **Driver education completion certificate** (if under 18 — issued by your school after the classroom phase, or by your approved third-party driver-ed provider).
5. **Parent/guardian consent**, signed in person at the MVD.

If you are choosing the federally compliant **REAL ID** version of the permit, the document list is more strict; otherwise you can request a Standard Driver Authorization Card-style credential.

## Tests at the MVD

At your appointment you will take:

- A **vision screening** (20/40 corrected in at least one eye).
- A **written knowledge test** based on the New Mexico Driver Manual. The test covers road signs, right-of-way, alcohol and drug laws, and GDL rules. You must score **at least 75%**.

The behind-the-wheel road test is **not** required at the permit stage — that comes later when you upgrade to a Provisional License.

## Fees

As of recent fee schedules, the Instructional Permit costs around **$10** for a one-year permit, though fees change — always confirm on the MVD website before your visit. Driver education tuition is separate and varies by provider.

## What the Permit Lets You Do

With an Instructional Permit you may drive only when accompanied by a **licensed driver age 21 or older** seated in the front passenger seat. You must hold this permit for a **minimum of 6 months**, remain crash-free and conviction-free, and log **50 hours of supervised driving practice** (with at least 10 of those hours at night) before you can apply for a Provisional License.

## Keeping the Permit Valid

Your parent or guardian must sign an **affidavit (MVD form, often referenced as MVD-10293)** verifying the 50 practice hours when you upgrade. Keep a written driving log — the MVD may ask to see it. Any traffic conviction during the permit phase can restart your 6-month waiting clock.

## Next Step

Once you have held your permit at least 6 months, completed driver education, logged your supervised hours, and turned 15½, you can schedule the road skills test to move up to a Provisional License.', 45, 0
);
