INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nm_new-mexico-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_nm_overlay', 'new-mexico-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Living With New Mexico GDL Restrictions', '## Why GDL Exists

New Mexico’s **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** system is designed to ease new drivers into full driving privileges as their skills mature. After holding the Instructional Permit for 6 months, completing driver education, and logging supervised hours, a teen who is at least **15 years and 6 months old** can take the road test and receive a **Provisional License**. This stage is where most teen-driving incidents happen, so the law adds important restrictions.

## The Nighttime Curfew

Provisional License holders may not drive between **midnight and 5:00 a.m.** unless one of these exceptions applies:

- Driving to or from work or a school-sponsored activity.
- Driving for a medical emergency.
- Driving when accompanied by a **licensed driver age 21 or older** in the front seat.

It is wise to carry written proof of your work schedule or school activity — a printed schedule, employer letter, or coach’s note — in case an officer stops you. “I was on my way home from a friend’s” is not an exception.

## The Passenger Limit

While holding a Provisional License you may carry **only one passenger under age 21** who is not an immediate family member. “Immediate family” means siblings, stepsiblings, and other members of your household. The rule exists because crash risk for teen drivers rises sharply with each additional teen passenger.

Violating the passenger rule is a primary offense — an officer can pull you over solely for that reason.

## Cell Phones and Devices

New Mexico bans **all use of a handheld or hands-free mobile communication device** by drivers under 18, except to call 911 in an emergency. That includes:

- Talking, even on a Bluetooth headset.
- Texting or messaging.
- Scrolling, streaming, or using navigation apps.

For drivers 18 and older, New Mexico bans texting statewide, and several cities (Santa Fe, Albuquerque, Las Cruces) ban all handheld use within city limits. Plan your route, queue your music, and put your phone in **Do Not Disturb While Driving** mode before you shift into gear.

## Seat Belts and Child Passengers

New Mexico is a **primary seat belt state** — everyone in the vehicle must be buckled, regardless of seating position. Children under 13 should ride in the back seat. Child safety seat rules apply through age 6 (or until the child reaches the seat’s height/weight limits).

## Alcohol and Drugs

New Mexico has a **zero-tolerance** law for drivers under 21: a BAC of **0.02% or higher** triggers license revocation. For drivers 21+, the legal limit is 0.08%. Cannabis is legal for adults 21+ in New Mexico, but **driving under the influence of cannabis is illegal at any age**, and a Provisional License holder caught with cannabis in the vehicle can lose driving privileges.

## Moving Up to an Unrestricted License

To move from Provisional to a full **Driver License**, you must:

- Be at least **16 years and 6 months old**, and
- Have held the Provisional License for **at least 12 months** with no crashes or moving-violation convictions.

A conviction or at-fault crash during the provisional year typically resets that 12-month clock. The takeaway: every clean month is progress — don’t throw it away with a texting ticket or a late-night run for snacks.', 40, 1
);
