INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nm_new-mexico-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_nm_overlay', 'new-mexico-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'New Mexico-Specific Rules and Quirks of the Road', '## Driving in the Land of Enchantment

New Mexico’s geography, weather, and wildlife make for some uniquely demanding driving conditions. Beyond the standard rules of the road, there are several New Mexico-specific laws and habits every new driver should know.

## Move Over Law

New Mexico’s **Move Over Law** requires drivers approaching a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or highway-maintenance vehicle with flashing lights to **change lanes away** from the stopped vehicle. If you can’t safely change lanes — because of traffic or because you’re on a two-lane road — you must **slow down significantly** below the posted speed limit. This applies on all multi-lane roads, not just interstates.

## Open Range and Livestock

Much of rural New Mexico is **open range**. That means livestock — cattle, horses, sheep — may legally roam onto highways, and in many counties **the driver is liable** for damage if they hit an animal. Watch for diamond-shaped “Open Range” signs, slow down at dusk and dawn, and never overdrive your headlights at night.

Elk and mule deer are also common, especially near the Sandias, Jemez, and Sangre de Cristo mountains. Two-vehicle elk collisions are often fatal because of the animal’s size and high center of mass — if a collision is unavoidable, **brake hard and aim for where the animal came from**, not where it’s going.

## Dust Storms and “Zero Visibility”

The stretch of I-10 between Las Cruces and Lordsburg, and parts of I-25 south of Socorro, are notorious for **sudden dust storms**. New Mexico DOT signs read **“Pull Aside — Stay Alive.”** Standard procedure during a dust storm:

1. Pull completely off the roadway.
2. Turn off headlights and tail lights (so drivers behind don’t follow your lights into the storm thinking you are still on the road).
3. Take your foot off the brake.
4. Set the parking brake.
5. Stay buckled and wait for the storm to pass.

## Mountain and High-Altitude Driving

Much of northern New Mexico sits above 6,000 feet. At altitude, engines lose power, braking distances on grades increase, and weather can change in minutes. On long descents — such as La Bajada Hill on I-25 or the descent from the Sandias on I-40 — **downshift** rather than riding the brakes. Watch for **runaway truck ramps** — they are a clue you’re on a serious grade.

Winter brings snow and black ice to the high country (Raton Pass, Cloudcroft, Taos). Carry chains or use winter tires when traveling north in winter.

## Tribal Lands and Pueblo Roads

New Mexico is home to **23 sovereign tribal nations**. When you drive onto Pueblo or Navajo Nation land, **tribal traffic laws and tribal police jurisdiction apply**. Speed limits and DUI thresholds may differ. Respect posted signs, do not photograph people or ceremonies without permission, and obey any roadway closures.

## Headlight and Wiper Law

New Mexico requires headlights to be on **anytime wipers are in continuous use** because of rain, snow, sleet, or fog — not just at night.

## Funeral Processions and School Buses

Funeral processions in New Mexico have the right-of-way at intersections once the lead vehicle has entered. For school buses with flashing red lights and an extended stop arm, traffic in **both directions** must stop unless separated by a physical median or divider.

## Border-Area Driving

Driving south of I-10 in counties bordering Mexico, you may encounter **U.S. Border Patrol checkpoints**. These are lawful interior checkpoints. Slow down, follow the agent’s instructions, and be prepared to answer brief questions about citizenship.

## Bottom Line

New Mexico’s wide-open roads can feel relaxing, but the combination of wildlife, weather, altitude, and tribal/border jurisdictional patchwork means a smart driver stays alert, plans ahead, and respects local conditions — not just the general rulebook.', 40, 2
);
