INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nv_how-to-get-a-nevada-instruction-permit', 'module_nv_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-nevada-instruction-permit', 'How to Get a Nevada Instruction Permit', '# How to Get a Nevada Instruction Permit

In Nevada, the instruction permit is the first official credential on the road to a driver''s license. It is issued by the Nevada Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) and is the legal document that lets a teen practice driving on public roads with a qualified supervising driver. Understanding exactly what the DMV expects up front will save you weeks of back-and-forth at the counter.

## Minimum age and prerequisites

You must be at least **15 years and 6 months old** to apply for an instruction permit in Nevada. You do *not* have to have completed driver education before getting the permit, but you cannot get the full driver''s license at 16 without completing driver ed, so most students enroll in a course at the same time they apply for the permit.

Before you go to the DMV, gather the following:

- **Proof of identity** — a certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or other DMV-accepted primary document.
- **Proof of Social Security number** — your Social Security card, a W-2, or a pay stub showing the full SSN.
- **Two documents proving Nevada residency** — utility bill, bank statement, lease, school enrollment letter, etc., showing your Nevada address. Parents'' documents can be used if accompanied by an affidavit of residency.
- **Parent or guardian signature** — anyone under 18 must have the *Financial Responsibility/Minor Affidavit* signed in person by a parent or legal guardian. The adult must appear with the teen unless the signature is notarized.
- **Vision screening** — administered free at the DMV counter.
- **Permit fee** — typically around $26 (subject to change; check NVDMV.gov).

## The knowledge test

The written test is 50 multiple-choice questions drawn from the **Nevada Driver''s Handbook**. You must score at least 80% to pass. Topics include traffic signs and signals, right-of-way rules, the state''s DUI and implied-consent laws, sharing the road, and the GDL restrictions you''ll be living under for the next two years. The test can be taken in English or Spanish, and the DMV offers it on a computer at the office. If you fail, you may retest the same day or the next business day, but additional attempts may require a waiting period.

## Make an appointment

Nevada DMV offices in Las Vegas, Henderson, Reno, and Carson City are extremely busy. **Make an online appointment** through the MyDMV portal — walk-ins can wait three to five hours, while appointment holders are usually seen within 15 minutes. Bring printed copies of your appointment confirmation and every required document.

## After you pass

Once you pass the knowledge test and vision screening, you''ll receive a paper interim permit on the spot; the plastic card arrives by mail in 10–14 days. From this moment, the **six-month clock** starts: you must hold the permit for at least six months *without any moving violations or at-fault crashes* before you can apply for a driver''s license. Any violation resets the six-month clock.

While holding the permit you must:

- Always have a **licensed driver at least 21 years old** seated next to you whenever the vehicle is in motion.
- Begin logging the **50 hours of supervised practice** (10 at night) on the DMV''s Beginning Driver Experience Log. A parent or guardian must certify each entry.
- Avoid any cell phone use — handheld use is illegal in Nevada for *every* driver, and a citation on your permit will reset your clock.

Keep the original log; the DMV will collect it when you return to take the road skills test. Lose it and you start over.', 35, 0
);
