INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_nv_nevada-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_nv_overlay', 'nevada-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Nevada GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Nevada GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Getting your license at 16 in Nevada doesn''t mean unrestricted freedom. The state''s **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** program puts real limits on what under-18 drivers can do for the first six months after licensure. These aren''t suggestions — violating them is a moving violation that can suspend your license, raise your family''s insurance, and reset your clean-record clock.

## The nighttime curfew

For the first **six months** after you receive your driver''s license, you may **not drive between 10:00 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.** This applies seven days a week. The only exemptions are travel to or from:

- A scheduled work shift (carry a note from your employer)
- An organized school activity or sporting event
- A medical or family emergency

"Going out with friends," "picking up food," and "giving a friend a ride home" are *not* exemptions. If you''re pulled over at 10:45 p.m. without documentation, expect a citation.

**Real-world example:** Friday-night high school football games in Reno often end after 9:30 p.m. If you stop for tacos with friends and roll out of the parking lot at 10:15, you are in violation — even if you''re 10 minutes from home. Plan to leave on time, or arrange a ride.

## The passenger restriction

Also for the **first six months**, you may not transport **any passenger under the age of 18** unless that passenger is an *immediate family member* (sibling, stepsibling, or another minor living in your household). It doesn''t matter if their parent gave permission or if you''re "just going around the block."

This is the rule most teens accidentally break. Common traps:

- Carpooling to school with a friend — *not allowed*.
- Driving a younger teammate home from practice — *not allowed* unless they live in your home.
- Taking your boyfriend or girlfriend to a movie — *not allowed* until they (or you) turn 18, or until the six months are up.

A licensed adult 21 or older in the front seat *does* allow you to carry under-18 passengers, because at that point you''re effectively in permit-style supervised driving.

## Cell phones — zero tolerance

Nevada law (NRS 484B.165) prohibits **all** drivers from holding a cell phone to talk, text, or use apps while driving. For under-18 drivers, the safest rule is **don''t touch the phone at all** — even hands-free. Mount it, set your navigation before you start, and use Do Not Disturb While Driving. A first phone-related citation is a $50 fine plus court fees; the second within seven years is $100; the third or any in a work zone is $250 and 4 demerit points, more than enough to threaten a young driver''s license.

## Seat belts and child passengers

Nevada is a primary-enforcement seat-belt state — an officer can stop you for an unbelted occupant alone. Drivers are responsible for every passenger under 18 being properly restrained. Children under 6 and under 60 pounds must be in an appropriate child-safety seat. If you''re driving younger siblings, double-check the buckle before you put the car in gear.

## What happens if you violate a GDL rule

A GDL violation is treated as a moving violation. Consequences escalate:

1. **First offense:** fine, possible mandatory traffic safety course.
2. **Second offense:** license suspension up to 90 days.
3. **Third offense:** suspension up to one year and re-application required.

More importantly, a violation **resets your clean-record requirements**, delaying when restrictions lift and damaging the insurance discount your family relies on. Following the rules for six months is a small price for a clean driving record that follows you for life.', 30, 1
);
