INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ny_getting-your-ny-learner-permit', 'module_ny_overlay', 'getting-your-ny-learner-permit', 'How to Get Your New York Learner Permit', '# How to Get Your New York Learner Permit

In New York, your driving journey starts at age 16 with a **Class DJ Junior Learner Permit** issued by the New York State Department of Motor Vehicles (NYSDMV). This lesson walks you through every step — including the special rules if you live in or want to drive in New York City.

## Step 1: Confirm You Meet the Age Requirement

You must be **at least 16 years old** to apply for a learner permit. If you are under 18, you will receive a *junior* permit (Class DJ for cars, MJ for motorcycles). Once you turn 18, you can upgrade to a Class D *senior* permit or license.

## Step 2: Gather Your Documents

The NYSDMV uses a **6-point ID verification system**. Common combinations for teens include:

- A valid U.S. passport (4 points)
- A certified U.S. birth certificate (2 points)
- Your Social Security card (2 points)
- A high school photo ID or report card (1 point)

You also need **proof of New York State residency** (a parent''s utility bill or bank statement showing your address) and your **Social Security Number**.

If you are under 18, a parent or guardian must sign the **MV-44 application** (Consent of Parent or Guardian).

## Step 3: Take and Pass the Written Knowledge Test

At the DMV office, you will take a **20-question multiple-choice written test** based on the *New York State Driver''s Manual (MV-21)*. You must answer at least **14 of 20** correctly, including at least 2 of the 4 road-sign questions. The test is offered in many languages and is available on tablets at most offices.

New York also allows the written test online for residents 18+, but **teens must take it in person at a DMV office**.

## Step 4: Pass a Vision Screening

You must meet **20/40 vision in at least one eye**, with or without corrective lenses. You can take the screening at the DMV or submit a recent eye exam from a licensed provider using form MV-619.

## Step 5: Pay the Fee

The combined permit and license fee runs roughly **$80 to $108** depending on your county and age. The fee covers your permit plus the eventual photo license document.

## Step 6: Get Your Permit Photo

If approved, you''ll have your photo taken on-site and walk out with a **temporary paper permit** the same day. Your plastic permit card arrives by mail within about two weeks.

## NYC-Specific Rules — Read This Carefully

If you live in New York City (Manhattan, the Bronx, Brooklyn, Queens, or Staten Island), you can still **apply for a junior permit**, but the permit is **NOT valid for driving anywhere within the five boroughs of NYC**. You can only practice driving outside the city — for example, in Westchester, Nassau, or upstate. This rule reflects how dense NYC traffic is considered too challenging for newly permitted teens.

Once you upgrade to a **senior (Class D) license at age 18**, the NYC restriction disappears.

## What Happens Next

After you receive your permit, you must:

1. Hold the permit for **at least 6 months** before taking the road test.
2. Log **50 hours of supervised driving practice** on form MV-262, including **15 hours after sunset** and **10 hours in moderate to heavy traffic**.
3. Complete a **5-hour Pre-Licensing Course (MV-278)** OR a high school/commercial driver education course.
4. Schedule and pass your road test.

With driver education completion, you can take the road test at **16½**. Without it, you must wait until **17**.', 35, 0
);
