INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ny_ny-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ny_overlay', 'ny-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'New York GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# New York GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

New York''s **Graduated Driver License (GDL)** system phases in driving privileges. Whether you hold a Junior Learner Permit or a Junior License (DJ), the restrictions below apply every day until you turn 18 or upgrade to a senior license. Knowing these rules cold protects your license — and your insurance rate.

## Permit Phase: Supervision Always

With a junior learner permit you may only drive when:

- A licensed driver **age 21 or older** is in the front passenger seat (or a 18+ driving instructor during a paid lesson).
- You are **outside New York City** entirely (the five-borough ban applies to permit holders).
- It is between **5:00 AM and 9:00 PM** unless your supervising driver is a parent or guardian.
- You are **not on any divided highway in a NYC park** (a long-standing NYC quirk).
- All occupants are wearing **seat belts** — the driver is responsible for passengers under 16.

You may not drive at all on the **Cross County, Hutchinson River, Saw Mill, Bronx River, or other NYC parkways** as a learner.

## Junior License Phase (Class DJ, Outside NYC)

After you pass the road test under age 18, you receive a **Junior Driver License (DJ)**. It allows more independence but keeps several limits:

### Nighttime Curfew
You generally cannot drive between **9:00 PM and 5:00 AM** unless:

- A parent or guardian is in the vehicle, OR
- You are driving **to/from work** with documentation, OR
- You are driving **to/from a school activity** with documentation, OR
- You are driving **to/from a medically necessary appointment**.

Note that Long Island (Nassau and Suffolk Counties) and Westchester County add their own curfew variations — generally requiring supervision after 9 PM in those areas, even though you are outside NYC.

### Passenger Limit
You may carry **no more than one passenger under age 21** in the vehicle, unless the additional passengers are **immediate family members** (siblings, step-siblings) or your spouse. This rule has zero flexibility — "just one friend home from practice" is a violation if another non-family teen is in the car.

### NYC Ban Continues
A junior license is still **not valid in the five boroughs of NYC**. If you want to drive into Manhattan to visit family, you cannot do so legally with a Class DJ.

### Seat Belt Rule
The driver is responsible for ensuring **all passengers under 16** are properly buckled, and **all front-seat occupants** regardless of age. As of 2020, New York extended the seat belt requirement to **all back-seat passengers**, including adults.

## Cell Phones and Distracted Driving

New York is a **hands-free state**. **All drivers** — not just teens — are prohibited from:

- Holding a phone to talk
- Texting, emailing, or browsing
- Taking photos or video while driving

For **junior license holders**, a first conviction for handheld phone use OR texting results in a **mandatory 120-day suspension**. A second conviction within six months brings a **1-year revocation**. There is no warning phase — the law is strictly enforced.

## Penalty for Any GDL Violation

Any conviction for a moving violation while holding a junior permit or license triggers:

- **60-day suspension** for the first conviction
- **6-month revocation** for a second conviction within 6 months of restoration

After restoration, you may be required to repeat the Pre-Licensing Course and retake the road test.

## Upgrading to a Senior License

When you turn **18**, your Class DJ automatically upgrades to a **Class D senior license** with no GDL restrictions — assuming you have not been suspended. If you completed driver education, the upgrade can happen at **17**.', 30, 1
);
