INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ny_ny-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ny_overlay', 'ny-rules-and-quirks', 'New York-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# New York-Specific Rules and Quirks

New York''s driving environment is uniquely shaped by **dense urban traffic in NYC**, sprawling suburban parkways on Long Island, and rural roads upstate. These rules are easy to miss in a generic driver''s course — and easy to get ticketed for.

## The MV-262 Pre-Licensing Certification

Before you can take the road test, you must complete **one** of the following:

1. A **5-hour Pre-Licensing Course (MV-278)** — offered by commercial driving schools and some county DMVs. It is a single classroom session covering perception, attitude, and the consequences of driving decisions.
2. A **high school driver education course** approved by the NY Department of Education.
3. A **commercial driver education program** that issues a Certificate of Completion (MV-285).

You must present the completion certificate at the road test site. **Without it, the examiner will not test you.**

## The MV-262 Practice Log

New York requires that you complete **50 hours of supervised driving practice** before the road test, documented on the **MV-262 Certification of Supervised Driving form**. The 50 hours must include:

- **At least 15 hours after sunset**
- **At least 10 hours in moderate to heavy traffic**

A parent or guardian signs the form under penalty of perjury. The examiner will check that the form is signed and dated.

## Parkways Are Not Always Open to All

Many NYC and Long Island **parkways** (Henry Hudson, Saw Mill River, Bronx River, Hutchinson River, Northern State, Southern State, Meadowbrook, Wantagh) are **closed to commercial vehicles** — including pickup trucks with commercial plates and box trucks. The low stone bridges over these parkways were designed for cars only. Even non-commercial pickup trucks have caused famous bridge strikes on the Southern State.

If you are driving a vehicle with a **commercial registration**, you cannot use these roads, even on a personal errand.

## Right Turn on Red — NOT in NYC

Upstate and on Long Island, **right turn on red is allowed after a complete stop** unless a sign prohibits it. In **New York City, right turn on red is PROHIBITED everywhere unless a sign specifically allows it**. This is the opposite of the rest of the state. Many out-of-town teens get tickets for habitually rolling right at a red light in Manhattan or Queens.

## Move Over Law

When approaching any **stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or maintenance vehicle** with flashing lights on a road with two or more lanes in your direction, you must **move over one lane**. If you can''t, slow down significantly. Violations carry points and fines.

## DWI and Zero Tolerance for Teens

New York''s Zero Tolerance Law makes it illegal for any driver **under 21** to operate a vehicle with a Blood Alcohol Content of **0.02% or higher**. A first violation:

- **6-month license suspension**
- **$125 civil penalty + $100 suspension termination fee**
- Required to attend a DMV hearing

For drivers 21+, the standard DWI threshold is 0.08%.

## School Bus Stops

You must stop for a stopped school bus with flashing red lights **in all directions**, even on a divided highway. This is stricter than many other states. Violation carries **5 points** on your license and a fine starting at **$250** — and increases sharply for repeat offenses. New York equips many buses with **stop-arm cameras** that automatically generate tickets.

## Snow and Ice Removal

Before driving in winter, you must **clear all snow and ice from your vehicle''s roof, hood, trunk, and lights**. "Christine''s Law" (effective 2024) makes it a violation to drive with accumulated snow/ice that can fly off and hit other vehicles. Fines range from **$150 to $1,200** depending on whether the falling debris causes injury.

## Speed Cameras and Red-Light Cameras

NYC operates **24/7 speed cameras** in school zones (which is now city-wide) and **red-light cameras** at hundreds of intersections. Tickets are mailed to the registered owner, do not carry points, but cost $50 each. As a teen who borrows a parent''s car, remember: the **parent gets the ticket**, but the family may bill you back.', 30, 2
);
