INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_oh_how-to-get-an-ohio-tipic', 'module_oh_overlay', 'how-to-get-an-ohio-tipic', 'How to Get Your Ohio Temporary Instruction Permit (TIPIC)', '## The Ohio teen path starts with a TIPIC

In Ohio, the learner permit you carry in your wallet is officially called the **Temporary Instruction Permit Identification Card**, almost always shortened to **TIPIC**. You can apply as early as **age 15 years, 6 months**, and you must hold it for **at least 6 months** before you are eligible to test for a probationary driver license. The TIPIC is issued by the **Ohio Bureau of Motor Vehicles (BMV)** and the knowledge test is given at a **Driver Exam Station**, which is a separate location from the deputy registrar where you eventually get your plastic license card.

## Step 1 — Enroll in driver education first (if you''re under 18)

Anyone under 18 must complete a state-approved driver education program **before** getting a probationary license. The program consists of:

- **24 hours of classroom instruction** (in-person or through an Ohio Department of Public Safety approved online course), and
- **8 hours of behind-the-wheel (BTW) instruction** with a licensed driving instructor.

You are allowed to start the classroom portion before you turn 15 1/2, but you cannot start BTW lessons until you have your TIPIC in hand.

## Step 2 — Gather your documents

Bring originals (no photocopies) to the Driver Exam Station:

1. **Proof of full legal name and date of birth** — certified U.S. birth certificate or valid passport.
2. **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN.
3. **Proof of Ohio residency** — two documents such as a utility bill, school record, or bank statement addressed to your parent/guardian.
4. **Proof of legal presence** — generally satisfied by the birth certificate or passport above.
5. A **parent or legal guardian** must accompany you and sign the application, because you are a minor.

If you want a **compliant** card (the one with a gold star, usable for boarding domestic flights), bring the documents listed for REAL ID; otherwise you''ll receive a standard card marked "Not For Federal Identification."

## Step 3 — Pass the tests

At the Driver Exam Station you''ll take:

- A **vision screening**.
- A **knowledge test** covering road signs and Ohio traffic law (40 questions; you must score 75% on each section). The questions come straight from the **Ohio Digest of Motor Vehicle Laws**, which is free to download from the BMV website.

Pay the TIPIC fee at the exam station. You''ll leave with a paper temporary permit; the plastic TIPIC card arrives by mail within about 10 business days.

## Step 4 — Drive with the right supervision

While holding the TIPIC, you may only drive when accompanied by:

- A **licensed parent, guardian, or driving instructor** seated in the front passenger seat, **or**
- Any **licensed driver 21 or older** if your parent/guardian has authorized it.

You cannot drive between **midnight and 6 a.m.** on a TIPIC unless accompanied by a parent or guardian. The whole car must be belted, and Ohio''s hands-free law applies to you the moment the engine starts.

## Step 5 — Log your 50 hours

Before the road test, your parent or guardian must certify that you completed **50 hours of supervised driving**, including **at least 10 hours at night**. Use the log form provided by your driving school or the BMV. Keep it accurate — examiners can and do ask to see it.

## What''s next

Once you''ve held the TIPIC for six months, completed driver ed, and logged your hours, you can schedule the **maneuverability and road skills test** with a state-contracted third-party examiner. Pass that, return to a deputy registrar with your test results, and you''ll be issued an Ohio probationary license valid until your 21st birthday.', 45, 0
);
