INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_oh_ohio-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_oh_overlay', 'ohio-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Living With Ohio''s GDL Restrictions', '## You got the probationary license — now what?

When an Ohio teen passes the road test before their 18th birthday, the BMV issues a **probationary driver license**. It looks similar to an adult license but carries **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** restrictions that change as you age and gain experience. Understanding them prevents a quick trip to driving court.

## Curfew, in two phases

Ohio splits the teen curfew into two tiers:

- **First 12 months of licensure, or until you turn 17 (whichever comes first):** no driving between **midnight and 6 a.m.** without a parent or guardian in the car.
- **From age 17 to 18 (or after the first 12 months):** the window narrows to **1 a.m. to 5 a.m.**

Exceptions exist for **work, school-sponsored activities, religious events, and emergencies**, but you must carry documentation — for instance, a signed note from your employer with the address and your shift hours. "My friend''s house" is not an exception, and "I lost track of time" is not an emergency.

## Passenger limits

Until the **first anniversary** of your probationary license **or until you turn 17**, you may carry **only one non-family passenger** unless a parent or guardian is along for the ride. "Family" means people related to you by blood, marriage, or adoption who live in your household. This is one of the most-cited GDL violations in Ohio — that car full of teammates after practice is not allowed in year one.

## Seat belts apply to everyone in your car

Under the GDL rules, **all occupants** of a vehicle driven by a probationary license holder must wear seat belts, regardless of where they sit. For adult drivers, Ohio''s adult belt law is technically secondary enforcement only for back-seat occupants 15 and older, but for teens it is **primary** — an officer can pull you over solely because a passenger is unbelted.

## Hands-free, period

Ohio enacted a hands-free law in 2023 that bans **all drivers** from holding or manipulating a phone, tablet, or other electronic device. For drivers under 18, the rule is stricter: **no use of any wireless communication device while driving, even hands-free.** That means no Bluetooth calls, no voice-to-text, no scrolling at a red light. Practically, set your destination, queue your music, and silence notifications before you put the car in drive.

## What happens if you get a ticket

The GDL has a "two strikes" structure. If you are convicted of two **moving violations** while holding the probationary license, the BMV requires you to be accompanied by a parent or guardian whenever you drive **for the next six months**, or until you turn 17 — whichever is longer. A third conviction triggers a **license suspension**. A single conviction for a serious offense (OVI, drag racing, fleeing) can trigger immediate suspension and re-testing.

## When do the restrictions go away?

Most GDL restrictions lift automatically at **age 18**. The hands-free law, of course, stays with you for life. The seat belt habit should too.

## Real-world planning tips

- If your shift ends at 11:45 p.m. and your drive home is 20 minutes, you''re already in a curfew gray zone. Keep your work schedule in the car.
- Saturday morning at 5:45 a.m. for fishing with one friend? Legal at 17, illegal at 16-and-fresh-licensed.
- Carpooling siblings counts as family. Carpooling cousins who don''t live with you does not.', 35, 1
);
