INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_oh_ohio-gdl-restrictions-daily-life_3', 'quiz_oh_ohio-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Under Ohio law, how can a driver under 18 legally use a cell phone while driving?', '["Hands-free only","For navigation only","Not at all — any use of a wireless communication device is prohibited","Only when the car is stopped at a light"]', 2, 'Ohio prohibits any use of a wireless communication device by drivers under 18, including hands-free use and use at stoplights.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_oh_ohio-gdl-restrictions-daily-life_4', 'quiz_oh_ohio-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'What happens after two moving-violation convictions during the Ohio probationary period?', '["Nothing — you get a warning","The license is suspended permanently","The teen must be accompanied by a parent or guardian for the next 6 months or until age 17, whichever is longer","The teen must retake the classroom course"]', 2, 'Two moving violations trigger a parent/guardian accompaniment requirement; a third conviction triggers suspension.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_oh_ohio-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_oh_overlay', 'ohio-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Ohio Rules and Quirks Every New Driver Should Know', '## Ohio has a few rules you won''t find spelled out the same way elsewhere

Most states share a common base of traffic law, but Ohio has its own personality. These are the rules and conventions that trip up new — and even experienced — drivers most often.

## The "Move Over" law applies to a lot more than police cars

Ohio''s Move Over law (R.C. 4511.213) requires you, when approaching **any stationary vehicle with flashing lights** on a road with two or more lanes in your direction, to either **change lanes away from the vehicle** if it is safe to do so, or **slow down significantly** if changing lanes is not safe. The list of covered vehicles is broad: law enforcement, fire, EMS, tow trucks, road maintenance, utility vehicles, waste collection, and even **regular motorists who are stopped on the shoulder with hazard lights on**. Violations are primary-enforcement and carry escalating fines, especially if the failure results in injury.

## Right turn on red — yes, but read the sign

Like most states, Ohio allows a right turn on red after a complete stop unless a sign prohibits it. Less well known: **left turn on red is also legal in Ohio from a one-way street onto another one-way street** after a complete stop, again unless signed otherwise. Many intersections in Cincinnati, Columbus, and Cleveland use this rule daily.

## Funeral processions have special standing

Ohio gives **funeral processions** the right-of-way at intersections once the lead vehicle has lawfully entered, even against a red light, provided each car in the procession has its headlights on and a flag or marker. Cutting into a procession is a specific traffic offense. New drivers should slow, hold their position, and let the entire line pass.

## "Failure to control" is the classic Ohio catch-all

If you slide off a snowy road, rear-end someone in traffic, or hit a curb hard, the officer''s most common citation in Ohio is **failure to control** (R.C. 4511.202). It''s a two-point offense and is often the first ticket new drivers see. Drive for the conditions, not the speed limit — black ice on a 65-mph rural highway is famous in Ohio.

## School buses, two ways

When a school bus stops with **flashing red lights and the stop arm extended**:

- On a **two-lane road**, all traffic in both directions must stop and remain stopped until the bus moves or extinguishes its lights.
- On a road with **four or more lanes**, only traffic moving in the **same direction** as the bus must stop; oncoming traffic may proceed with caution.

Under Ohio law you must remain stopped at least **10 feet** from the bus. Violations are primary offenses and can include a license suspension.

## Snow emergencies and the county-by-county color code

Ohio counties issue **snow emergency levels** declared by the county sheriff:

- **Level 1:** roads are hazardous; drive cautiously.
- **Level 2:** only those who feel it is necessary to drive should be on the roads; contact your employer.
- **Level 3:** all roadways are closed to non-emergency personnel. Driving is a misdemeanor and you may be cited.

Check your county sheriff''s site or local news before driving during winter storms.

## Headlights, wipers, and the "if one, then the other" rule

Ohio requires headlights from **sunset to sunrise**, in any **adverse weather** that limits visibility to less than 1,000 feet, and **whenever your windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to weather. Driving in rain with wipers on and headlights off is a frequent citation.

## License plates — front and rear

As of July 1, 2020, Ohio **eliminated the front plate requirement**. Only a **rear plate** is required. You''ll still see many older Ohio cars with front plates and many Ohioans who simply prefer them, but it''s optional.

## Bicycles get a full lane

Ohio law treats bicycles as vehicles. When passing a cyclist, you must give **at least 3 feet of clearance**, and you may legally cross a double-yellow line to do so when oncoming traffic is clear. Squeezing past a cyclist in the same lane is illegal.

## Pump-your-own gas (and the no-cash quirk)

Ohio is a self-serve gas state — there is no "full service required" oddity like New Jersey or Oregon. However, many Ohio stations require **prepay after dark**, and some smaller-town stations still mark pumps **cash only** with a higher credit price. Look before you lift the nozzle.', 40, 2
);
