INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ok_how-to-get-an-oklahoma-learner-permit', 'module_ok_overlay', 'how-to-get-an-oklahoma-learner-permit', 'How to Get a Learner Permit in Oklahoma', '# How to Get a Learner Permit in Oklahoma

Getting your first driving credential in Oklahoma is handled by **Service Oklahoma** (the agency that took over most driver licensing functions from the Department of Public Safety). This lesson walks you through the exact steps, paperwork, and fees so you arrive at your appointment prepared.

## Step 1: Know Your Minimum Age

Oklahoma is one of a shrinking number of states that lets you start earlier *if* you complete driver education:

- **15 years and 6 months** — if you complete an approved driver education course (30 hours of classroom plus 6 hours of behind-the-wheel instruction).
- **16 years old** — if you do not complete driver ed.

Because this course you are taking counts toward the driver-ed requirement, plan to finish all classroom and behind-the-wheel hours before your 15.5 birthday if you want to test on the earliest possible day.

## Step 2: Gather Your Documents

Service Oklahoma uses the federal REAL ID document standard, so you will need originals (no photocopies) of:

1. **Proof of identity** — certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or permanent resident card.
2. **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub with full SSN.
3. **Two proofs of Oklahoma residency** — utility bill, bank statement, school records, or a parent''s documents combined with a notarized affidavit if you live with them.
4. **Parent or guardian signature** — anyone under 18 must have a parent or legal guardian present to sign the application in front of the examiner. If only one parent has custody, bring the court order.
5. **School enrollment/attendance verification** — Oklahoma''s "Stay in School" law requires applicants under 18 to show they are enrolled, have graduated, or have a GED. Your school counselor can issue the form.
6. **Driver education completion certificate** — issued by your driving school once classroom and BTW hours are finished.

## Step 3: Schedule Your Knowledge Test

The written knowledge test covers Oklahoma road signs, traffic laws, and safe-driving practices from the Oklahoma Driver''s Manual. You can:

- **Schedule online** through the Service Oklahoma website, or
- **Walk in** to a participating licensed operator (tag agency) that offers testing.

The test is 50 multiple-choice questions; you must answer at least 40 correctly (80%) to pass. If you fail, you must wait at least one day before retesting and pay the test fee again.

## Step 4: Pass the Vision Screening

A quick vision check is performed at the testing location. If you wear glasses or contacts, bring them — a "corrective lenses" restriction will be added to your permit and you must always drive with them.

## Step 5: Pay the Fees

Fees change periodically, but budget roughly:

- Learner permit fee (around $38)
- Knowledge test fee (around $4)
- REAL ID surcharge if you choose the federally compliant version

Bring a debit card, credit card, or cash — most tag agencies do not take personal checks.

## Step 6: Receive Your Permit and Start the Clock

Once you pass, you will receive a temporary paper permit and your printed card will arrive by mail within 10 business days. The day you receive the permit starts a **mandatory 6-month holding period** before you can advance to an intermediate license.

## What the Permit Lets You Do

With a learner permit you may drive **only when accompanied by a licensed driver 21 or older** seated beside you in the front passenger seat. You may not drive solo, and you may not use any handheld electronic device while driving — period.

## Common Mistakes That Delay Teens

- Forgetting the school enrollment form.
- Bringing photocopies of birth certificates instead of certified originals.
- Arriving without both parents'' signatures when custody is shared.
- Failing the knowledge test because you studied a generic national prep app instead of the Oklahoma manual.

With the right paperwork and a little preparation, most teens leave Service Oklahoma the same day with their permit in hand.', 25, 0
);
