INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ok_oklahoma-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ok_overlay', 'oklahoma-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Oklahoma-Specific Rules and Quirks of the Road', '# Oklahoma-Specific Rules and Quirks of the Road

Every state has its own legal twists, road conditions, and cultural driving habits. Oklahoma — with its mix of rural two-lanes, turnpikes, oil-field traffic, and tornado-prone weather — has more than its share. Learning these now will save you fines, fender-benders, and at least a few panicked moments.

## Turnpikes and PIKEPASS

Oklahoma operates one of the largest toll-road systems in the country. The **Turner, Will Rogers, H.E. Bailey, Indian Nation, Muskogee, Cherokee, Cimarron, Creek, and Kilpatrick turnpikes** are all operated by the Oklahoma Turnpike Authority. Key points:

- Most toll plazas have transitioned to **cashless tolling** under the "PlatePay" / PIKEPASS system. If you do not have a PIKEPASS transponder, cameras photograph your plate and mail an invoice to the registered owner — usually your parents.
- Always check that your vehicle has a working PIKEPASS or that your parents are aware you will be using a turnpike, or you may rack up unexpected bills.
- The minimum speed on most turnpikes is 40 mph; the maximum is typically **75 mph**, though some rural stretches are posted at 80 mph.

## Tornado and Severe Weather Driving

Oklahoma sits in the heart of Tornado Alley. Spring storms (March-June) can produce hail the size of baseballs, microbursts, and tornadoes with little warning.

- **Never park under an overpass during a tornado.** Contrary to old folklore, overpasses funnel wind and create deadly debris zones. Get off the road, find a low ditch away from your vehicle, and lie flat with your hands over your head.
- During heavy rain or hail, pull off onto a wide shoulder, turn on hazard lights, and wait it out. Hail can shatter windshields in seconds.
- Be aware of **flash flooding** on rural roads. "Turn Around, Don''t Drown" is the law — Oklahoma''s swift-water rescue statute can bill drivers who ignore barricades.

## Move Over Law

Oklahoma''s "Move Over" law requires drivers approaching any **stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, utility vehicle, or roadside maintenance vehicle** with flashing lights to:

1. Move over one lane away from the stopped vehicle if it is safe to do so, **or**
2. Slow to at least 10 mph below the posted speed limit if moving over is not safe.

Violations carry steep fines and points.

## Open Range and Wildlife

Large swaths of western and southern Oklahoma are **open range**, meaning livestock may legally be on or near the roadway. If you hit a cow on an open-range road, *you* may be liable for the animal. Always reduce speed at dusk and dawn, when deer are most active across the entire state.

## Implied Consent and Zero-Tolerance Alcohol

By accepting an Oklahoma driver license, you give **implied consent** to chemical testing if law enforcement has reason to suspect impaired driving. For drivers under 21, Oklahoma has a **zero-tolerance** law: any detectable alcohol (BAC of 0.02% or higher) results in license revocation. Refusing the test triggers an automatic 6-month revocation for a first offense, regardless of guilt.

## School Bus Stop Laws

When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and stop arm extended:

- On a **two-lane road**, all traffic in both directions must stop.
- On a **divided highway with a physical median or barrier**, only traffic in the same direction as the bus must stop.
- A painted center turn lane is **not** a divider — both directions must still stop.

Fines for illegally passing a school bus in Oklahoma can exceed $500, plus court costs and points.

## Funeral Processions Have the Right of Way

Oklahoma is one of the states that explicitly grants funeral processions the right of way at intersections, even against red lights, as long as the lead vehicle entered legally. Yield, do not cut in, and do not pass on a two-lane road.

## Quirks Worth Remembering

- **Headlights when wipers are on** is recommended but not strictly required statewide; do it anyway.
- **No texting, period** — Oklahoma''s texting-while-driving ban applies to every driver, every age.
- **Helmet law** for motorcyclists applies only to riders under 18, but eye protection is required for all.
- Some small Oklahoma towns are notorious **speed traps**; watch for speed-limit drops at city limits, especially on US highways.

Driving in Oklahoma rewards drivers who pay attention to the sky, the shoulder, and the speed-limit sign. Build those habits during your restricted period, and you will be ready for everything from a turnpike road trip to a sudden hailstorm by the time you earn an unrestricted license.', 25, 2
);
