INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_or_how-to-get-an-oregon-instruction-permit', 'module_or_overlay', 'how-to-get-an-oregon-instruction-permit', 'How to Get an Oregon Instruction Permit', '# How to Get an Oregon Instruction Permit

In Oregon, the **Instruction Permit** is your first official step toward becoming a licensed driver. It is issued by the **Oregon Driver and Motor Vehicle Services (DMV)**, which is part of the Oregon Department of Transportation (ODOT). This lesson walks through who can apply, what to bring, what tests to pass, and what to expect on the day of your visit.

## Who can apply

You must be **at least 15 years old** to apply for an Oregon Instruction Permit. There is no upper age limit, but the **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** rules and the driver education incentives in this lesson only apply to teens under 18.

If you are **under 18**, a parent or legal guardian must sign your application in person at the DMV office. The signing adult is accepting financial responsibility for any damages you might cause while driving — Oregon law (ORS 807.065) requires this signature.

## What to bring to the DMV

Oregon DMV requires proof of **identity, date of birth, lawful presence in the U.S., Social Security number, and Oregon residence address**. You generally need to bring:

- A certified U.S. birth certificate or valid U.S. passport (originals, not copies)
- Your Social Security card or an official document showing your full SSN
- Two proofs of Oregon residence address (e.g., a utility bill, school records, a parent’s lease that lists you)
- A parent or guardian (if you are under 18) with their own ID
- The application fee (check the current DMV fee schedule before you go)

If you want a **Real ID-compliant** permit, bring the same documents — Real ID has been the default identity standard for several years now.

## The tests

To earn your Instruction Permit you must pass:

1. **A vision screening** at the counter (20/40 in at least one eye, with correction allowed).
2. **The knowledge (written) test**, covering Oregon traffic laws, road signs, safe driving practices, and the GDL rules. The test is multiple choice and is based on the current **Oregon Driver Manual**, available free as a PDF on the ODOT/DMV website.

You do **not** take a road (behind-the-wheel) test for the permit itself — that comes later when you upgrade to your provisional license.

## What the permit lets you do

With an Oregon Instruction Permit you may drive **only when supervised** by a licensed driver who is **at least 21 years old** seated next to you in the front passenger seat. Driving alone on a permit is illegal in Oregon and can reset the clock on your eligibility for a provisional license.

## Driver education: the fast track

Oregon strongly incentivizes ODOT-approved driver education. If you complete an approved course (typically **30 hours of classroom instruction and 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training**), you only need to log **50 hours of supervised practice** — at least 10 of those hours at night — before you can apply for your provisional license at age 16.

If you skip an approved course, you must log **100 hours of supervised practice** (50 of which must be after you turn 16, with at least 10 at night) before you can apply for your provisional license. Most Oregon teens take the course because it cuts the practice requirement in half and may qualify you for an insurance discount.

## How long the permit lasts

The Oregon Instruction Permit is valid for **two years**. You must hold it for at least **6 months** before applying for your provisional license, and you must be **at least 16 years old** at the time of that application.

Keep a written or app-based **practice driving log** the entire time you hold the permit — Oregon DMV may ask you (and your parent) to certify it when you apply for your provisional license.', 45, 0
);
