INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_or_oregon-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_or_overlay', 'oregon-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Oregon GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Oregon GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Getting your **provisional license** in Oregon at age 16 is not the end of the road — it is the start of a structured **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** period that lasts until you turn 18. These rules exist because crash data consistently shows that newly licensed teens are highest risk when they drive late at night, with peers in the car, or while distracted. This lesson translates Oregon’s GDL rules into the situations you will actually face.

## The nighttime curfew

**For the first 6 months** after you get your Oregon provisional license, you may not drive between **midnight and 5:00 a.m.** unless one of these applies:

- You are driving **to or from work** (and you can show proof if asked).
- You are driving **for a school activity** (sports, performance, club event).
- A **licensed driver age 25 or older** is in the front passenger seat.
- You are driving **as part of your job** (e.g., a delivery shift).
- There is a **medical or other emergency**.

Real-life translation: a midnight movie that lets out at 1:00 a.m.? You need a 25+ licensed driver next to you, or someone else has to drive home. A 1:00 a.m. fast-food run? Not allowed.

## The passenger limits

**First 6 months:** You may not transport **any passenger under age 20** unless they are a **member of your immediate family** (a parent, sibling, stepsibling, etc.).

**Second 6 months (months 7–12):** You may transport **up to three passengers under age 20** who are not immediate family. After that — once you have held the provisional license for a full year, or you turn 18 — the passenger limit goes away.

Real-life translation: in the first 6 months you cannot drive your friends to a football game, even if they all fit safely in the car. Adult passengers (20+) are always fine.

## The cell phone rule (this one is strict)

Oregon law forbids **any driver under 18** from using a **mobile communication device** while driving — for **any purpose**, **even hands-free**. That means no calls (even on Bluetooth), no texting, no GPS app interaction, no music app skipping. Set everything before you put the car in drive, or pull over.

Adult drivers are also banned from **holding** a phone, but they may use hands-free voice features. Teens get the stricter rule.

A first offense can be a **Class B traffic violation** with a base fine in the hundreds of dollars, and it can extend your GDL restriction period.

## Seat belts — everyone, every seat

Oregon is a **primary enforcement** state: an officer can pull you over solely for a seat belt violation. Every person in the vehicle must be properly restrained. Children under age 2 must be in a rear-facing seat; children under 40 lbs must be in a harness car seat; children under 4''9" tall or under age 8 must be in a booster.

As the driver, **you** are responsible for making sure every passenger under 16 is buckled.

## Consequences for breaking GDL rules

If you are cited for any traffic offense (GDL violation, speeding, etc.) during your provisional period:

- **First conviction:** You may be required to take a DMV-approved traffic safety course, and your GDL restriction clock can be **extended**.
- **Second conviction within the GDL period:** Your driving privileges can be **suspended for 90 days** or until you turn 17, whichever is longer.
- **Third conviction:** Suspension until age 18.

These rules “reset” your timeline — meaning the 6-month passenger and curfew clocks restart, pushing back the day you become a fully unrestricted driver.

## Practical tips

- Put your phone in **Do Not Disturb While Driving** mode automatically.
- Tell friends in advance you can’t drive them for the first 6 months — set expectations early.
- If you have an evening job or extracurriculars, **carry proof** (a paystub, schedule printout, or coach’s note) in the glovebox in case you are stopped after midnight.', 40, 1
);
