INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_or_oregon-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_or_overlay', 'oregon-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Oregon-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Oregon-Specific Rules and Quirks

Every state has driving rules that surprise visitors and newly licensed teens. This lesson covers Oregon’s most distinctive laws — the ones that affect daily driving and that out-of-state drivers most often get wrong.

## Self-service gas (mostly) — finally

For decades, Oregon was one of only two U.S. states (with New Jersey) that **banned self-service gasoline at retail stations**. As of August 2023, Oregon law changed: **drivers may now pump their own gas statewide**. Stations are required to still offer attendant service for those who want it (at least half of the pumps if they have an attendant on duty), but you are free to pump your own fuel.

If you grew up in Oregon, this is a habit shift. If you visit New Jersey, remember: there, self-serve is still banned.

## Studded tires have a season

Oregon allows **studded snow tires** only between **November 1 and March 31**. Driving with studded tires outside that window is a traffic violation. The state has long debated banning studs entirely because of the pavement damage they cause; for now, the seasonal limit stands.

Non-studded winter (M+S or 3PMSF-rated) tires and chains have no seasonal restriction.

## Bicycles, e-scooters, and the bike box

Oregon — especially Portland — has heavy bicycle traffic. Two rules to internalize:

- **Three feet to pass.** When passing a bicyclist on a road with a posted speed of 35 mph or less, you must give at least the distance the cyclist would fall if they tipped over (commonly summarized as **3 feet or more**, more on faster roads).
- **Bike boxes.** In Portland and other cities, you will see green-painted **bike boxes** at intersections. Cars must **stop behind** the bike box at a red light (not in it), and right turns on red are prohibited where bike boxes are marked.

## Pedestrians: every intersection is a crosswalk

Under Oregon law (ORS 801.220), **every intersection is a legal crosswalk**, whether or not it is marked with paint. You must **stop and remain stopped** for a pedestrian who is in your lane, the lane next to yours, or stepping off the curb in either of those lanes. Failure to stop is a serious violation and a common cause of teen-driver tickets.

## DUII — Oregon’s name for impaired driving

Oregon calls it **DUII** (Driving Under the Influence of Intoxicants), not DUI. The state has **zero tolerance for drivers under 21**: any measurable amount of alcohol (BAC above 0.00) is grounds for license suspension. For drivers 21+, the limit is 0.08% BAC. Oregon also has an **implied consent law** — refusing a breath test triggers an automatic license suspension and a fine, separate from any criminal charge.

Marijuana is legal for adults 21+ in Oregon, but **driving while impaired by cannabis is still a DUII**. There is no “safe amount” for a driver.

## Roundabouts and “move over”

Oregon has been building **roundabouts** at a steady clip to replace dangerous rural intersections. Always yield to traffic already in the circle, signal your exit, and never stop inside the circle.

Oregon’s **Move Over Law** requires you to change lanes away from any stopped vehicle on the shoulder with flashing lights — police, fire, tow trucks, roadside assistance, **and any vehicle with hazard lights on**. If you cannot safely change lanes, slow down significantly.

## Headlights and weather

When wipers are on for weather, your **headlights must be on** too. Daytime running lights are not enough — full headlights illuminate your tail lights so other drivers can see you in rain or fog, which Oregon has plenty of.

## License plate quirks

Oregon requires a **front and rear license plate** on most passenger vehicles. Out-of-state transplants from single-plate states are often surprised — you must mount both plates, and missing the front plate is a fixable but real traffic violation.', 40, 2
);
