INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_pa_how-to-get-a-pa-learners-permit', 'module_pa_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-pa-learners-permit', 'How to Get a Pennsylvania Learner''s Permit', '## Earning Your Pennsylvania Learner''s Permit

In Pennsylvania, the first step toward a driver''s license is the **learner''s permit**, issued by the **Pennsylvania Department of Transportation (PennDOT)**. You can apply on or after your 16th birthday. Pennsylvania uses a three-stage Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) program: learner''s permit, junior license, and unrestricted license.

### Step 1: Gather Your Paperwork

Before your trip to a PennDOT Driver License Center, assemble the following:

- **Form DL-180** (Non-Commercial Learner''s Permit Application). Applicants under 18 must complete **Form DL-180TT** as well, which requires a parent or legal guardian''s signature in front of a notary or a PennDOT representative.
- **Form DL-180** also includes a **physical examination** section that must be completed and signed by a licensed physician, certified registered nurse practitioner, or physician assistant within the past 6 months.
- **Proof of identity** (certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or other PennDOT-accepted document).
- **Proof of Social Security number** (Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing full SSN).
- **Two proofs of Pennsylvania residency** (utility bill, lease, W-2, etc.). If you''re under 18, your parent''s documents may be used along with the parent consent form.
- **Application fee** (currently $39.50 for a non-commercial learner''s permit; verify the current fee on the PennDOT website before your visit).

### Step 2: Pass the Knowledge Test

At the Driver License Center you''ll take a **multiple-choice knowledge test** covering road signs, traffic laws, and safe-driving practices drawn from the **PA Driver''s Manual (Publication 95)**. The test is 18 questions; you can miss no more than 4. If you fail, you may retest the same day if time permits, or return another day.

You will also pass a **basic vision screening** (20/40 in at least one eye, with or without corrective lenses).

### Step 3: Receive Your Permit

Once you pass, you receive a **camera card** that serves as your interim permit, and your photo permit arrives by mail within 15 days. Your permit is valid for **1 year** (or longer if you''re under 18 — until the day before your 18th birthday plus one year).

### Step 4: Practice — A Lot

With your permit, you may drive only when supervised by a **licensed driver age 21 or older** seated in the front seat. (A spouse who is 18 or older with a valid Pennsylvania license also counts.)

If you are **under 18**, you must complete **65 hours of supervised practice driving**, including:
- **10 hours at night**
- **5 hours in inclement weather** (rain, snow, fog)

Your parent or guardian certifies these hours on **Form DL-180C** when you apply for your junior license. Keep a written log — many parents and instructors use a printed practice log or the official PennDOT form throughout the 6 months.

### Step 5: Hold the Permit for at Least 6 Months

Under-18 applicants must hold the permit **at least 6 months** before taking the road test. You must also be free of any crash or traffic violation for the **6 months immediately preceding** the road test.

When ready, schedule your road test online through PennDOT. Pass it, and you graduate to a **junior driver''s license** — but with restrictions that the next lesson covers in detail.', 35, 0
);
