INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_pa_pa-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_pa_overlay', 'pa-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Pennsylvania GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '## Living With a Pennsylvania Junior License

Passing the road test does **not** mean you get the same license your parents have. Drivers under 18 in Pennsylvania receive a **junior driver''s license**, which carries real, enforceable restrictions for at least the first year. Knowing these rules — and following them — keeps you legal, keeps your insurance affordable, and keeps everyone in your car safer.

### The Nighttime Curfew

Junior license holders **may not drive between 11:00 p.m. and 5:00 a.m.** There are three documented exceptions:

1. Driving to or from **employment**
2. Driving to or from a **volunteer or charitable service** activity
3. Driving to or from a **school-sponsored** activity

If an officer stops you between 11 p.m. and 5 a.m., be ready to show proof — a work schedule from your employer, a note from a coach or club advisor, or similar documentation. "My friend lives across town" is not an exception.

### The Passenger Limit

For the **first 6 months** of your junior license, you may carry **no more than one passenger under age 18** unless those additional passengers are immediate family members (parents, siblings, etc.).

After the first 6 months, if you have **no convictions for driving violations or partial responsibility for a reportable crash**, the limit increases to **up to 3 passengers under 18**. Any violation resets the more restrictive limit.

Note that **immediate family members do not count** toward the limit. Driving your younger sister and her two friends to soccer practice counts as two non-family passengers under 18 — only allowed after the first 6 months and only if you remain violation-free.

### Seat Belts: Stricter Than Adult Law

When the driver is **under 18**, Pennsylvania law requires **every occupant** of the vehicle to be wearing a seat belt — regardless of where they''re sitting. This is a **primary offense**, meaning an officer can stop you specifically for an unbelted passenger. Adult drivers face a secondary belt law for back-seat passengers; for junior drivers, it''s primary for everyone.

### Cell Phones and Distraction

Pennsylvania bans **texting while driving** for every driver. As of 2025, Pennsylvania also enforces **Paul Miller''s Law**, a **hands-free** statute that prohibits holding a mobile device for any reason while driving — calls, GPS, music selection, anything. The safest rule for junior drivers: phone goes in Do Not Disturb mode and stays out of your hands until the engine is off.

### Crashes and Violations Have Extra Consequences

A junior driver who accumulates **6 or more points** or is convicted of driving **26+ mph over the limit** faces an automatic **90-day license suspension**. A second occurrence is 6 months. There is no "first-time" leniency.

A **reportable crash** in which you are even partially at fault, or **any** conviction for a violation, can also reset your passenger restriction and delay full licensure.

### Graduating to an Unrestricted License

The junior license automatically converts to an **unrestricted Class C license** on your **18th birthday**, provided you have **no convictions or partial-responsibility crashes for the 12 months prior**. If you do have a recent violation, the restrictions remain until you''ve had a clean 12-month window.

In short: drive like the restrictions matter, because they do — and the cleanest path to an adult license is to never give an officer a reason to stop you.', 30, 1
);
