INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_pa_pa-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_pa_overlay', 'pa-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Pennsylvania-Specific Rules and Road Quirks', '## Driving Rules That Are Distinctly Pennsylvania

Much of traffic law is similar from state to state, but Pennsylvania has several rules and physical road features that surprise new drivers — and out-of-state visitors. Knowing them keeps you safe and out of trouble.

### The Steady Red Arrow Rule

In many states you may turn right on red after stopping, even from a dedicated right-turn lane controlled by a red **arrow**. **Pennsylvania law treats a steady red arrow as a hard stop:** you may **not** turn against a red arrow, even right on red, unless a sign explicitly permits it. A round red ball signal still allows right-on-red (and left-on-red onto a one-way from a one-way) after a complete stop where not prohibited.

### Move Over for Emergency and Disabled Vehicles

Pennsylvania''s **Steer Clear Law** (sometimes referred to with the broader Move Over Law) requires drivers approaching an emergency response area — police, fire, EMS, tow trucks, utility vehicles, or any disabled vehicle with flashing lights or road flares — to **move over one lane** if safe, or **slow to no more than 20 mph below the posted speed limit** (and to no more than 20 mph in work zones) if moving over is not possible. Violations carry significant fines and points.

### Headlights Required With Wipers

Whenever your **windshield wipers are in continuous or intermittent use** due to weather, Pennsylvania law requires your **headlights to be on**. Daytime running lights alone do not satisfy this rule because they typically do not turn on your tail lights. This is one of the easiest tickets to avoid: if wipers are on, lights are on.

### School Bus Stops: All Directions, Almost Always

When a school bus stops with **flashing red lights and the stop arm extended**, traffic in **all directions** must stop — including oncoming traffic — unless you are on the **opposite side of a divided highway separated by a physical barrier or unpaved median**. Painted lines or a center turn lane do **not** count as a divider; you still must stop. The penalty includes a **60-day license suspension**, 5 points, and a $250 fine.

### Roundabouts Are Multiplying

Pennsylvania has invested heavily in **modern roundabouts**, especially on rural and suburban arterials. The rules: yield to traffic already in the circle, enter only when there is a safe gap, do **not** stop inside the roundabout, and **yield to pedestrians** in the crosswalks at the entrance and exit. Trucks may use the apron — give them room.

### Pennsylvania Turnpike: Cashless Tolling

The **Pennsylvania Turnpike** is fully **cashless**. You pay either with an **E-ZPass** transponder or via **Toll By Plate**, which photographs your license plate and bills the registered owner (at a higher rate). There are no toll booths to stop at; just drive through at the posted speed.

### Snow and Ice Removal

Under Pennsylvania law, drivers can be cited if **snow or ice falls from their vehicle** and causes injury or damage to another person or vehicle. Clear your roof, hood, and trunk before driving in winter — a tall SUV with a snow slab on top is a common offender.

### Deer, Potholes, and Two-Lane Mountain Roads

Practical PA quirks: the state leads the nation in deer-vehicle collisions, peaking in **October–December at dawn and dusk**. Slow down, scan the shoulders, and remember deer travel in groups — if one crosses, expect another. On rural two-lane roads, expect **slow-moving farm equipment** and **Amish horse-drawn buggies** (especially in Lancaster, Berks, and surrounding counties); pass only with full visibility of oncoming traffic and never crest a hill or curve while passing.

### Final Tip: Read the Signs, Not the Rumor Mill

A lot of "Pennsylvania driving lore" — about jughandles, U-turns, or right-on-red — is actually about New Jersey or other neighboring states. Trust posted signage and Publication 95 (the PA Driver''s Manual), not what your cousin from across the river told you.', 30, 2
);
