INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ri_how-to-get-a-permit-in-rhode-island', 'module_ri_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-permit-in-rhode-island', 'How to Get Your Limited Instruction Permit in Rhode Island', '# How to Get Your Limited Instruction Permit in Rhode Island

Rhode Island calls the teen learner credential a **Limited Instruction Permit**, and it is issued by the **Rhode Island Division of Motor Vehicles (RI DMV)** out of the Cranston headquarters and a handful of branch offices. This lesson walks through exactly what you need, in what order, so you do not waste a trip to Forand Plaza.

## Step 1: Hit the minimum age

You must be at least **16 years old** to apply. There is no provision for 15-year-olds to begin the permit process in Rhode Island, even with parental consent. If you are under 18, you must also be enrolled in or have completed a state-approved driver education program before the DMV will issue the permit.

## Step 2: Complete driver education (under 18)

Rhode Island requires applicants under 18 to complete a **33-hour classroom course** through a state-licensed driving school or a participating high school program. The course covers Rhode Island traffic law, the GDL system, impaired and distracted driving, sharing the road, and basic vehicle operation. Most programs also include or coordinate a **10-hour behind-the-wheel (BTW)** component with a certified instructor.

When you finish the classroom portion, the school issues you a **Driver Education Certificate of Completion**. Keep the original — the DMV will collect it at the permit appointment.

## Step 3: Gather your documents

Rhode Island uses federal REAL ID standards. Bring originals (not photocopies) of:

- **Proof of identity**: certified birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or permanent resident card.
- **Proof of Social Security number**: SSN card, W-2, or 1099.
- **Two proofs of Rhode Island residency**: utility bill, bank statement, school records, or a parent''s residency affidavit if you live with them.
- **Parent or guardian consent**: a parent or legal guardian must appear in person to sign the consent form if you are under 18.
- **Driver education completion certificate** (if under 18).

## Step 4: Make an appointment

Rhode Island DMV permit testing is **by appointment only** through the RI DMV online portal. Walk-ins for permits are generally not accepted. Appointments at Cranston fill up quickly — book several weeks in advance.

## Step 5: Pass the knowledge and vision tests

At your appointment you will take:

- A **vision screening** (corrective lenses are fine; the restriction will be noted on your permit).
- A **written knowledge test** of 25 multiple-choice questions drawn from the Rhode Island Driver''s Manual. You need 80% to pass. The test covers signs, signals, right-of-way, GDL rules, and safe driving practices. Study the most current edition of the manual — it is updated periodically.

## Step 6: Pay the fee and get your permit

Pay the permit fee at the cashier, take your photo, and you''ll walk out with your Limited Instruction Permit. From this day forward, the **6-month minimum holding period** clock starts ticking. You cannot test for a license sooner than 6 months from the permit issue date, no matter how prepared you feel.

## What the permit lets you do

With a Limited Instruction Permit you may drive **only when accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older** who is seated next to you in the front passenger seat. The supervising driver must have held a valid license for at least 5 years. You may not drive solo — ever — on a permit.

Start logging your **50 hours of supervised practice driving** (including **at least 10 hours at night**) immediately. You will need to certify these hours when you apply for your license.', 45, 0
);
