INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ri_rhode-island-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_ri_overlay', 'rhode-island-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Rhode Island GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Rhode Island GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Rhode Island''s **Graduated Driver License (GDL)** program does not stop at the moment you pass your road test. The **provisional license** you receive at 16.5 (or older) comes with real restrictions that last until you turn 18 — and police actively enforce them. Knowing the rules keeps your license, keeps your insurance affordable, and keeps your passengers safe.

## The provisional license window

When you pass your Rhode Island road test before turning 18, you receive a **provisional license**, not a full unrestricted license. The provisional designation lasts until your 18th birthday. During that window, two restrictions matter most: the **nighttime curfew** and the **passenger limit**.

## Nighttime curfew: 1 AM to 5 AM

Provisional license holders under 18 **may not drive between 1:00 AM and 5:00 AM**. This applies every day of the week, including weekends, holidays, and summer vacation.

There are narrow exceptions if you can document the reason:

- Driving to or from **work** (carry a paystub, work schedule, or letter from your employer).
- Driving to or from a **school-sanctioned event**.
- Driving to or from a **religious activity**.
- A **medical or family emergency**.
- Driving while accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older.

If you get pulled over at 2 AM and cannot produce proof of an exception, expect a citation and a likely license suspension. "I was just driving home from a friend''s house" does not count.

## Passenger limit: one young passenger

For the **first 12 months** after you get your provisional license, you may not transport **more than one passenger under age 21** unless one of the following is true:

- A **parent, legal guardian, or licensed driver age 21+** is in the vehicle, OR
- The additional young passengers are **immediate family members** (siblings, half-siblings, step-siblings living in your household).

This is the rule most often broken — and most often caught — because teens cram four friends into a car for a beach run to Narragansett or a mall trip to Providence Place. A traffic stop, a fender-bender, or a parking lot incident can all expose the violation.

## Cell phone and electronic device ban

Rhode Island has one of the stricter teen distracted-driving laws in the Northeast. If you are **under 18**, you may not use **any** electronic communication device while driving — **handheld or hands-free**. That means no Bluetooth, no speakerphone, no Apple CarPlay phone calls. The only legal use is to call 911 in an emergency.

All drivers, regardless of age, are banned from **texting while driving**, and Rhode Island also has a statewide **handheld phone ban** for drivers of any age. Hands-free is permitted for adults but still forbidden for under-18 provisional drivers.

## Seat belts — non-negotiable

Rhode Island has a **primary seat belt law**: police can pull you over solely for an unbuckled occupant. As the driver, you are responsible for ensuring every passenger under 18 is buckled. Fines and points apply.

## Penalties stack quickly

Violating GDL restrictions can result in:

- A **30-day license suspension** for a first offense.
- **90 days** for a second offense.
- **6 months** for a third.
- Mandatory **reinstatement fees** and possible re-completion of driver education.
- Sharp insurance premium increases — often doubling.

## Practical planning

Build your social and work calendar around the curfew: leave the late shift at Newport restaurants before midnight, or arrange a ride. Decide before you start the car who is riding with you and whether your passenger count is legal. Put your phone in **Do Not Disturb While Driving** mode before you shift into Drive — Rhode Island courts have accepted phone records as evidence in citations.', 40, 1
);
