INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ri_rhode-island-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ri_overlay', 'rhode-island-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Rhode Island-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Rhode Island-Specific Rules and Quirks

Driving in the Ocean State is unlike driving in any of its neighbors. Rhode Island is geographically small, densely populated, and packed with old colonial road layouts that predate the automobile by two centuries. This lesson covers the rules, road features, and seasonal quirks that surprise new RI drivers.

## Rotaries (traffic circles)

Rhode Island has a higher density of **rotaries** — what other states call roundabouts or traffic circles — than almost any other state. Common examples include the **Apponaug rotary in Warwick**, **rotaries on Aquidneck Island**, and several along Route 1 in South County.

The rules:

- **Yield to traffic already in the rotary.** Vehicles inside the circle have the right of way.
- **Enter to the right** and travel **counter-clockwise**.
- **Signal your exit** as you pass the exit before yours.
- **Do not stop inside the rotary** unless necessary to avoid a collision.
- **Large trucks may straddle lanes** — give them room.

Multiple recent reconstructions (notably Apponaug) replaced traffic signals with modern roundabouts. The geometry is engineered to slow traffic to about 20 mph at the entry. Slow down, scan left, and merge smoothly.

## Bridges, tolls, and E-ZPass

Rhode Island operates several major bridges, most famously the **Claiborne Pell Bridge** (the Newport Bridge) connecting Jamestown to Newport, which is **tolled**. The toll is collected electronically — there are no cash booths. Use an **E-ZPass transponder** for the lowest rate; otherwise the system photographs your plate and mails a bill to the registered owner at a higher rate.

The **Mount Hope Bridge** (Bristol to Portsmouth) and the **Jamestown Verrazzano Bridge** are toll-free for now, but tolling policies evolve.

RI also operates **truck-only tolls** on some highway gantries — these do not apply to passenger cars but you will see the gantries.

## Coastal and weather quirks

- **Nor''easters** in winter and early spring bring heavy wet snow, ice, and sustained high winds. Bridges, especially the Pell, may close or impose **wind restrictions** for high-profile vehicles.
- **Flooding** is common in low-lying areas like parts of Warwick, Cranston, and the South County coast during storm surge. **Never drive into standing water** — six inches can stall a car, twelve inches can float one.
- **Sand and salt** on coastal roads year-round affect traction and accelerate vehicle corrosion.
- **Deer** are common throughout western RI (Foster, Glocester, Burrillville) and along Aquidneck Island, particularly at dawn and dusk.

## Narrow colonial streets

Providence''s East Side, Newport, Wickford, and Bristol all have streets that were laid out in the 1600s and 1700s. Expect:

- **Two-way streets so narrow** that one car must yield to oncoming traffic.
- **On-street parking on both sides** further narrowing the travel lane.
- **One-way networks** in Federal Hill, College Hill, and downtown Newport — read signs carefully.
- **Cobblestone and brick surfaces** that are slippery when wet.

## Move Over Law

Rhode Island''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers to change lanes away from any stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or highway maintenance vehicle displaying flashing lights. If changing lanes is not safe, **slow down significantly** below the posted speed limit. Violations carry fines and points.

## School buses

When a school bus stops with its **red lights flashing and stop arm extended**, traffic in **both directions must stop**, except on a divided highway with a physical barrier or median. Rhode Island enforces this aggressively, and many buses now carry stop-arm cameras.

## Inspection and registration

Rhode Island requires **biennial safety and emissions inspections** for most passenger vehicles at licensed inspection stations. A windshield sticker shows the next due date. Driving with an expired inspection is a ticketable offense.

## DUI is zero tolerance for under 21

Rhode Island''s BAC limit is **0.08 for adults**, but for drivers **under 21 it is 0.02** — effectively any detectable alcohol. A first underage DUI brings license suspension, fines, mandatory alcohol education, and a permanent criminal record consideration.

## Headlights and wipers

If your **wipers are on, your headlights must also be on**, day or night. This is the law in Rhode Island and is regularly cited as a contributing factor in rainy-weather crashes.', 40, 2
);
