INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_sc_getting-your-sc-beginners-permit', 'module_sc_overlay', 'getting-your-sc-beginners-permit', 'Getting Your South Carolina Beginner''s Permit', '## Your First Step: The Beginner''s Permit

In South Carolina, the entry point to the Graduated Driver License (GDL) system is the **Beginner''s Permit**, issued by the South Carolina Department of Motor Vehicles (SCDMV). You can apply on or after your **15th birthday**, and the permit must be held for at least **180 days (six months)** before you can move to the next stage.

### Who Issues It and Where

The SCDMV issues permits at any SCDMV branch office. Unlike some states, South Carolina does **not** currently accept online permit applications for first-time teen drivers — you and a parent or legal guardian must appear in person. Walk-ins are accepted, but most branches let you reserve a time slot through the SCDMV website to avoid long waits.

### What to Bring

You will need to present, at minimum:

- **Proof of identity** — a certified U.S. birth certificate or valid U.S. passport.
- **Proof of Social Security number** — your SS card, a W-2, or a 1099.
- **Two proofs of South Carolina residency** — a utility bill, lease, bank statement, or school record bearing your parent''s name and address.
- **A completed SCDMV Form 447-PA** — the parental consent form, signed by your custodial parent or legal guardian in the presence of an SCDMV examiner or notary.
- **Payment** — a small permit fee (currently $2.50 per year of validity, so typically $5).

If you were born outside the United States or are not a U.S. citizen, you must also bring proof of lawful presence (such as a permanent resident card or unexpired visa with I-94).

### The Knowledge and Vision Tests

At the branch you will take:

1. A **vision screening** (you may use corrective lenses; a restriction will be added if you do).
2. A **traffic-sign identification test** — you must correctly identify common signs by shape, color, and meaning.
3. A **30-question written knowledge test** covering South Carolina traffic laws, safe-driving practices, and the contents of the SC Driver''s Manual. You must answer at least **24 questions correctly (80%)** to pass.

The manual is free at any branch and online at scdmvonline.com. The SCDMV also offers a free practice test on its website.

### What the Permit Lets You Do

Once issued, your Beginner''s Permit allows you to drive **between 6:00 a.m. and midnight** with a licensed driver age 21 or older in the front passenger seat. Between **midnight and 6:00 a.m.**, that supervising driver must be your parent or legal guardian. You may **not** drive alone under any circumstances.

### Driver Education and the 40-Hour Log

While you hold your permit, you will:

- Complete an approved **driver education course** (typically 30 hours of classroom plus 6 hours of behind-the-wheel instruction). Completion is required for anyone under 17 who wants to skip the on-road test waiting list or qualify for a Conditional License at 15-and-a-half.
- Log at least **40 hours of supervised driving practice**, including a minimum of **10 hours at night**, on the SCDMV practice-driving log signed by your parent or guardian.

Keep the log with you — examiners may request it when you return to test for your next credential.

### Tip for Test Day

Study the sign chapter carefully. South Carolina is one of the states that tests sign recognition separately from the written exam, and applicants who breeze through the written portion sometimes stumble here.', 35, 0
);
