INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_sc_sc-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_sc_overlay', 'sc-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'SC GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '## Living Under South Carolina''s Graduated Driver License

After your six-month permit period, you can apply for one of two intermediate credentials: a **Conditional License** (if you are at least 15 years and 6 months old and have completed driver education) or a **Special Restricted License** (if you are 16 but did not complete driver education and have waited the additional 90 days required to test). Both come with rules that shape your daily life behind the wheel.

### The Seasonal Curfew — A South Carolina Quirk

Unlike most states that pick a single nighttime cutoff (often 10 or 11 p.m.), South Carolina ties its curfew to **daylight saving time**:

- **November through March:** you may not drive between **6:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m.**
- **April through October:** you may not drive between **8:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m.**

The rule shifts on the same Sunday clocks change. In winter, that means you may need a ride home from any after-school activity that ends after dark. Plan for it — getting pulled over five minutes after the cutoff still counts.

### Curfew Exceptions

You may drive during the restricted hours only if:

1. A **licensed adult 21 or older** is in the front passenger seat, **or**
2. You are traveling **to or from work, school, or a church-related activity** and can document it (a pay stub, schedule, or letter from your employer/school).

"I was on my way home from a friend''s house" is not a recognized exception. Keep documentation in the car.

### Passenger Limits

While holding the Conditional or Special Restricted License you may not transport **more than two passengers under age 21** who are not members of your immediate family — unless a licensed parent or guardian is in the front seat. Immediate family includes siblings, stepsiblings, and others living in your household. This rule exists because crash data consistently shows that teen-driver risk rises sharply with each additional teen passenger.

### Seat Belts

South Carolina is a **primary enforcement** state: an officer can pull you over solely for an unbuckled seat belt. All occupants under 17 must be buckled regardless of seating position. As a new driver, you are responsible for confirming your passengers are belted before you put the car in gear.

### Phones and Distraction

South Carolina law bans **texting while driving** statewide, and several municipalities (Columbia, Mt. Pleasant, Hilton Head, and others) ban any handheld phone use. Even where local handheld use is technically legal, conditional license holders should treat the phone as off-limits while the engine is running. Use Do Not Disturb While Driving or a similar feature.

### Moving to a Full License

The Special Restricted/Conditional License is lifted automatically on your **17th birthday**, provided you have had no major convictions in the previous 12 months. There is no extra test — your license simply converts to a standard Class D. A conviction for reckless driving, DUI, or accumulating six or more points can delay that transition.

### A Practical Daily Checklist

Before you back out of the driveway, ask:

- What time will I be coming home? Is it past my seasonal curfew?
- How many friends will be in the car?
- Is my phone silenced and out of reach?
- Is everyone buckled?

These four questions, asked every trip, prevent the overwhelming majority of citations issued to South Carolina teen drivers.', 30, 1
);
