INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_sc_sc-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_sc_overlay', 'sc-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'South Carolina-Specific Rules and Quirks', '## Rules That Surprise New SC Drivers

Every state has driving rules that catch newcomers off-guard. South Carolina has a handful of laws — some old, some recent — that even lifelong residents sometimes get wrong. Knowing them is the difference between a clean record and a costly ticket.

### Move Over Law

South Carolina''s **Move Over Law** requires drivers approaching any stationary emergency, utility, recovery, or maintenance vehicle displaying flashing lights to:

- Move one lane away from the vehicle if it is safe to do so, **or**
- If moving over is not possible, slow to a safe speed below the posted limit.

The law was expanded in recent years to cover tow trucks, sanitation vehicles, and roadway maintenance vehicles — not just police, fire, and EMS. Violations carry a fine of up to **$500** and can add points to your record. New drivers often forget that the law applies on **all roads**, not just interstates.

### Slow Traffic Keep Right

On multi-lane highways, South Carolina specifically prohibits driving in the **left lane** except when passing. SC Code 56-5-1810 was strengthened in 2021 to make left-lane camping an enforceable offense. If you are cruising in the leftmost lane and faster traffic catches you, move right — even if you are at the speed limit.

### Open Headlights Rule

State law requires headlights to be on:

- From a half-hour after sunset to a half-hour before sunrise.
- Any time **windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to rain, fog, sleet, or snow.

This "wipers on, lights on" rule is enforced and is one of the most common citations issued to new drivers during the rainy spring and tropical-storm seasons that affect the Lowcountry.

### School Buses

When a school bus is stopped with its red lights flashing and stop arm extended:

- On a **two-lane road**, traffic in **both directions** must stop.
- On a divided highway with a physical median or barrier, only traffic **traveling in the same direction** as the bus must stop.

A painted line or center turn lane does **not** count as a divided highway. When in doubt, stop. The penalty for passing a stopped school bus starts at $500 and 6 points.

### Coastal and Tourist Considerations

If you drive in the Lowcountry or along the Grand Strand, watch for:

- **Pedestrian-heavy zones** in Charleston, Beaufort, and Myrtle Beach where jaywalking is common and unmarked crosswalks are legal crossings.
- **Horse-drawn carriages** in downtown Charleston — give them a full lane and pass only when clearly safe.
- **Hurricane evacuation routes** marked with blue-and-white signs; during a declared evacuation, certain interstates (notably I-26 westbound from Charleston) may be lane-reversed.

### Insurance and SR-22

South Carolina requires **minimum liability coverage** of 25/50/25 ($25,000 bodily injury per person, $50,000 per accident, $25,000 property damage) plus uninsured motorist coverage at the same limits. Driving without insurance is a misdemeanor and can result in license suspension. Teen drivers convicted of DUI, reckless driving, or driving without insurance may be required to file an **SR-22** financial-responsibility certificate for three years.

### Renewal Quirk

Standard South Carolina licenses are valid for **eight years**, but those issued to drivers under 21 expire shortly after their 21st birthday — a built-in checkpoint that ensures the photo and restrictions are updated when the driver reaches full drinking and driving age. Plan a SCDMV visit in the months around your 21st birthday.

Mastering these state-specific rules now will keep your record clean as you transition from a Conditional License to your full SC driving privileges.', 30, 2
);
