INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_sd_south-dakota-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_sd_overlay', 'south-dakota-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'South Dakota GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '## Living Inside South Dakota''s Graduated Licensing System

Getting your permit or restricted minor''s permit is just the start. South Dakota''s GDL program controls **when**, **where**, and **with whom** you can drive until you reach an unrestricted license. This lesson translates the legal restrictions into the situations you will actually face: school nights, weekend trips with friends, sports practice, and that first solo drive to a part-time job.

### The Three GDL Stages

1. **Instruction Permit (age 14+)** - supervised driving only with a 18+ licensed driver in the front seat. Valid 180 days; can be renewed.
2. **Restricted Minor''s Permit (age 14.5+)** - allows limited solo driving once the teen has held the instruction permit 6 months with no violations and completed 50 hours of supervised driving.
3. **Full Operator''s License (age 16)** - all GDL restrictions lift. (A 14.5-15.5 year old who completes an approved driver-education course and holds a clean restricted minor''s permit for 180 days may also qualify for the full license before age 16.)

### The Nighttime Curfew

While holding the restricted minor''s permit, you may not drive between **10:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m.** unless:

- A licensed parent, guardian, or driver 18 or older is in the front passenger seat, OR
- You are driving **directly to or from work** or a **school-sponsored activity**.

"Directly" means by the most reasonable route. Stopping for fast food on the way home from work can technically violate the curfew. Bring proof - a pay stub, your work schedule, a coach''s note - in your glove box.

### Passenger Rules

South Dakota does not impose a hard statewide cap on the number of non-family teen passengers during the restricted minor''s permit stage the way Minnesota or California do. But:

- **Every passenger must wear a seat belt** (children under 5 in a child restraint).
- A car full of friends is the #1 distraction factor in crashes involving teen drivers. Schools and insurers strongly recommend limiting passengers during your first 6 months solo.

### Cell Phones and Distracted Driving

South Dakota has two important rules:

1. **Texting is illegal for ALL drivers, of any age.** This includes reading or composing a text or email, whether stopped at a light or moving.
2. **All drivers under 18** are also prohibited from using any wireless communication device - even hands-free - except to report an emergency.

A citation for distracted driving counts as a moving violation. **Any moving violation during the instruction-permit period restarts the 6-month clean-record clock.**

### Seat Belts

South Dakota''s seat-belt law is **primary enforcement for drivers under 18** (and front-seat occupants of any age). If you are under 18, an officer can stop your vehicle solely because a seat belt is unbuckled. Make a habit of checking every passenger before shifting into Drive.

### Daily Scenarios

- **School night, restricted permit, no school activity**: You must be off the road by 10:00 p.m. unless an 18+ licensed driver is in the front seat.
- **Friday football game ending at 10:30 p.m.**: You may drive home directly because it is a school-sponsored activity. Keep the game program or a parent text in the car as evidence.
- **Weekend job ending at 11:00 p.m.**: You may drive directly home from work. No grocery store side trips.
- **Calling your parent on a hands-free Bluetooth at age 17**: Still illegal. The under-18 prohibition covers hands-free use too.
- **Glancing at GPS directions you set before driving**: Allowed - the wireless ban targets active communication, not navigation set in advance. When in doubt, pull over.

### How Violations Set You Back

- During the **instruction permit**: any moving violation resets your 6-month clean-record requirement. You start counting again from the date of the violation.
- During the **restricted minor''s permit**: violations can extend the time before you are eligible for a full license and may trigger a driver-improvement program.
- During the **first year of full licensure**: South Dakota does not have a probationary stage like some states, but your insurance rates will spike sharply after a citation or crash.

### Build Habits That Outlast the Rules

The curfew, the hands-free ban, and the seat-belt rule will all lift the day you turn 16 with a full license. The habits you build before then determine whether you become a safe lifetime driver. Phone in the glove box. Belt on. Headlights on at dusk. Hands at 9-and-3. Practice it now and it will be automatic when the restrictions disappear.', 30, 1
);
