INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_sd_south-dakota-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_sd_overlay', 'south-dakota-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'South Dakota-Specific Rules and Quirks', '## What Makes Driving in South Dakota Different

South Dakota is mostly rural, sparsely populated, and famous for long, straight roads, sudden weather, and wildlife on the shoulder. The laws and quirks below show up on the written test and - more importantly - in real driving. Master them and you will be a safer South Dakota driver from day one.

### 80 mph Rural Interstates

In 2015 the South Dakota Legislature raised the rural interstate speed limit to **80 mph**, one of the highest in the United States. Important nuances:

- 80 mph applies only to the **rural** stretches of I-29 and I-90. Urban segments, construction zones, and many state highways post lower limits.
- At 80 mph your stopping distance can exceed **500 feet**. Increase following distance to at least **4 seconds** in dry conditions and double it in rain.
- Cruise control on long, empty stretches induces drowsiness. Stop every 100 miles, get out, walk around.

### Two-Lane Highways and Passing

Outside the interstates, much of South Dakota is two-lane state and county highway. You will need to pass slower vehicles (often farm equipment) safely.

- Pass only in legally marked passing zones (broken yellow line on your side).
- Never pass within **100 feet** of an intersection, railroad crossing, bridge, or tunnel.
- When meeting an oversize farm vehicle, slow down and move toward the shoulder - tractors and combines may be wider than a lane.

### Wildlife: Deer, Pheasants, and Cattle

South Dakota leads the nation in some categories of animal-vehicle crashes. Dawn and dusk in autumn are the peak risk hours.

- If a deer enters the road, **brake firmly, do not swerve**. Swerving causes most serious injuries in deer crashes.
- Watch for **open-range** areas in the western part of the state. Cattle and bison may legally be on or near the road; a struck animal is your financial responsibility if you exceeded a safe speed for conditions.
- Slow vehicle (orange triangle) emblems indicate something moving 25 mph or less - common on rural roads.

### Winter Driving and "No Travel Advised"

Winter conditions in South Dakota change quickly.

- The Department of Transportation issues road condition reports ranging from green (normal) to **"No Travel Advised"** and ultimately **road closure**. Driving during a no-travel advisory can result in being charged for rescue costs.
- Carry a winter kit: blanket, water, snacks, flashlight, cell-phone charger, traction aid.
- Plug-in block heaters are common in older diesels. Make sure you unplug before pulling away.

### School Bus Stops

South Dakota requires drivers on **both sides** of a two-lane road to stop when a school bus has its **red lights flashing and stop arm extended**. On a divided highway (median or physical barrier), only traffic moving in the same direction as the bus must stop.

### Move Over Law

When approaching a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or maintenance vehicle with flashing lights, drivers must **move over** to a non-adjacent lane when safe, or **slow down significantly** if moving over is not possible. Failure to do so is a fineable offense and frequently appears on the written test.

### Implied Consent and Zero Tolerance

By driving in South Dakota you give implied consent to a chemical test if a peace officer has probable cause to suspect impaired driving.

- Adults: legal BAC limit **0.08%**.
- Drivers under 21: **zero tolerance**. Any detectable alcohol (0.02%) can result in license suspension.
- Refusing a chemical test results in an automatic license revocation.

### Headlights and Visibility

Headlights must be on:

- From **sunset to sunrise**.
- Whenever weather (rain, snow, fog, dust) reduces visibility to less than **200 feet**.
- Whenever windshield wipers are in continuous use - a good rule of thumb statewide.

### Mount Rushmore, Sturgis, and Tourist Traffic

From late spring through fall the Black Hills, Badlands, and Sturgis Motorcycle Rally bring out-of-state traffic. During the **Sturgis Rally (early August)** the western half of the state sees hundreds of thousands of motorcyclists.

- Allow at least **4 seconds following distance** behind motorcycles.
- Check blind spots twice before lane changes - motorcycles are easy to miss.
- Expect sudden slowdowns near scenic viewpoints (Needles Highway, Iron Mountain Road).

### Quirky Rules Worth Knowing

- Motorcycle helmets are required **only for riders and passengers under 18** in South Dakota. As a car driver, expect to share the road with many unhelmeted riders.
- **Studded snow tires** are legal between October 1 and April 30 only.
- **U-turns** are legal unless prohibited by sign and may not be made on any curve or grade where the driver cannot be seen by another vehicle within 1,000 feet.

Knowing these South Dakota-specific rules is the difference between passing the written test and being prepared for the realities of the state''s roads.', 30, 2
);
