INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_tn_how-to-get-a-tn-learner-permit', 'module_tn_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-tn-learner-permit', 'How to Get a Tennessee Learner Permit', '# How to Get a Tennessee Learner Permit

In Tennessee, the Learner Permit is the first stage of the Graduated Driver License (GDL) program. It is issued by the **Tennessee Department of Safety and Homeland Security, Driver Services Division** (often just called "Driver Services" or the DOS). You cannot legally practice on public roads as a teen driver without it, so understanding the process matters.

## Step 1: Confirm you meet the age requirement

You must be **at least 15 years old** to apply for a Learner Permit in Tennessee. There is no upper age limit, but applicants under 18 are subject to additional rules described below.

## Step 2: Gather your documents

Tennessee uses federal REAL ID document standards. You will need to bring originals (not copies) of:

- **Proof of U.S. citizenship or lawful presence** — a certified U.S. birth certificate or U.S. passport is the most common choice.
- **Proof of Social Security Number** — a Social Security card, W-2, or paystub showing your SSN.
- **Two proofs of Tennessee residency** — utility bill, bank statement, school enrollment letter, or lease. If you live with your parents, your parents'' documents plus an affidavit can work.
- **Parental consent (if under 18)** — a parent or legal guardian must appear in person at the Driver Services Center to sign the **Minor/Teenage Affidavit and Cancellation (Form SF-0259)**, which makes them financially responsible for your driving.
- **Proof of school compliance (if under 18)** — the **Certificate of Compulsory School Attendance**, signed by a school official within the last 30 days. This is required by Tennessee''s School Attendance and Dropout Prevention law (SADAP).

## Step 3: Visit a Driver Services Center

Learner Permits are issued in person at any **Driver Services Center**. Tennessee does **not** issue Learner Permits online or by mail. You can reserve an appointment through the Driver Services website, which dramatically reduces wait times.

At the center you will:

1. Submit your documents.
2. Pass a **vision screening** (corrective lenses are fine; a restriction will be added to your permit).
3. Pass the **knowledge test** — a multiple-choice exam based on the *Tennessee Comprehensive Driver License Manual*. The test covers road signs, signals, right-of-way, GDL restrictions, and safe driving practices. You need a passing score (commonly 80%) to qualify.
4. Have your photo taken and pay the permit fee.

If you pass, you typically leave with a temporary paper permit; your permanent card arrives by mail within a few weeks.

## Step 4: Understand what a permit lets you do

A Tennessee Learner Permit allows you to drive **only when accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older who is seated in the front passenger seat**. You must hold the permit for **at least 180 days (6 months)** without any traffic convictions or seat-belt violations before applying for an Intermediate Restricted License at age 16.

During those six months, you must also log **50 hours of supervised driving practice, including at least 10 hours at night**, certified by a parent or guardian on the **Affidavit of Driving Experience** form. Keep your log accurate — Driver Services can ask to see it.

## Step 5: Plan for the next stage

The permit is not the end goal — it is a learning stage. While you hold it:

- Build hours behind the wheel in a variety of conditions: highway, rain, dusk, congested traffic.
- Avoid any moving violations; a citation can reset your 180-day clock.
- If you are taking a driver education course, schedule your behind-the-wheel sessions early so they don''t bottleneck your road-test eligibility at 16.

Follow this process carefully and you will arrive at your 16th birthday ready to take the road skills test for the Intermediate Restricted License.', 35, 0
);
