INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_tn_how-to-get-a-tn-learner-permit_3', 'quiz_tn_how-to-get-a-tn-learner-permit', 'When driving with a Tennessee Learner Permit, who must be in the vehicle with you?', '["Any licensed driver age 18 or older in any seat","A licensed driver age 21 or older in the front passenger seat","A parent only, in any seat","No one — solo driving is allowed during daylight"]', 1, 'Tennessee requires a supervising driver who is at least 21 and seated in the front passenger seat.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_tn_how-to-get-a-tn-learner-permit_4', 'quiz_tn_how-to-get-a-tn-learner-permit', 'How many hours of supervised driving practice must a Tennessee teen log before taking the road skills test, and how many must be at night?', '["30 hours total, 5 at night","40 hours total, 10 at night","50 hours total, 10 at night","60 hours total, 15 at night"]', 2, 'Tennessee requires 50 total hours of supervised practice with at least 10 hours after dark.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_tn_tn-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_tn_overlay', 'tn-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Tennessee GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Tennessee GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Tennessee''s Graduated Driver License (GDL) program has three stages: **Learner Permit**, **Intermediate Restricted License**, and **Intermediate Unrestricted License**. Each stage layers on new freedoms while still limiting the highest-risk behaviors for teen drivers. Knowing the restrictions in real-world terms — not just textbook language — keeps your license clean.

## Stage 1: Learner Permit (age 15)

- **Supervision required at all times.** A licensed driver age 21+ must occupy the front passenger seat whenever the wheel is in your hands.
- **No solo driving — ever.** Driving alone, even to the end of the driveway on a public road, is a violation.
- **Seat belts for everyone.** A seat-belt citation can reset your 180-day permit clock.
- **No cell phones.** Drivers under 18 may not use a cell phone or other wireless device while driving, even hands-free.

Daily life: This stage is about practice with a parent or coach. Most teens use the permit to commute to school with a parent, drive on weekend errands, and rack up the 50 required practice hours.

## Stage 2: Intermediate Restricted License (age 16)

Granted at 16 after the 180-day permit period, 50 logged hours, and a passing road skills test. You can now drive solo — but with two important limits:

- **Nighttime restriction.** You may not drive between **11:00 PM and 6:00 AM**. Exceptions exist for documented driving to/from work, school events, or religious activities, and when accompanied by a parent, legal guardian, or licensed adult 21+. Carry documentation (work schedule, school activity letter) if you''ll be on the road during restricted hours.
- **Passenger restriction.** You may transport **only one passenger** at a time. Siblings, friends, classmates — all count. The only exceptions are when a parent or licensed adult 21+ is supervising.

Daily life examples:
- Driving yourself to and from a 6:30 AM swim practice — fine, but be aware 6:00 AM is the cutoff for the nighttime restriction.
- Taking two friends to a movie — **not allowed**; you can only take one passenger.
- Driving home from a closing shift that ends at 11:30 PM — allowed if you have a copy of your work schedule in the car.
- Driving siblings to school — only one sibling at a time unless a parent rides along.

## Stage 3: Intermediate Unrestricted License (age 17)

At age 17, restrictions ease but do not disappear:

- The nighttime restriction is lifted.
- You may carry up to **three passengers under 18** who are not immediate family. (Family members do not count toward the limit.)
- The under-18 cell phone ban still applies until you turn 18.

This stage still feels like teen driving with training wheels: you have more freedom, but the state still recognizes that crash rates for 17-year-olds are higher than for adults.

## Statewide rules that apply to every Tennessee driver

GDL restrictions stack on top of laws that apply to everyone:

- **Hands-free law.** No Tennessee driver may hold a phone or text while driving. For drivers under 18, the rule is even stricter — no wireless device use at all.
- **Move Over law.** Change lanes or slow down for stopped emergency, utility, and tow vehicles.
- **Open container law.** No open alcoholic beverages in the passenger area.
- **Zero tolerance for under-21 drinking and driving.** A BAC of 0.02 or higher results in license suspension.

## Consequences of GDL violations

Violating a GDL restriction is a traffic offense in Tennessee. Penalties can include fines, license suspension, and — for permit holders — a reset of the 180-day waiting period. Insurance rates also climb quickly after any teen traffic conviction. Treat the restrictions as bright lines, not suggestions, and you''ll arrive at your 18th birthday with a clean record and a full license.', 30, 1
);
