INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_tn_tn-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_tn_overlay', 'tn-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Tennessee-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Teen Driver Should Know', '# Tennessee-Specific Rules and Quirks Every Teen Driver Should Know

Most driving laws look similar from state to state, but Tennessee has a handful of unique rules that surprise new drivers — including some that can suspend your license long before you ever get a speeding ticket. This lesson covers the Tennessee-specific quirks worth memorizing.

## 1. SADAP — the School Attendance and Dropout Prevention law

Tennessee is one of the strictest states in the country about linking driving privileges to school attendance. Under the **School Attendance and Dropout Prevention (SADAP)** program:

- If you are **under 18 and drop out of school**, your driver license or permit is automatically revoked.
- If you accumulate **10 or more unexcused absences in a semester**, the school must report you, and your driving privileges can be suspended.
- If you have failing grades in more than half your courses, you can also lose your license.

To apply for a Learner Permit you must present a **Certificate of Compulsory School Attendance** signed within the past 30 days. You can also lose your driving privileges through SADAP even after you''ve been licensed for months. The lesson: in Tennessee, the school principal can take your keys.

## 2. Statewide hands-free law

Tennessee was relatively late to pass a strong distracted-driving law, but the current statute is strict. **All drivers, regardless of age**, are prohibited from:

- Holding a phone with any part of their body while driving.
- Writing, sending, or reading text messages.
- Watching videos.
- Recording video.

First-offense fines start at $50 and rise for repeat or work-zone violations. For drivers **under 18**, the rule is even stricter: no wireless device use at all, even hands-free. Mounted phones on speakerphone or via car Bluetooth are the only safe option.

## 3. "Slowpoke" left-lane law

Tennessee enforces a left-lane-must-yield rule on multi-lane highways. If you are in the left (passing) lane and a faster vehicle approaches from behind, you must move right to let it pass. Violations can be ticketed. New teen drivers often default to the left lane out of habit on interstates like I-40 or I-65 — get comfortable cruising in the right lane and using the left only to pass.

## 4. Move Over law — broader than most states

Tennessee''s Move Over law applies not just to police, fire, and ambulance vehicles, but also to **utility vehicles, road maintenance crews, and tow trucks** with flashing lights on the shoulder. Either change lanes away from the stopped vehicle or slow to a safe, reasonable speed if changing lanes is unsafe.

## 5. Headlights when wipers are on

A classic Tennessee quirk: if your **windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to rain, fog, or other weather, your **headlights must be on**. Running daytime running lights or parking lights only is a violation. This rule matters in Tennessee''s frequent summer thunderstorms and morning fog in valleys and along rivers.

## 6. School bus stop-arm — both directions on undivided roads

When a school bus stops with its stop-arm extended and red lights flashing:

- On a **two-lane or undivided road**, traffic in **both directions** must stop.
- On a **divided highway with a physical median or barrier**, only traffic traveling in the **same direction** as the bus must stop.

Violations carry steep fines and can be reported by camera systems on the buses.

## 7. Implied consent

By accepting a Tennessee driver license or permit, you have given **implied consent** to a chemical test (breath, blood, or urine) if an officer has reasonable cause to suspect impaired driving. Refusing the test results in an automatic **one-year license suspension** for a first refusal — independent of any DUI charge. For drivers under 21, a BAC of just 0.02 is enough to trigger zero-tolerance suspension.

## 8. Funeral procession right-of-way

Tennessee gives funeral processions the right of way at intersections. Even if you have a green light, you must yield to a clearly marked funeral procession that has begun crossing. This catches out-of-state drivers off guard but is well-known in Tennessee communities.

## Putting it together

The biggest Tennessee-specific risks to a teen driver''s license are **not** dramatic crashes — they are everyday mistakes: skipping school, holding a phone at a stoplight, or cruising in the left lane. Treat SADAP and the hands-free law as seriously as you''d treat a stop sign, and you''ll keep your driving privileges intact.', 30, 2
);
