INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_tx_tx-how-to-get-a-permit', 'module_tx_overlay', 'tx-how-to-get-a-permit', 'Getting Your Texas Learner License: Parent-Taught vs. Traditional Driver Ed', '# Getting Your Texas Learner License

In Texas, a teen driver''s journey begins with the **learner license** — the credential that lets you legally practice driving with a licensed adult in the passenger seat. The Texas Department of Public Safety (DPS) issues the license, but you cannot apply until you have started or completed a state-approved driver education program. This lesson walks you through eligibility, the three legal pathways to driver ed, and exactly what to bring to the DPS office.

## Eligibility at a Glance

You must be **at least 15 years old** to apply for a Texas learner license. You must also be enrolled in (and making progress through) an approved driver education course, and you must pass a written knowledge test and a vision exam. If you are under 18, a parent or legal guardian must accompany you to the DPS office and sign for you. You''ll also need to provide proof of identity, U.S. citizenship or lawful presence, Texas residency, Social Security number, and — for applicants under 18 — proof of school enrollment, called a **Verification of Enrollment (VOE)**, which your school issues.

## The Three Pathways to Texas Driver Education

Texas is one of the few states that allows parents to teach driver education at home. Your family can choose:

### 1. Parent-Taught Driver Education (PTDE)
PTDE is administered by the **Texas Department of Licensing and Regulation (TDLR)**. To qualify as a parent-instructor, you must order a PTDE Program Guide from TDLR, be the teen''s parent, stepparent, legal guardian, grandparent, or court-appointed managing conservator, hold a valid driver license for at least three years, and have no convictions for DWI or criminally negligent homicide in the prior three years. You then purchase a TDLR-approved PTDE course (there are several vendors) and teach the 32 hours of classroom material plus supervise the 14 hours of behind-the-wheel and observation time at home. PTDE is popular because it is flexible, lower cost, and lets families control the schedule.

### 2. Traditional Classroom (Licensed Driving School)
A TDLR-licensed commercial driving school delivers the classroom instruction in person and provides behind-the-wheel training with a state-licensed instructor in a properly equipped car. This pathway works well when parents prefer not to teach, when the teen learns better in a peer setting, or when the family wants in-car instruction from a professional from day one.

### 3. TDLR-Approved Online Course
The 32 hours of classroom content can be taken entirely online through a TDLR-approved provider. The behind-the-wheel portion still has to be done either with a parent (under PTDE rules) or with a licensed commercial driving school.

All three pathways teach the same state curriculum and end with the same outcome: a completion certificate that satisfies the DPS requirement.

## The Six-Hour Rule

Texas teens may apply for the learner license after completing the **first six hours of classroom instruction** (often called "Phase 1, Module 1"). You do not have to finish the full 32 hours before going to DPS. Your driver ed provider will issue an interim certificate documenting those first six hours.

## At the DPS Office

Make an appointment at your local DPS driver license office (walk-ins are usually slammed). Bring:

- Your driver ed six-hour completion certificate (or full DE-964 if you''ve finished)
- Proof of identity (certified birth certificate or U.S. passport)
- Proof of Social Security number
- Two documents proving Texas residency in the parent''s name
- Verification of Enrollment (VOE) from your school, dated within 30 days
- Your parent or guardian, who must sign in person
- Application fee (currently $16 for the learner license)

You''ll take the **written knowledge test** (covering signs and traffic laws) and a vision screening. Pass both, and DPS issues a paper learner license on the spot; the plastic card arrives by mail in a few weeks.

## What Comes Next

With your learner license in hand, the six-month clock starts. You must hold the learner license for **at least six months** (and be at least 16) before you can take the road test for a provisional license. During those six months, finish the rest of your driver ed, log your supervised practice hours, and prepare for the Impact Texas Teen Drivers video that you''ll need within 90 days of your skills test.', 45, 0
);
