INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_tx_tx-gdl-daily-life', 'module_tx_overlay', 'tx-gdl-daily-life', 'Living With Texas GDL Restrictions: The First Year of Your Provisional License', '# Living With Texas GDL Restrictions

When a Texas teen passes the road test, DPS issues a **provisional driver license** — a real license, but one with extra rules attached for the first year (and until your 18th birthday). These rules are Texas''s version of a **Graduated Driver License (GDL)** program, and the restrictions exist because crash data consistently shows the first 6–12 months of solo driving are by far the highest-risk window of a person''s driving life. Understanding them is not just about avoiding tickets; it''s about not becoming a statistic.

## What the Provisional License Allows — and What It Doesn''t

A Texas provisional license looks and functions like a regular Class C license, except that two specific restrictions apply during the **first 12 months** after issuance:

### Passenger Restriction
You may not have **more than one passenger under age 21** in the vehicle at any time, unless those additional passengers are members of your immediate family. "Immediate family" means brothers, sisters, stepsiblings, and similar — not friends, cousins you grew up with, or your boyfriend''s little sister. The rule is strict: the moment a second non-family passenger under 21 gets in, you''re in violation, even on a short drive to a coffee shop.

**Real-life translation:** If you and three teammates need to get to a Friday night game, you can take one of them in your car. The other two need another ride. If you have two younger siblings and a friend, the friend can''t come.

### Nighttime Driving Restriction
You may not drive between **midnight and 5:00 a.m.** unless you''re driving:
- To or from work,
- To or from a school-related activity, or
- Because of a medical emergency.

This is one of the tightest windows in the country — many states'' curfews start at 10 or 11 p.m. — but it covers exactly the hours when fatigue, impairment, and crash risk peak. If you take a shift at a restaurant that ends at 1 a.m., you''re fine driving home. If you''re driving back from a friend''s house after a movie, you''re not — even if you''re three blocks away.

## The Cell Phone Rule (This One''s Strict)

Texas bans **all wireless communication device use** by drivers under 18, including hands-free systems, except in a true emergency. That means:

- No talking on the phone, even through Bluetooth.
- No texting, even at a stoplight.
- No navigating an app while in motion (set it before you put the car in drive).
- No music app interactions beyond starting a pre-loaded playlist.

The statewide texting-while-driving ban applies to drivers of every age, and handheld use in active school zones is illegal for everyone. For teens, though, the bar is much higher: any device interaction is a violation, regardless of how the device is held.

## Seat Belts and Passengers

Texas law requires every occupant of a moving vehicle to wear a seat belt, and as the driver, you''re legally responsible for passengers under 17 who aren''t buckled. Children under 8 (and under 4''9") must be in an appropriate child safety seat. If you''re driving younger siblings around, this is now your legal responsibility every trip.

## What Happens If You Violate a GDL Rule?

Violations of the passenger or nighttime restrictions are moving violations. Beyond the fine, they put a conviction on your record, which can trigger:

- A required driver safety course,
- License suspension (especially after a second offense),
- A skyrocketing insurance premium — teen insurance is already expensive; one ticket can double it,
- An extension of the restriction period in some cases.

DPS also runs a points system. Two moving violations in 12 months or three in 24 months triggers a surcharge, and license suspension can follow.

## When Does It All End?

The passenger and nighttime restrictions automatically lift on the **earlier of**: 12 months after the provisional license was issued, or your 18th birthday. The cell phone restriction lifts on your 18th birthday. Until then, the rules are the rules — even when they feel inconvenient. Plan rides ahead. Schedule late-night work shifts knowing the curfew. Tell friends up front you can only take one of them. The freedom of driving in Texas is real, but the first year is a probationary period in everything but name.', 40, 1
);
