INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_tx_tx-ittd-and-quirks', 'module_tx_overlay', 'tx-ittd-and-quirks', 'Texas Quirks: Impact Texas Teen Drivers (ITTD), Move Over, and Other Lone Star Rules', '# Texas Quirks: ITTD, Move Over, and Other Lone Star Rules

Every state has its own driving culture and a handful of laws that catch out-of-staters by surprise. Texas is no exception. This lesson covers the rules that are unique — or unusually emphasized — in Texas and that you''ll be tested on, ticketed for, or simply expected to know.

## Impact Texas Teen Drivers (ITTD)

Probably the single most distinctive Texas requirement is the **Impact Texas Teen Drivers** program, often shortened to ITTD. It''s a free, two-hour video produced by DPS that uses real footage and survivor stories from Texas crashes involving teen drivers. Topics include distracted driving, impairment, speed, and seat-belt use.

**The key rule: every Texas applicant under 18 must complete ITTD within 90 days before taking the driving skills test.** If you watched it 91 days before your test, it''s expired and you''ll have to watch it again. DPS examiners will check for the completion certificate before they administer your skills test — show up without it and you''ll be sent home.

Applicants who are 18–24 must complete a similar program called **Impact Texas Young Drivers (ITYD)**, which is shorter but works the same way: complete it within 90 days of the skills test. (The whole umbrella program is called **Impact Texas Drivers, or ITD**.)

The video is free at impacttexasdrivers.dps.texas.gov. Treat it as a checklist item, but actually watch it — the content is genuinely sobering and is some of the most effective driver-safety material the state produces.

## The Move Over / Slow Down Law

Texas''s **Move Over law** requires drivers approaching a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, TxDOT vehicle, or utility service vehicle with activated lights to either:

- **Move over** one lane away from the stopped vehicle, or
- **Slow down** to 20 mph below the posted speed limit (or to 5 mph if the limit is 25 mph or less).

This applies on highways, surface streets, and frontage roads. Texas has aggressively expanded this law over the years — it now covers tow trucks and even sanitation vehicles — because roadside fatalities for first responders have been climbing. Violations carry fines that escalate sharply if anyone is injured.

## Frontage Roads, Texas U-Turns, and the Two-Way/One-Way Question

Texas highways famously feature **frontage roads** (sometimes called "access roads" or "feeders") parallel to interstates. In urban areas, most are **one-way** in the direction of highway traffic; in rural areas, many are **two-way**. The sign at the entrance ramp tells you which. Driving the wrong way on a one-way frontage road is one of the most common — and most dangerous — out-of-state-driver mistakes in Texas.

The **"Texas U-turn"** is a free left turn lane that bridges over or under the highway, letting frontage-road drivers reverse direction without a traffic light. They''re convenient but require you to yield to traffic coming off the highway exit ramp.

## Open Container — Even For Passengers

Texas''s open container law prohibits any open container of alcohol in the **passenger area** of a vehicle on a public highway, whether the vehicle is moving or parked. Unlike some states, the rule applies to passengers as well as the driver. For a teen driver, the consequences of being pulled over with an open container — even one belonging to a passenger — can include a DUI charge under Texas''s **zero-tolerance law for minors**, which forbids any detectable alcohol in a driver under 21.

## Driver Responsibility Surcharges and Failure to Maintain Financial Responsibility

Driving without liability insurance in Texas is a **Failure to Maintain Financial Responsibility** offense and carries fines starting around $175–$350 for a first offense and escalating after that, plus the possibility of license and registration suspension. Texas requires a minimum **30/60/25** liability policy (30,000 per person bodily injury, 60,000 per crash, 25,000 property damage). Always keep proof of insurance accessible — many Texans use the digital insurance card on their phone, which is legally accepted.

## School Buses and Stopped-Bus Rules

When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and the stop arm extended, you must stop — **from both directions** on undivided roads. The only exception is on a divided highway where a physical barrier or median separates oncoming traffic; in that case, only vehicles traveling in the same direction as the bus must stop. Penalties in Texas are severe: fines up to $1,250 for a first offense.

## The Practical Takeaway

Texas''s distinctive rules cluster around three themes: protecting teen drivers from themselves (ITTD, GDL), protecting roadside workers and school children (Move Over, school bus rules), and the unusual road geometry of Texas highways (frontage roads, Texas U-turns). Knowing them isn''t just about passing the test — it''s about driving safely in a state with the most highway miles in the country.', 35, 2
);
