INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_ut_utah-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_ut_overlay', 'utah-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Utah-Specific Rules and Quirks', '# Utah-Specific Rules and Quirks

National driver-ed curricula cover the basics of stop signs, right-of-way, and freeway merging. But Utah has a handful of rules and conditions that catch out-of-state drivers — and new Utah teens — by surprise. This lesson covers them.

## 1. The ''Utah Left'' is illegal — but turning on a steady red after a left-turn-only red arrow is sometimes allowed

Utah allows a **left turn on red from a one-way street onto another one-way street** after stopping, when no sign prohibits it. Right turns on red are also permitted after a full stop, unless posted otherwise. What is **not** allowed is the ''Utah Left'' — a U-turn from a center turn lane to avoid a no-left-turn restriction. Use the next protected intersection instead.

## 2. .00 BAC for drivers under 21 — and Utah''s adult limit is .05

Utah was the first state to lower the adult per-se DUI limit to **.05 BAC** (most states are .08). For drivers under 21, the legal limit is effectively **zero** under Utah''s ''Not-A-Drop'' law. Any measurable alcohol can trigger an automatic license suspension of at least six months for a first offense, plus mandatory ignition interlock when reinstated.

## 3. Cannabis and prescription medications

Utah has a limited medical cannabis program, but driving under the influence of cannabis — including any detectable THC metabolite — is a DUI. Many common prescription medications (opioids, benzodiazepines, certain ADHD stimulants, some antihistamines) can also support a DUI charge. If a label says ''may cause drowsiness,'' do not drive until you know how it affects you.

## 4. Snow, ice, and the ''Cottonwoods''

If you drive in the Wasatch Front, you will encounter winter conditions for roughly five months a year. Specific Utah quirks:

- **Tire-traction law in the canyons.** From November 1 through April 30, vehicles entering Little Cottonwood and Big Cottonwood Canyons (SR-210 and SR-190) may be required to have **snow tires, all-season M+S tires, or chains**. UDOT posts the requirement on variable message signs and enforces it with fines up to $750 if you cause a road closure.
- **Black ice on shaded curves.** Bridges, overpasses, and north-facing curves stay icy long after the rest of the road is dry. Slow down well before the curve, not in it.
- **Inversion days.** The valley''s winter air-quality inversions cut visibility and irritate eyes; turn on headlights even at midday and increase following distance.

## 5. Move-Over Law

Utah''s Move-Over law requires drivers to move over one lane (or slow down significantly if moving over is unsafe) when approaching **any stopped vehicle with flashing lights** — police, fire, EMS, tow trucks, UDOT vehicles, and even ordinary motorists using hazard flashers on the shoulder.

## 6. School buses and flashing red lights

On a two-lane road, traffic in **both directions** must stop for a school bus displaying flashing red lights and an extended stop arm. On a divided highway with a physical median or barrier, only traffic traveling in the **same direction** as the bus must stop.

## 7. Headlights: when the wipers are on

Utah requires headlights when visibility is less than 1,000 feet, between sunset and sunrise, and **any time windshield wipers are in continuous use** due to weather. Daytime running lights do not satisfy this rule — your taillights must also be on.

## 8. Vehicle registration and proof of insurance

Utah requires **liability insurance** ($25,000 / $65,000 / $15,000 minimums) and **personal injury protection** ($3,000 minimum). Proof of insurance can be presented electronically (a phone screen is acceptable) at a traffic stop. Driving without insurance is a class B misdemeanor and triggers an immediate license suspension.', 30, 2
);
