INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_va_getting-your-virginia-learners-permit', 'module_va_overlay', 'getting-your-virginia-learners-permit', 'How to Get a Learner''s Permit in Virginia', '## The Virginia Path to a Learner''s Permit

In Virginia, the learner''s permit is your legal authorization to begin practicing on public roads with a licensed adult. The Virginia Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) — not the courts or the school — issues the permit, and the requirements are codified in the Code of Virginia.

### Minimum Age and Who Must Sign

You may apply for a learner''s permit at **age 15 years and 6 months**. If you are under 18, a parent, legal guardian, foster parent, or grandparent (when the grandparent is the primary caregiver) must appear at the DMV with you and sign the application. This signature legally accepts responsibility for your driving until you turn 18 and can be withdrawn at any time — if it is withdrawn, your permit or license is canceled.

### Documents You Must Bring

Virginia requires you to prove four things at the counter:

1. **Identity** — typically a certified U.S. birth certificate or unexpired passport.
2. **Legal presence** — the identity document usually covers this.
3. **Social Security number** — your SSN card, W-2, or 1099.
4. **Two proofs of Virginia residency** — a utility bill, bank statement, school enrollment letter, or similar mail addressed to your home. If you live with a parent, the parent can use the *Proof of Residency* affidavit (DMV Form DL 5) and provide their own proofs.

All Virginia credentials default to **REAL ID** compliance only if you specifically request it and present the upgraded document set; otherwise you receive a standard credential marked "Not for federal identification."

### The Knowledge and Vision Tests

At the DMV office you will take:

- A **vision screening** (20/40 in at least one eye, with or without corrective lenses).
- A **two-part knowledge test**: a 10-question road signs portion (you must get all 10 right, with retakes allowed within the same visit) and a 25-question general knowledge portion (you must get at least 20 right). Both come from the *Virginia Driver''s Manual*, which is free online.

If you fail either portion, you must wait **15 days** before retesting.

### Fees and Processing

The permit fee is modest (currently around $3 per year of validity), and Virginia mails the physical permit to your home within about 10–15 business days. In the meantime you drive on a **paper interim permit** printed at the DMV office.

### Holding Period and What Comes Next

Once issued, you must hold the permit for **at least 9 months** before you are eligible for a driver''s license, and you must remain conviction-free of any traffic offense during that period — a single conviction can restart the 9-month clock. During the holding period you must:

- Always be accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older (or a licensed sibling, spouse, or stepsibling at least 18) seated in the front passenger seat.
- Carry no more than one passenger under age 21 who is not a family member.
- Complete a state-approved **driver education program** (36 classroom periods plus 14 in-car periods of 50 minutes each — 7 behind the wheel and 7 observation).
- Log **45 hours of supervised practice**, including at least 15 hours after sunset, on the DMV''s official **Form DEC 1**, signed by a parent or guardian.

When all requirements are met and you are at least **16 years and 3 months old**, you become eligible for the driver''s license — which in Virginia is typically presented at a **juvenile court license ceremony** rather than at the DMV counter.', 35, 0
);
