INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_vt_how-to-get-a-vermont-learner-permit', 'module_vt_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-vermont-learner-permit', 'How to Get a Learner Permit in Vermont', '# How to Get a Learner Permit in Vermont

Getting your Learner Permit in Vermont is the first official step in the state''s Graduated Driver License (GDL) program. This lesson walks you through exactly what you need, where to go, and what to expect on test day.

## Who issues your permit

The **Vermont Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV)** issues all driver credentials in the state. The main office is in Montpelier, but there are branch offices and mobile DMV stops across Vermont. Many services require an appointment, so check `dmv.vermont.gov` before showing up.

## Minimum age and eligibility

You must be **at least 15 years old** to apply for a Vermont Learner Permit. If you are under 18, a parent or legal guardian must sign your application, accepting financial responsibility for your driving. There is no maximum age for a permit, but if you are 18 or older you can skip several of the junior operator steps and apply directly for a regular operator license after holding the permit for at least 30 days.

## Documents you need

Bring original documents (not photocopies):

- **Proof of identity and date of birth** — certified birth certificate, U.S. passport, or permanent resident card.
- **Proof of Social Security number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing your SSN.
- **Two proofs of Vermont residency** — examples include a utility bill, school transcript, lease, or a parent''s documents combined with a notarized affidavit if you live with them.
- **Parental consent form** if you are under 18, signed in front of DMV staff or notarized in advance.
- **REAL ID documents** if you want a REAL ID-compliant permit (look for the star). REAL ID will be required for domestic flights and federal buildings.

## Fees and forms

You will complete application form **VL-021** (Application for License/Permit). Fees are modest compared to many states; check the DMV site for the current amount. Bring a check, cash, or card — not all branches accept every payment method.

## The knowledge test

The written knowledge test is based on the **Vermont Driver''s Manual**, which is free to download from the DMV website. The exam covers:

- Vermont traffic laws and signs
- Right-of-way rules
- Speed limits and following distances
- Alcohol and drug laws, including the under-21 zero-tolerance rule
- Sharing the road with bicyclists, pedestrians, motorcycles, farm equipment, and moose
- Winter driving basics

You must score at least **80%** to pass. The test is offered in English and several other languages, and accommodations are available for documented disabilities. If you fail, you can retake it after a short waiting period — usually the next business day.

## The vision test

A basic vision screening is administered at the DMV. You need at least **20/40 vision in at least one eye**, with or without corrective lenses. If you need glasses or contacts to meet the standard, your permit will carry a corrective-lens restriction.

## After you pass

Once you pass the knowledge and vision tests, pay the fee, and have your photo taken, you receive your Learner Permit. From that moment you may drive **only** when:

- A licensed driver who is at least **25 years old** (or a licensed parent, guardian, or driver education instructor) is seated next to you in the front seat.
- All passengers are wearing seat belts.
- You are not using any handheld electronic device — not even hands-free if you are under 18.

## The 12-month holding period

You must hold the Learner Permit for **at least 12 months** before you can take the road test for a Junior Driver License. During the final 6 months, you must have no convictions for moving violations and no license suspensions. If you get a ticket, the clock can reset.

Use this year deliberately: log your 40 hours of supervised practice (including night driving), get comfortable on Vermont''s dirt roads and mountain grades, and practice in winter conditions before your road test.', 35, 0
);
