INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_wa_wa-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_wa_overlay', 'wa-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Washington GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '## Living with Your Washington Intermediate License

Once you turn 16 and meet all the requirements, the Department of Licensing issues you an **Intermediate Driver License (IDL)**. This is not a full unrestricted license — for the first year (or until you turn 18, whichever comes first), Washington''s Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL) law places real, enforceable limits on when you drive, who is in the car, and what you can hold in your hand.

### The passenger restriction

Washington''s passenger rule is among the strictest in the country:

- **First 6 months of intermediate license**: You may not transport **any passengers under age 20** unless they are members of your immediate family (parents, siblings, stepsiblings, your own children).
- **Months 7 through 12**: You may transport **no more than 3 passengers under age 20**, with the same immediate-family exception.

This catches many new drivers by surprise — your best friend riding shotgun to school is a violation. Plan ahead with carpools that use a 19+ driver, the school bus, or transit. A first violation is a traffic infraction; subsequent violations can extend your restrictions or trigger a license suspension.

### The nighttime restriction

For the **first 12 months** of your intermediate license you may not drive between **1:00 a.m. and 5:00 a.m.** unless:

- You are accompanied by a licensed driver age 25 or older, **or**
- You are driving to or from work (and can show proof, like a pay stub or employer note), **or**
- You are driving for a school-authorized activity, **or**
- You are driving for a farm-related agricultural activity.

If you regularly close at a restaurant or work an early-morning shift, keep written proof in the vehicle. "I was driving home from a friend''s house" is not a recognized exception.

### The wireless device rule for teens

Washington bans **all wireless device use** — including hands-free Bluetooth, voice commands to send a text, and headphones — for drivers under 18 with an intermediate license. The only allowed use is to report an emergency. This is stricter than the rule for adult drivers, who may use hands-free devices.

In addition, the statewide **E-DUI law** prohibits any driver from holding a personal electronic device — phone, tablet, gaming device — while driving, even when stopped at a red light. A first E-DUI ticket is reportable to insurance.

### Seat belts and DUI

- Every occupant must wear a seat belt; the driver is responsible for passengers under 16.
- Washington has a **zero-tolerance** DUI standard for drivers under 21. Any measurable alcohol (.02 BAC or higher) triggers license suspension. The standard adult limit (.08) still applies to criminal DUI charges.

### How violations escalate

Washington uses a tiered enforcement model for intermediate drivers:

- **First moving violation**: a notice is sent to you and your parents.
- **Second moving violation OR an at-fault collision**: 6-month restriction extension or suspension until age 18, plus possible nighttime/passenger restriction enforcement.
- **Third violation**: license suspension until age 18.

The restrictions end automatically when you turn 18 or have held the intermediate license for 12 months with a clean record, whichever happens first. The license card itself doesn''t change — the restrictions just no longer apply to you.', 30, 1
);
