INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_wa_washington-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'module_wa_overlay', 'washington-specific-rules-and-quirks', 'Washington-Specific Rules and Quirks', '## Washington-Specific Rules Every New Driver Should Know

Washington shares most of its traffic laws with the rest of the United States, but there are several rules, road designs, and weather conditions that catch new drivers off guard. Knowing them now will keep you safer and reduce your odds of an expensive ticket.

### The Move Over Law (and what counts)

Washington''s Move Over law requires you to slow down and, if safely possible, change lanes away from a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or roadside assistance vehicle with flashing lights. As of recent updates, the law also covers **any vehicle with hazard lights flashing on the shoulder** — including a regular passenger car with a flat tire. On a two-lane road where you cannot change lanes, you must slow to a safe speed below the posted limit.

### Roundabouts are everywhere

Washington has aggressively replaced four-way intersections with **modern roundabouts**, especially in suburban areas around Seattle, Spokane, Vancouver, and Bellingham. Rules to remember:

- **Yield to traffic already in the circle** — do not yield to vehicles approaching from your right.
- Enter only when there is a safe gap.
- Use your right turn signal only when you are about to exit.
- Large trucks may straddle both lanes — give them space and never pass on the right inside a roundabout.

### The HOV/HOT lane system

In the Puget Sound and I-405 corridor, Washington uses both **HOV lanes** (left-most lane, requires 2 or 3 occupants depending on the section) and **HOT lanes** (express toll lanes where solo drivers can pay to enter). Crossing the double-white line into or out of an HOV/HOT lane is illegal and ticketed by camera. Always enter and exit only at the marked dashed-line zones.

### Studded tires and chains

Washington allows **studded snow tires only between November 1 and March 31**. Using them outside that window is a fineable offense. In mountain passes like Snoqualmie, Stevens, White, and Blewett, WSDOT can require **traction tires or chains** during winter storms — watch the variable message signs and check WSDOT''s pass report before you travel.

### Ferries are part of the road system

Washington State Ferries are legally an extension of the state highway system. When loading, follow crew directions, set your parking brake, turn off the engine, and do not return to your vehicle until told. The same traffic laws (seat belts, no phone in hand) apply on the car deck while you are moving.

### Rain, not snow, is the real hazard

Most of western Washington''s serious crashes happen in the **first 15 minutes of rain**, when oil that has built up during dry days mixes with water and creates a slick surface. Increase following distance to at least 4 seconds, turn on headlights (Washington law requires headlights any time wipers are in continuous use), and avoid cruise control on wet pavement.

### Pedestrian right-of-way

Every intersection in Washington is legally a **crosswalk**, marked or unmarked, unless signage says otherwise. You must stop — not just yield — for a pedestrian in your half of the roadway or approaching it on a two-lane road. Fines start at over $100 and climb with school zones.

### School bus stop-arm rule

On a two-lane road, traffic in **both directions** must stop when a school bus extends its stop arm. On a divided highway with a physical barrier or median, only traffic on the bus''s side must stop. "Divided" means a physical barrier; a center turn lane does not count.

### Bicycles and the Idaho Stop

Washington adopted a version of the **"Idaho Stop"** law: bicyclists may legally treat stop signs as yield signs. Expect cyclists to roll through quiet stop-sign intersections legally — give them room and never pass a cyclist with less than 3 feet of clearance.', 30, 2
);
