INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_wi_wisconsin-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'module_wi_overlay', 'wisconsin-gdl-restrictions-daily-life', 'Wisconsin GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '# Wisconsin GDL Restrictions in Daily Life

Wisconsin''s **Graduated Driver Licensing (GDL)** program is built around a simple idea: new drivers get more independence in stages as they prove they can handle the road safely. Once you move from the instruction permit to the **probationary license**, several restrictions follow you for at least the first 9 months — or until you turn 18, whichever comes first. Understanding how those rules play out in real life keeps you legal and keeps your license.

## The nighttime driving window

Probationary drivers under 18 are **not allowed to drive between midnight and 5:00 a.m.** This rule is enforced strictly, and a violation can extend your probation period or trigger license suspension.

There are three narrow exceptions:

1. **Driving to or from work** — you should keep a recent pay stub or a note from your employer in the glove box.
2. **Driving to or from a school-sponsored activity** — for example, returning home from a late basketball game or a band competition.
3. **Driving to or from a religious event** — late services or youth-group meetings count.

In all three cases, an officer can still pull you over and ask for proof. "I was just heading home from a friend''s house" is **not** a valid exception, even if the friend lives next door. If you are accompanied by a **qualified adult** (parent, guardian, spouse 19+, or a licensed driver 21+ with 2+ years of experience) in the front seat, the curfew does not apply.

## The passenger limit

During the first **9 months** of holding the probationary license, you may only carry **one passenger** who is not an immediate family member, unless a qualified adult is seated in the front passenger seat.

In day-to-day terms:

- Driving your younger brother and sister to school? **Allowed** — they are immediate family.
- Picking up three teammates for practice? **Not allowed.**
- Giving a single friend a ride home? **Allowed.**
- Driving two friends with your mom in the front seat? **Allowed** — the qualified adult overrides the limit.

This rule exists because crash data consistently shows that the **fatality risk for a teen driver more than doubles** with two or more teen passengers in the car.

## The cell phone ban

Wisconsin law goes beyond the general texting-while-driving ban for permit and probationary drivers: you may **not use a cell phone in any manner** — handheld, hands-free, Bluetooth, or speakerphone — while operating the vehicle. The **only** exception is reporting an emergency (a crash, a medical situation, an impaired driver). Even using your phone as a GPS counts as a violation if it is in your hand or you are interacting with it.

Practical habits to adopt:

- Mount your phone before you start the engine and program your route in advance.
- Set your device to "Do Not Disturb While Driving" mode.
- Pull into a parking lot — not the shoulder — to take an unavoidable call.

## Seat belts and zero tolerance for alcohol

Wisconsin enforces a **primary seat belt law** — an officer can pull you over solely for an unbelted driver or passenger. Probationary drivers are also subject to **Wisconsin''s Not-a-Drop law**: any detectable alcohol in the system of a driver under 21 results in license suspension and fines, regardless of whether you appear impaired.

## Convictions and your timeline

Any conviction during the probationary period — speeding, a curfew violation, riding with too many passengers — **restarts the conviction-free clock** you need to complete the GDL phase. Two convictions can trigger suspension; three results in revocation. The 9-month restriction window can stretch into a year or more if violations stack up. Treat the first 9 months as the most important driving habits you will ever build: they shape both your record and your insurance rate for years.', 25, 1
);
