INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_wv_how-to-get-a-wv-permit', 'module_wv_overlay', 'how-to-get-a-wv-permit', 'How to Get Your West Virginia Level 1 Instruction Permit', '# How to Get Your West Virginia Level 1 Instruction Permit

West Virginia uses a three-step Graduated Driver License (GDL) program administered by the West Virginia Division of Motor Vehicles (WV DMV). The very first step is the **Level 1 Instruction Permit**, which lets you practice driving with a licensed adult before you ever drive alone. This lesson walks you through exactly what you need, what to expect at the DMV office, and how to prepare so you pass on the first try.

## Step 1: Confirm You Are Eligible

To apply for a Level 1 Instruction Permit in West Virginia, you must be **at least 15 years old**. There is no upper age limit, but applicants under 18 have additional requirements. You also must:

- Be a resident of West Virginia.
- Provide proof you are enrolled in school, have graduated, or have earned a GED. WV will not issue a permit to a school-age minor who is not making satisfactory academic progress.
- Have written consent from a parent or legal guardian if you are under 18. The parent or guardian must sign the application in front of the DMV clerk or have it notarized.

## Step 2: Gather Your Documents

West Virginia follows federal REAL ID rules. Bring originals or certified copies — photocopies are not accepted. You will need:

1. **Proof of identity** — certified U.S. birth certificate, valid U.S. passport, or an immigration document.
2. **Proof of Social Security Number** — Social Security card, W-2, or pay stub showing the full SSN.
3. **Two proofs of West Virginia residency** — utility bill, bank statement, school record, or similar document dated within the last 60 days and showing your WV address. If you live with a parent, a parental affidavit plus their proofs work.
4. **Proof of school enrollment / progress** (if under 18) — the WV DMV-DS-1 form signed by your school.
5. **Parental consent** — the parent/guardian section of the application, signed in person or notarized.

## Step 3: Pay the Fee and Take the Tests

Go to any WV DMV regional office. Walk-ins are accepted but appointments are faster — you can book one at dmv.wv.gov. At the counter you will:

- Pay the instruction permit fee (currently around \$7.50, plus a small lamination fee). Bring a card or cash; check the DMV website for current amounts.
- Pass a **vision screening** (20/40 in at least one eye, with or without corrective lenses).
- Pass the **knowledge test** — 25 multiple-choice questions drawn from the WV Driver''s Licensing Handbook. You must get at least 19 correct (76%). Questions cover road signs, traffic laws, safe driving practices, and the GDL restrictions themselves.
- Have your photo taken.

If you fail the knowledge test, WV requires you to wait until the next business day to retake it. Study the handbook — it is free at dmv.wv.gov.

## Step 4: Start the 180-Day Holding Period

Once issued, you must hold the Level 1 permit for **at least 180 days (six months)** before you can move up to a Level 2 Intermediate License. During this period:

- You may only drive when accompanied by a licensed driver age 21 or older who is seated next to you.
- All occupants must wear seat belts.
- You may not use any cell phone or wireless device while driving, even hands-free.
- You must log **50 hours of supervised driving**, including **at least 10 hours at night**. Keep the WV DMV practice log — you will turn it in when you apply for Level 2.

Any moving violation, alcohol offense, or seat belt violation during Level 1 can extend the holding period or delay your move to Level 2.

## Step 5: Plan Ahead for Level 2

Mark your calendar for 180 days out. As that date approaches, make sure your practice log is complete, signed by a parent or guardian, and that you have scheduled your road skills test. We will cover the Level 2 transition in the next lesson.

**Bottom line:** show up to the WV DMV with the right documents, study the handbook, and treat the 180-day permit phase as real practice — not a waiting period. Every hour behind the wheel now is an hour that will make your road test, and your first solo drive, dramatically safer.', 35, 0
);
