INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_wy_how-to-get-a-wyoming-learner-permit_2', 'quiz_wy_how-to-get-a-wyoming-learner-permit', 'Who must accompany a Wyoming learner permit holder while driving?', '["Any licensed driver age 16 or older","A licensed driver age 18 or older in the front passenger seat","A parent or guardian only","A driving instructor only"]', 1, 'A licensed driver age 18 or older must be seated in the front passenger seat at all times when a permit holder is driving.', 2
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_wy_how-to-get-a-wyoming-learner-permit_3', 'quiz_wy_how-to-get-a-wyoming-learner-permit', 'What is the minimum visual acuity (with or without correction) needed to pass the Wyoming vision screening?', '["20/20 in both eyes","20/30 in both eyes","20/40 in at least one eye","20/70 in at least one eye"]', 2, 'Wyoming requires at least 20/40 vision in one eye, with or without corrective lenses. If you need glasses or contacts to pass, a corrective-lens restriction is added to your permit.', 3
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO quiz_question (id, quizId, prompt, choices, correctIndex, explanation, ordinal) VALUES (
  'q_wy_how-to-get-a-wyoming-learner-permit_4', 'quiz_wy_how-to-get-a-wyoming-learner-permit', 'How long must a Wyoming learner permit be held before the holder can apply for an intermediate license?', '["3 months","6 months","10 months","12 months"]', 2, 'Wyoming requires a 10-month holding period on the learner permit, and the applicant must also be at least 16 years old to advance.', 4
);
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO lesson (id, moduleId, slug, title, body, estimatedSeatMinutes, ordinal) VALUES (
  'lesson_wy_wyoming-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'module_wy_overlay', 'wyoming-gdl-restrictions-in-daily-life', 'Wyoming GDL Restrictions in Daily Life', '## Living With the Wyoming Intermediate License

Once you turn 16 and have held your learner permit for at least 10 months, completed your 50 hours of supervised practice, and passed the road skills test, WYDOT issues an **intermediate license**. You are now allowed to drive alone — but with two important restrictions designed to reduce the leading causes of teen crashes: **late-night driving** and **peer passengers**.

These restrictions stay in effect until you turn **17 years old**, when you graduate to an unrestricted license automatically (you don''t have to retest or reapply — it just becomes effective on your birthday).

### The Nighttime Restriction

Between **11:00 PM and 5:00 AM**, an intermediate license holder may not drive alone. You may only drive during these hours if:

- A licensed driver age 18 or older is seated next to you in the front, **or**
- You are driving directly to or from **work**, with documentation (a pay stub or note from your employer), **or**
- You are driving to or from a **school-sanctioned event** (a game, a play, an academic competition), **or**
- You are traveling to or from a **religious activity**, **or**
- You are responding to a verified **emergency**

Key word: *directly*. "Directly" means the most reasonable route between two points — not the long way around with three stops along the way. If you get pulled over at 12:30 AM and tell the trooper you were at a friend''s house after your shift ended at 10:00 PM, the work exemption no longer applies.

Plan ahead. If your shift ends at 10:45 PM and home is 20 minutes away, you''re fine. If it ends at 11:30 PM, you''re fine *if you go straight home*. If you stop at the gas station, then a friend''s, then home — you have given up the exemption.

### The Passenger Restriction

For the first year of your intermediate license, you may carry **only one passenger under age 18 who is not a member of your immediate family**. "Immediate family" means siblings, step-siblings, and children of your parents or legal guardians who live in your household.

This is the rule teens forget most often. A common scenario: you have your license, three friends pile into your car after school to go get food, and you''re now in violation — even if everyone is buckled and you''re driving safely. A traffic stop for any reason (broken taillight, rolling stop, speeding) can result in a citation for the passenger violation on top of the original offense.

The restriction does not apply when an adult age 18 or older is also in the car supervising. So a carpool driven by a parent, with multiple teens, is fine.

### Why These Rules Exist

National crash data shows that the **first six to twelve months** of solo driving are by far the most dangerous period in any driver''s life. Crash risk goes up dramatically with each additional teen passenger and triples after midnight. Wyoming''s GDL rules are not arbitrary — they are calibrated to the situations that disproportionately kill teen drivers.

Violating a GDL restriction in Wyoming can result in fines, license suspension, an extended period in the intermediate stage, and increased insurance premiums. Some violations stay on your record and become visible to employers, the military, and out-of-state DMVs.

### Documentation You Should Always Carry

Until you turn 17, carry the following in your glove box:

- A current **pay stub or letter from your employer** if you ever drive home from work after 11:00 PM
- A copy of your **school activity schedule** if you have late practices or games
- Your **insurance card** and **vehicle registration**
- Your **intermediate license** (not just a photo of it on your phone)

If an officer stops you and you can immediately show that you fit a documented exception, the stop typically ends much faster.', 30, 1
);
